<DOCNO> APW19991002.0002 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-02 13:31:02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> international </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Milan Fashions Elegant, Colorful </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	MILAN, Italy (AP) -- The Versace collection that closed the  
``moda Milanese'' previews summed up the mood for the first summer 
of the new millennium -- ladylike, colorful and free. 
</P>
<P>
	Departing from the label's fame as a sex tank, Donatella Versace  
on Friday showed pretty, printed silk gowns with long sleeves and a 
discreet decollete, spiffy pantsuits with only moderately tight 
trousers and cropped jackets, and evening gowns in embroidered 
chiffon that showed more fabric than flesh. 
</P>
<P>
	``Basta (enough) with body baring,'' the designer said after the  
show, held in a former General Electric factory on Milan's 
outskirts. 
</P>
<P>
	To emphasize her new covered look, Donatella wrapped the body in  
scarves from the neck to the buttocks. The theme was especially 
evident in the evening wear, where gowns were little more than 
scarves creatively tied together. 
</P>
<P>
	Bright shades, from leaf-green to orange-red, highlighted the  
show -- confirming this season's trend of abandoning black and 
rediscovering color. 
</P>
<P>
	There also was the sense of freedom of choice, which has marked  
this round of preview showings, in the Versace collection, from the 
ladylike dresses to the sequined hot pants. 
</P>
<P>
	Throughout the week designers have mixed, matched and separated.  
</P>
<P>
	Unlikely combinations include a man-tailored shirt worn with a  
glitzy sequined skirt (Dolce &AMP; Gabbana), a skirt in rainbow pastels 
matched with a colorful geometric print top (Armani) and a tiny 
jacket over extra-wide pants (Gucci). 
</P>
<P>
	``Fashion should be pick and chose,'' said Stefano Gabbana, who  
with his partner, Domenico Dolce, staged their show in the setting 
of an outdoor market. 
</P>
<P>
	Choices came in shapes too. Trousers went from extra-tight to  
comfortably loose, with the favorite style cropped anywhere between 
ankle and knee. Skirt hemlines played mainly around the knee, but 
others crept up the thigh, culminating in Dolce &AMP; Gabbana's 
six-inch strip. 
</P>
<P>
	Tank tops beat a summer retreat, replaced by bare-backed apron  
tops in anything from traditional silk to high-tech plasticized 
fabrics. But T-shirts, blouses, bra tops and closely fitted 
sweaters are also fine. 
</P>
<P>
	In a dubious season switch, stockings, absent from the winter  
runway, make a summer comeback in fishnet, leopard print or bright 
pink. 
</P>
<P>
	Adding to the mixed fashion bag, folklore themes abound. Indian,  
peasant, punk and beachcomber all live happily together on the 
runway, united by the strand after strand of beading. 
</P>
<P>
	It's a good season for the silk manufacturers, with designers  
favoring silk jersey, silk prints and chiffon, along with heavy 
doses of gilded and silver silk fabric. 
</P>
<P>
	Shoes are mainly high-heeled, either pumps, slingbacks or  
one-strap sandals. The latest news in the footwear department is 
the suspended heel built on a metal brace introduced by Karl 
Lagerfeld for Fendi. 
</P>
<P>
	Makeup tends toward a natural look, as do hairstyles that are  
either long and loose or demurely pinned up. Tom Ford for Gucci 
created a new style intended to be neo-punk, which actually 
resembles an old scarecrow. 
</P>
<P>
	After a few seasons of quiet shows, there was a big comeback of  
celebrity fashion-watchers on the front rows, with rock stars 
scoring the most points. 
</P>
<P>
	The British group All Saints showed up at Versace, Whitney  
Houston was at Dolce &AMP; Gabbana with husband Bobby Brown, and teen 
heartthrob Ricky Martin flew in from Los Angeles for Armani. 
</P>
<P>
	Off the runway, the big talk was about buying and selling -- not  
only clothes, but companies. 
</P>
<P>
	The hottest item at present is Fendi, whose one-of-a-kind  
``baguette'' bag has become one of the most sought-after 
accessories. The company owned by the five Fendi sisters, with Karl 
Lagerfeld as their designer, is also famous for its extravagant 
furs. 
</P>
<P>
	Both Prada with the French conglomerate LVMH and Gucci have set  
their eyes on Fendi, which would reportedly cost over $800 million. 
</P>
<P>
	The sisters have yet to agree on whether to sell, or to whom.  
</P>
<P>
	Also up for grabs is the Church and Co., the elite British shoe  
manufacturer. 
</P>
<P>
	Both Prada, which last month bought upscale Jil Sander, the  
German company known for its exquisitely tailored minimalist style, 
and shoemaker Diego della Valle are eyeing Church. 
</P>
<P>
	``Fashion is a business and it's always on the move,'' said  
Beppe Modenese, honorary president of Italy's fashion chamber and 
the man credited with putting the ``moda Milanese'' on the 
international fashion map. 


  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
