<DOCNO> APW19991002.0003 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-02 03:00:09 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Woman Pays High Price for Prize </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	MILWAUKEE (AP) -- The prize was a split-level ranch house  
overlooking a small lake. The price was a $50 raffle ticket. 
</P>
<P>
	Or so Christine Curl thought.  
</P>
<P>
	Curl won the $240,000 home in the Milwaukee suburb of Oak Creek  
in a raffle held for the St. Ann Center for Intergenerational Care, 
an adult day care program. 
</P>
<P>
	However, the $240,000 prize put Curl into an unfamiliar  
category. Curl, who has worked for 23 years at a post office, was 
suddenly part of the nation's wealthy elite, in the view of the 
Internal Revenue Service. 
</P>
<P>
	The wealth meant she had to pay 39.6 percent of her earnings in  
federal income taxes. Combined with state and property taxes, she 
wound up paying $108,000 for her prize. 
</P>
<P>
	The same week she won the house she put it up for sale and  
accepted a couple's offer of $220,000. 
</P>
<P>
	The house has still given Curl and her family some money. Cash  
from the house sale will go toward her daughter's wedding this 
weekend. And she still has enough money for a sizable down payment 
somewhere else. 
</P>
<P>
	But despite the tax hassles, Curl wouldn't mind another free  
house. St. Ann is holding another house raffle Oct. 9, for a 
four-bedroom colonial. This time, she plans to buy three tickets. 
</P>
<P>
	``You never know,'' she said. ``My chances are pretty good.''  
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
