<DOCNO> APW19991002.0005 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-02 14:40:02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> international </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE>  Myanmar Embassy Hostages Released </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	BANGKOK, Thailand (AP) -- Thailand engineered a peaceful end  
Saturday to the armed takeover of the Myanmar Embassy by five 
pro-democracy activists, flying the rebels by helicopter to the 
Thai-Myanmar border, where they were allowed to go free. 
</P>
<P>
	After holing up in the embassy for 26 hours, the raiders  
released all 38 hostages, Thai Interior Minister Sanan 
Kachornprasart said at a news conference. Another 51 Myanmar 
citizens -- mostly family of diplomatic personnel -- who had hidden 
inside the walled embassy compound were also allowed to walk out. 
</P>
<P>
	``We don't consider them to be terrorists,'' said Sanan, who was  
one of the government's negotiators with the rebels. ``They are 
student activists struggling for democracy. We have done what we 
have promised them.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Calling themselves the Vigorous Burmese Student Warriors, the  
hostage-takers had demanded the release of all political prisoners 
in Myanmar, a meaningful dialogue between pro-democracy leader Aung 
San Suu Kyi and the military government, and the convening of an 
elected parliament. 
</P>
<P>
	Democracy activists say the rebels' takeover of the embassy  
sprang from deep frustration that their cause is receiving neither 
international attention nor making headway in their homeland. 
</P>
<P>
	Dissident groups called the incident a ``wake up call'' and  
warned of more violence ahead if the government of Myanmar doesn't 
change its harsh, autocratic rule. 
</P>
<P>
	``In the past 11 years the democracy movement has consistently  
stood for a non-violent solution, but this hasn't really delivered 
significant progress,'' said activist Debbie Stothard of the 
Alternative ASEAN Network on Burma. 
</P>
<P>
	``The students appear to have acted out of outrage at the  
regime's increasing repression and frustration with the failure of 
the international community to respond to the plight of Burma's 
people,'' the Washington-based Free Burma Coalition said of the 
take-over in a statement. 
</P>
<P>
	Once among the country's best and brightest, thdissidents live  
in malaria-ridden jungle camps and are sometimes attacked by 
Myanmar troops. While dissidents continue to predict victory over 
the military, there are few signs the generals who have ruled 
Myanmar for the past 37 years are loosening their grip on power. 
</P>
<P>
	The exact whereabouts of the five student militants were  
unclear, but the leader of a border-based Myanmar ethnic rebel 
group said he would grant them sanctuary. 
</P>
<P>
	``I will accept them in even though they are not our group's  
members because they have the same passion that we do to oppose the 
Burmese junta government,'' Bo Mya of the Karen National Union told 
reporters at his stronghold opposite Thailand's Tak province. 
</P>
<P>
	The Karen are the last sizable ethnic minority group fighting  
the central government of Myanmar, also called Burma. 
</P>
<P>
	The move will gall Myanmar's government, which has long  
described the Karen guerrillas as terrorists. Public comments by 
senior Thai officials describing the hostage-takers as fighters for 
democracy were also likely to irritate Yangon's generals. 
</P>
<P>
	``No matter under what pretext or disguise it might have been  
staged, the peace-loving people of the world community will not 
tolerate the criminal and the terrorist activities they have 
committed,'' the Myanmar government said in an official news 
release. 
</P>
<P>
	Sanan warned legal action would be taken against the rebels if  
they returned, but also said that Thailand would continue to 
tolerate freedom of expression for Myanmar dissident exiles as long 
as it was within the law. 
</P>
<P>
	One of two senior Thai officials who volunteered to fly with the  
five young rebels as surrogates for the hostages also expressed 
sympathy for their cause. Deputy Foreign Minister Sukhumbhand 
Paribatra said in an interview with Thailand's ITV television 
network that the militants were youths who were fighting for 
democracy. 
</P>
<P>
	Sukhumbhand and a senior refugee official, Chaiyapruek  
Sawaengcharoen, returned to Bangkok after leaving the five students 
at a drop-off point about a mile from the Myanmar border. 
</P>
<P>
	``They thanked me for saving their lives,'' said Sukhumbhand.  
``I thanked them back and we shook hands before they got off the 
helicopter.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19991002.0006 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-02 14:40:02 </DATE_TIME>
