<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-02 16:20:15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> AP Top News at 7 p.m. EDT  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 *Saturday, Oct. 2, 1999    	

</P>
<P>
	Riot Police Stop Belgrade March  
</P>
<P>
	BELGRADE, Yugoslavia (AP) -- About 15,000 pro-democracy  
protesters marched toward Belgrade's main hospital Saturday -- only 
to be stopped by heavily armed riot police. The march was to 
demonstrate support for those hurt by police earlier in the week 
when hundreds of riot police charged at protesters marching toward 
President Slobodan Milosevic's villa three nights ago, injuring at 
least 60 people. 

</P>
<P>
	Eight Killed On Eve of India Election  
</P>
<P>
	NEW DELHI, India (AP) -- Suspected guerrillas pushing villagers  
to boycott India's elections set off a land mine Saturday, killing 
five people and wounding three others in Assam state on the eve of 
the last round of India's five-phase ballot, police said. Police 
also shot and killed two rebels in Assam and one local politician, 
bringing the day's death toll to eight in election-related 
violence. 

</P>
<P>
	White House Hurries To Save Test Ban  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- WASHINGTON (AP) -- The White House launched an  
effort today to save a global nuclear test ban treaty, and accused 
Senate Republicans of trying to kill it with an unexpectedly quick 
vote. Trying to build support, President Clinton will speak about 
the treaty Tuesday when he signs a major defense bill at the 
Pentagon. Senate GOP leaders abruptly decided Thursday to hold a 
vote on the treaty Oct. 12. 

</P>
<P>
	Reform Party Aims to Reunite  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Top Reform Party officials worked today to  
coax a splinter group of their own to return. But organizers of the 
split said they first needed guarantees that Republican 
presidential candidate Pat Buchanan would not become the party's 
nominee. The efforts to reunify came as the party dealt with 
another brouhaha involving comments made by Minnesota Gov. Jesse 
Ventura, the Reform Party's top elected official, in an interview 
with Playboy magazine. 

</P>
<P>
	Russia Takes Chechen Village  
</P>
<P>
	GROZNY, Russia (AP) -- Russian troops took control of a village  
in Chechnya and clashed with rebels in several parts of the 
breakaway republic today. Chechnya's vice president vowed his 
people would fight off the Russians -- but also called for 
negotiations. Vakha Arsanov suggested Georgian President Eduard 
Shevardnadze could organize talks between Russian and Chechen 
authorities. Russia began air raids on Chechnya last month after 
Muslim militants based in the territory invaded neighboring 
Dagestan, seeking to create an Islamic state. 

</P>
<P>
	Gore Campaign Defends Manager  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- The Al Gore 2000 presidential campaign issued  
a statement defending campaign manager Tony Coelho, who is facing 
scrutiny for financial irregularities during a previous job. ``Tony 
Coelho does a great job as general chair of Gore 2000,'' the 
statement said. Stanley Brand, Coelho's personal lawyer, said his 
client did not violate any laws in a job that did not pay him a 
salary. State Department investigators say Coelho made the 
government liable for a $300,000 personal loan while directing the 
U.S. pavilion at the 1998 world's fair in Portugal. 

</P>
<P>
	Ginsberg's Return To Court Unknown  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- When the Supreme Court's marshal tells  
courtroom spectators Monday that ``the court is now sitting,'' 
Justice Ruth Bader Ginsburg may be absent. Ginsburg returned home 
Sept. 27 after an 11-day hospital stay and surgery for colon 
cancer. The prognosis from her doctor is good, but it is not known 
how long the 66-year-old justice will be homebound. She already has 
participated in court business since her surgery, but cannot take 
part in oral arguments unless in the courtroom. 

</P>
<P>
	Astros Shut Out Dodgers 3-0  
</P>
<P>
	HOUSTON (AP) -- Jose Lima and Craig Biggio gave the Houston  
Astros one more chance to win the NL Central title in the final 
regular-season game in the Astrodome. Lima joined teammate Mike 
Hampton as the league's only 21-game winners and Biggio homered in 
the sixth inning to break a scoreless tie today, giving the Astros 
a 3-0 win over Los Angeles and a one-game lead in the division over 
Cincinnati, which lost to Milwaukee today 10-6. 

</P>
<P>
	No. 22 Syracuse Beats Tulane 47-17  
</P>
<P>
	SYRACUSE, N.Y. (AP) -- Two years ago, it took a miracle finish  
for Syracuse to beat Tulane. Today, no miracles were needed. Madei 
Williams hit Pat Woodcock with a 22-yard touchdown pass and Nate 
Trout kicked a 37-yard field goal in the final minute of the first 
half to break open a tight game. The defense then held the 
high-powered Green Wave scoreless in the second half as No. 22 
Syracuse rolled to a 47-17 victory. 

</P>
<P>
	AP NewsBrief by KELLY GRUEL  
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
