<CATEGORY> entertainment </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Schwarzenegger Remaining Actor </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	SAN JOSE, Calif. (AP) -- Actor Arnold Schwarzenegger is  
terminating rumors that he plans to run for governor of California. 
</P>
<P>
	``I have thought about it many times, but I'm in show  
business,'' Schwarzenegger said Friday. ``I am in the middle of my 
career. Why would I go away from that and jump into something 
else?'' 
</P>
<P>
	Schwarzenegger had hinted in the November issue of Talk magazine  
that he might one day be a candidate for governor. But on Friday, 
he said his remarks about running for public office in 2002 had 
been taken too seriously. 
</P>
<P>
	He was visiting San Jose as the national chairman of the  
Inner-City Games, which aims to keep poor children out of trouble 
by encouraging them to play sports. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19991002.0009 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-02 11:00:17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Missile Defense System Test Slated </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	VANDENBERG AIR FORCE BASE, Calif. (AP) -- A prototype national  
missile defense system faced a critical test Saturday amid 
criticism that a successful demonstration of the technology would 
only heighten the nuclear threat. 
</P>
<P>
	An unarmed Minuteman missile was set for launch about 7:30 p.m.  
PDT on a flight over the Pacific to the Marshall Islands, where a 
``kill vehicle'' missile was to be launched to try to attempt an 
interception. 
</P>
<P>
	If successful, the interceptor would collide with the  
intercontinental ballistic missile at a combined speed of 16,000 
mph about 140 miles above the ocean. 
</P>
<P>
	The Minuteman was configured with a dummy warhead and a decoy  
balloon. 
</P>
<P>
	The defender was the Raytheon-built Exoatmospheric Kill Vehicle,  
a 55-inch-long, 120-pound device carried aloft on a booster rocket. 
</P>
<P>
	The system is designed to destroy missiles launched by rogue  
states or terrorists, not a multimissile barrage from a major 
nuclear power. 
</P>
<P>
	Some critics have faulted the test plan as unrealistic and too  
limited to make a sound decision, while peace activists who 
demonstrated outside the base a week ago denounced the testing as 
preparation for war. They planned a demonstration Saturday. 
</P>
<P>
	Pentagon officials played down expectations, saying that even a  
miss would be considered a success -- as long as the reason was 
known. 
</P>
<P>
	The test, however, is the first of three before a readiness  
review scheduled by the Pentagon for next June. To proceed with 
broader testing, at least two of the tests must result in an 
interception. A White House decision on initial deployment is 
expected after the June review. 
</P>
<P>
	The test comes as nations such as North Korea, Iran and Syria  
are, according to the CIA, developing long-range missiles that 
could hit the United States. 
</P>
<P>
	Unarmed U.S. ICBMs are routinely tested in launches from  
Vandenberg to a Marshall Islands target range about 4,200 miles 
across the Pacific. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19991002.0010 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-02 12:00:16 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
