<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Ex-Student Radical Freed From Jail </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	FRAMINGHAM, Mass. (AP) -- Katherine Ann Power, the student  
radical who spent 23 years underground after taking part in an 
armed robbery that ended with the death of a police officer, was 
released from prison today. 
</P>
<P>
	Power, 49, said nothing to reporters as she left MCI-Framingham,  
where she has spent the last six years. 
</P>
<P>
	In a statement issued by her attorney, James M. Doyle, Power  
said she ``will always carry my human responsibility for the sorrow 
my actions have caused.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Power, then a 21-year-old student at Brandeis University, and  
four others robbed a Boston bank to fund radical efforts against 
the Vietnam war. She was waiting in the getaway car when another 
member of the group, William ``Lefty'' Gilday, shot Schroeder in 
the back. Only Power got away. 
</P>
<P>
	For 23 years, she lived under the alias Alice Metzinger,  
eventually settling near Corvallis, Ore. She married a bookkeeper, 
Ronley Duncan, worked as a chef, and had a son, now 21. 
</P>
<P>
	Power returned to Massachusetts in 1993, pleaded guilty to  
manslaughter and was sentenced to eight to 12 years. 
</P>
<P>
	She was released early with credit for good behavior and time  
served. 
</P>
<P>
	Power has not said where she will go next. Duncan told the  
Boston Herald he and Power separated over a year ago. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
