<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Ginsberg's Return To Court Unknown </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- When the Supreme Court's marshal tells  
courtroom spectators Monday that ``the court is now sitting,'' 
Justice Ruth Bader Ginsburg may be absent. 
</P>
<P>
	Ginsburg returned home Sept. 27 after an 11-day hospital stay  
and surgery for colon cancer. The prognosis from her doctor is 
good, but it is not known how long the 66-year-old justice will be 
homebound. 
</P>
<P>
	She already has participated in court business since her  
surgery, but cannot take part in oral arguments unless in the 
courtroom. For cases in which she misses the arguments, Ginsburg 
can listen to audio tapes and read transcripts if she chooses to 
participate in deciding them. 
</P>
<P>
	If she opts out of them, her eight colleagues could reach a  
decision without her or order the case reargued. A 4-4 split of the 
justices automatically upholds a lower court's ruling but sets no 
legal precedent. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
