<HEADLINE> AP Top News at 4 p.m. EDT  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 *Saturday, Oct. 2, 1999    	

</P>
<P>
	Gore Campaign Manager Scrutinized  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- State Department investigators say they have  
uncovered some possible financial irregularities committed by Vice 
President Al Gore's campaign manager in a previous job. 
Investigators say Tony Coelho misused airline tickets, gave his 
niece a federal job and received a $300,000 personal loan that may 
be repaid by the government -- all while he directed the U.S. 
pavilion at a 1998 exposition in Portugal. The report was released 
by the Center for Public Integrity, a nonprofit organization. The 
center said Coelho's actions may have violated federal laws. 

</P>
<P>
	Gunmakers Hold Talks With Cities  
</P>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- For the first time since they have been sued  
over gun-related violence, gun manufacturers started talking with 
various cities on how to improve safety and make weapons tougher to 
get. The negotiations, held Monday in Washington, were an initial 
effort to settle the suits brought by cities across the country, 
which seek millions of dollars in damages to recoup costs related 
to gun violence. Unidentified gun industry executives who attended 
said they would consider a list of the cities' demands, including 
mandatory safety devices and a crackdown on corrupt gun retailers, 
The New York Times reported today. 

</P>
<P>
	Clinton To Preach Tolerance  
</P>
<P>
	PALO ALTO, Calif. (AP) -- Citing recent shootings in California  
and the Midwest, President Clinton says it is time Americans deal 
with ``the fear of the other'' that motivates such acts of hatred. 
The president was taking his message of tolerance before gay and 
lesbian supporters tonight at a Los Angeles dinner expected to 
raise $850,000 for Democratic candidates. Serving as host for 
Saturday's dinner was ANGLE -- Action Now for Gay and Lesbian 
Equality -- and organizers said it was one of the largest events of 
its kind outside Washington. 

</P>
<P>
	Russia Takes Control of Chechen Village  
</P>
<P>
	GROZNY, Russia (AP) -- Russian troops took control of a village  
in Chechnya and clashed with rebels in several parts of the 
breakaway republic today. Chechnya's vice president vowed his 
people would fight off the Russians -- but also called for 
negotiations. Vakha Arsanov suggested Georgian President Eduard 
Shevardnadze could organize talks between Russian and Chechen 
authorities. Russia began air raids on Chechnya last month after 
Muslim militants based in the territory invaded neighboring 
Dagestan, seeking to create an Islamic state. 

</P>
<P>
	GOP Sets Budget Priorities  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Republicans stressed their commitment today to  
protecting Social Security, opposing any tax increase and giving 
schools more money with fewer strings. Sen. Slade Gorton said the 
GOP will stick to those priorities and ensure that government keeps 
running during budget battles with the White House. ``A government 
shutdown is not necessary,'' Gorton, R-Wash., said in the party's 
weekly radio address. 

</P>
<P>
	Indonesia Election Moved Up  
</P>
<P>
	JAKARTA, Indonesia (AP) -- Indonesia will choose a new president  
on Oct. 20, three weeks earlier than scheduled, the country's major 
political leaders decided today. The date was moved up amid 
impatience with President B.J. Habibie's handling of East Timor and 
a banking scandal that has implicated top officials. The 700-member 
People's Consultative Assembly will select the next president. A 
debate on East Timor is expected to include a vote to endorse the 
results of the Aug. 30 referendum in which the people of the 
half-island territory overwhelmingly voted to become independent. 

</P>
<P>
	Controversial NYC Art Exhibit Opens  
</P>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- ``Sensation,'' the controversial art exhibit  
that set New York on its ear even before it arrived, opened today 
at the Brooklyn Museum of Art. About three dozen protesters showed 
up. They included protesters from the conservative Catholic League 
and from animal rights groups. One demonstrator protesting Mayor 
Rudolph Giuliani's efforts to stop the show was arrested. 

</P>
<P>
	Rockets Trade Pippen to Portland  
</P>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Scottie Pippen today was traded from the Houston  
Rockets to the Portland Trail Blazers for Kelvin Cato, Stacey 
Augmon, Walt Williams, Ed Gray, Brian Shaw and Carlos Rogers. 
Pippen wanted out of Houston, as evidenced by his highly critical 
remarks Wednesday about Rockets teammate Charles Barkley, but would 
have preferred to go to the Lakers so he could be reunited with 
Phil Jackson, his coach in Chicago when Pippen and the Bulls won 
six championships. 

</P>
<P>
	McGwire Moves to No. 10 on Career HR List  
</P>
<P>
	ST. LOUIS (AP) -- Mark McGwire hit his 64th home run in the first  
inning today, tying him for 10th on the career list and putting him 
two ahead of Sammy Sosa. Sosa was watching in right field when 
McGwire hit a drive estimated at 424 feet that gave the St. Louis 
Cardinals a 1-0 lead over the Chicago Cubs. It was McGwire's 521st 
career home run, tying Willie McCovey and Ted Williams. 

</P>
<P>
	AP NewsBrief by GABRIEL MADWAY  
  	   	
</P>
