<HEADLINE> Boggs Hits 3,000, Still Going </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	ST. PETERSBURG, Fla. (AP) -- Missing the final month of the  
regular season taught Wade Boggs one thing: he is not ready to stop 
playing. 
</P>
<P>
	``I'm not ready to quit,'' the Tampa Bay Devil Rays third  
baseman said on Friday. ``The fire is still burning.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Boggs, who on Aug. 7 became the 23rd player with 3,000 career  
hits underwent season-ending arthroscopic right knee surgery one 
month later. He was hitting .301 with two homers and 29 RBIs when 
his 18th season abruptly ended. 
</P>
<P>
	``The last month has been extremely tough,'' said Boggs, who has  
started a normal offseason training regiment now that his knee has 
healed. ``It's not fun sitting at home. It shows I still want to 
play.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The Devil Rays hold an option for next season and have said a  
final decision won't be made until the offseason. 
</P>
<P>
	``Right now, I don't know what to expect for the future,'' Boggs  
said. 
</P>
<P>
	Boggs was honored Friday with a plaque on ``Baseball Boulevard''  
outside Tropicana Field commemorating his 3,000th hit. 
  	   	
</P>
