<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Heir Searcher Has Lots to Ponder </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	PINE CITY, Minn. (AP) -- A man who has promised to will his  
$375,000 estate to a church opened his living room on Saturday to 
ministers and lay people, hoping they could provide him answers to 
weighty theological questions. 
</P>
<P>
	Clayton Goward, 79, hasn't decided which church will get the  
money. 
</P>
<P>
	Goward began his search for an heir with a personal ad in the  
Star Tribune of Minneapolis in July appealing for suggestions for 
what to do with his estate, since he's estranged from his three 
sons and divorced their mother long ago. Because of the news 
coverage that followed, he's received more than 40,000 pieces of 
mail since then, and he doesn't want any more. 
</P>
<P>
	As it turned out, the 60-plus people who packed his sunny living  
room on a beautiful fall day were more interested in sharing their 
faith than getting his money. 
</P>
<P>
	``Is it really necessary to be born again?'' Goward asked. ``How  
can we KNOW the Bible is true? ... Why can't we KNOW instead of 
having to guess?'' 
</P>
<P>
	The crowd -- heavy on Evangelicals and Pentecostalists -- was  
eager to help resolve his uncertainty. 
</P>
<P>
	``The fact that you're questioning, Clayton, is a sign that God  
is working in your heart,'' said David Holt, a pastor from First 
Evangelical Free Church in La Crosse, Wis., whose sentiments were 
repeated by several others. 
</P>
<P>
	``Why isn't God here right now?'' Goward asked later.  
</P>
<P>
	``He is,'' nearly everyone responded in unison.  
</P>
<P>
	``I don't see him,'' Goward said.  
</P>
<P>
	Goward expressed frustration that there are so many religions  
and so many different interpretations of the Bible. The frustration 
was illustrated by the heated debate that broke out after Gary 
Amirault, who drove in from Hermann, Mo., disputed the existence of 
hell. The lengthy debate appeared to sway nobody, though Goward 
said he found it interesting. 
</P>
<P>
	Afterward, Goward said he has some thinking to do.  
</P>
<P>
	``I'm going to mull it over,'' he said as he helped himself to a  
plate of fried chicken, mashed potatoes and coleslaw. ``What I'm 
just going to have to do is believe. It's a faith thing.'' 
</P>
<P>
	And as for what to do with his money -- which is mostly tied up  
in his house and land -- he said he still has to think about that, 
too. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
