<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-02 08:20:10 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Supreme Court Faces Old Quandary </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- The Supreme Court, having reshaped the balance  
of federal-state government power in recent years, begins its 
1999-2000 term Monday with several chances to fire fresh volleys in 
what some call a states' rights revolution. 
</P>
<P>
	The justices also confront an old quandary -- public aid to  
religious schools -- and a new one close to home -- grandparents' 
right to see their grandchildren. 
</P>
<P>
	Heading into the new century, the court also is tackling  
disputes over tobacco regulation, automobile safety, anti-abortion 
demonstrations and limits on political contributions. 
</P>
<P>
	The nine-member court has been intact since 1994 and, despite  
Justice Ruth Bader Ginsburg's recent colon cancer surgery, is not 
expected to undergo any change before the next presidential 
election. 
</P>
<P>
	Three cases will test the court's commitment to giving states  
more power at the federal government's expense -- a phenomenon 
Washington lawyer Charles Cooper calls ``the most noticeable 
development of the Rehnquist court.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Chief Justice William H. Rehnquist has led the court since 1986.  
</P>
<P>
	``These cases address in differing ways a single political  
impulse -- to give more power to the states,'' said Steven Shapiro, 
legal director of the American Civil Liberties Union. ``This year, 
the court's consideration of those questions comes even closer to 
core concerns of the civil rights community.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The relationship between the federal government and the states --  
what constitutional scholars call federalism -- is not widely 
considered as politically volatile as abortion, religion and other 
topics that reach the nation's highest court. But the justices' 
view of that relationship defines in fundamental ways the ebb and 
flow of political power while affecting everyday American life. 
</P>
<P>
	The justices will use a Virginia case to decide whether Congress  
exceeded its authority in 1994 when it enacted a law allowing women 
who are raped or stalked to sue their attackers. 
</P>
<P>
	A federal appeals court threw out the law after ruling that  
Congress' power to regulate interstate commerce and assure equal 
protection for all citizens did not authorize it to give victims 
such a legal right. 
</P>
<P>
	A Florida case will determine whether state employees who say  
they are victims of age discrimination can make a federal case of 
it. 
</P>
<P>
	The justices must decide whether Congress, in passing the Age  
Discrimination in Employment Act of 1967, wiped out the 11th 
Amendment immunity states enjoy against being sued in federal 
courts. 
</P>
<P>
	A South Carolina dispute over states' practice of selling  
personal information from driver's license records -- such as 
addresses and Social Security numbers -- focuses on Congress' power 
to require states to close motor vehicle records to the public. 
</P>
<P>
	The fate of a 1994 federal law, the Driver's Privacy Protection  
Act, hangs in the balance. 
</P>
<P>
	In a parochial-aid case from Louisiana, the justices must decide  
whether computers and other instructional materials paid for with 
taxpayer money can be lent to all private schools, including those 
with religious missions. 
</P>
<P>
	What the court says could become ``the most important  
church-state decision in over two decades,'' according to the Rev. 
Barry Lynn of Americans United for Separation of Church and State. 
The ruling also may determine the scope of federal efforts to 
connect every American classroom to the Internet. 
</P>
<P>
	Two 1970s decisions limited such direct aid to the lending of  
textbooks, but today's court has, in other contexts, proved more 
tolerant of ties between government and religion. 
</P>
<P>
	A case from Washington state focuses on a state's power to  
provide grandparents with visitation rights even when the 
children's parents object. All 50 states provide such rights. 
</P>
<P>
	The justices -- six of whom are grandparents -- must decide  
whether such laws wrongly interfere with parents' right to rear 
their families without government interference. 
</P>
<P>
	The Clinton administration and tobacco industry square off  
before the court in a fight over smoking. The justices must decide 
whether the Food and Drug Administration can regulate tobacco by 
cracking down on cigarette sales to minors. 
</P>
<P>
	In another regulatory dispute, the court will decide whether  
people who own cars built before air bags became mandatory can sue 
automakers on grounds the safety devices could have saved them from 
injuries. 
</P>
<P>
	The justices will decide whether Colorado went too far in  
limiting ``sidewalk counseling'' by anti-abortion demonstrators 
when it enacted a 1993 law that bars people from getting within 
eight feet of someone without consent when near a health clinic 
entrance. 
</P>
<P>
	A decision likely will contain important new guidelines for  
other states and for communities nationwide. 
</P>
<P>
	And the court will judge the constitutionality of Missouri's  
money limits on contributions to political candidates. The justices 
are being asked to use the case to reconsider the court's landmark 
1976 ruling that imposed a $1,000 limit on contributions to 
candidates for federal office. 
</P>
<P>
	In all, the court has committed itself to deciding 44 cases by  
late June. Dozens more will be added in the coming months. The 
justices decided 75 cases during their last nine-month term, and 
rejected some 7,000 other appeals that reached them. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
