<HEADLINE> AP Top News at 11 p.m. EDT  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 *Saturday, Oct. 2, 1999    	

</P>
<P>
	Clinton Expected To Raise $850,000  
</P>
<P>
	PALO ALTO, Calif. (AP) -- President Clinton was expected to raise  
$850,000 for Democratic candidates while speaking before gay and 
lesbian supporters at a dinner in Los Angeles tonight. The sum is 
the largest amount of his three-day West Coast swing. Serving as 
host for tonight's dinner was ANGLE -- Access Now for Gay and 
Lesbian Equality -- and organizers said it was one of the largest 
events of its kind outside Washington. 

</P>
<P>
	Missile Interceptor Passes Crucial Test  
</P>
<P>
	VANDENBERG AIR FORCE BASE, Calif. (AP) -- A prototype national  
missile defense system passed a critical test today, intercepting 
an unarmed missile on a 16,000-mph collision course over the 
Pacific. ``It was a successful intercept,'' a spokeswoman said for 
the Department of Defense. An unarmed Minuteman missile was 
launched just after 7 p.m. on a flight over the Pacific to the 
Marshall Islands, where it collided with an intercontinental 
ballistic missile about 140 miles above sea level. 

</P>
<P>
	Japanese Fear Radiation As They Return Home  
</P>
<P>
	TOKAIMURA, Japan -- Life began returning to normal Sunday for  
townspeople living next to the site of Japan's worst nuclear 
disaster, with most spending the night at home after the government 
lifted an evacuation order. Many in Tokaimura, a town of 33,000 
about 70 miles northeast of Tokyo, were still not convinced that it 
was safe to go home. Late Saturday, the government lifted an 
evacuation order for the more than 160 residents who had been holed 
up in a community center. 

</P>
