	Big Union Gives Endorsement to Gore  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- A large health care workers union endorsed  
Vice President Al Gore over Bill Bradley today in the race for the 
Democratic presidential nomination. AFL-CIO officials were watching 
the straw vote of Local 250 of the Service Employees International 
Union for signs of Gore's strength going into next week's crucial 
AFL-CIO convention. It is the nation's second-largest health 
workers union with 46,000 members in Northern California. 

</P>
<P>
	Venezuelans March to Support Chavez  
</P>
<P>
	CARACAS, Venezuela (AP) -- Thousands of backers of President Hugo  
Chavez marched through downtown Caracas today to support what the 
former coup leader calls a ``peaceful revolution'' aimed at 
reducing rampant corruption and poverty. Protesters said they 
wanted the popularly elected assembly to quickly finish its 
principal mission -- writing a new constitution -- so that new 
elections for Congress, state governors, mayors and possibly even 
the presidency could be held. 

</P>
<P>
	Experts Warn of New Nuclear Threats  
</P>
<P>
	STOCKHOLM, Sweden (AP) -- Another war between India and Pakistan  
could include a nuclear exchange, former U.S. defense secretary 
William Perry said Saturday at an arms control symposium. Speaking 
in a panel discussion that ended a two-day Nobel Symposium called 
``A future arms control agenda,'' Perry said he thinks it's likely 
that more nations will obtain nuclear weapons. 

</P>
