<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Carter Celebrates 75th Birthday </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	AMERICUS, Ga. (AP) -- Wearing a tuxedo and his trademark toothy  
grin, former President Jimmy Carter was in a jovial mood as he 
celebrated his 75th birthday with about 800 well-wishers. 
</P>
<P>
	``I'm glad I made it,'' Carter quipped during Friday night's  
festivities. ``I've never had a better time in my life.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The birthday bash at the historic Rylander Theatre in Americus,  
just 12 miles east of Carter's hometown of Plains, included 
performances by Pat Boone and the Indigo Girls, a giant birthday 
cake and healthy helpings of anecdotes about Carter's days in the 
White House. 
</P>
<P>
	Supporters filled the theater's 630 seats, while another 200 sat  
outside in a parking lot to enjoy the celebration on a giant 
television screen. 
</P>
<P>
	Joined by his wife, Rosalynn, at a news conference, Carter  
called his loss to Ronald Reagan in the 1980 presidential election 
his ``biggest failure.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``At that time, I looked on it as an embarrassing failure,''  
Carter said. 
</P>
<P>
	``I could rationalize and say `If the hostages hadn't been held,  
I would have been re-elected,''' he said referring to the 1979 
crisis when Iranian students held 52 Americans hostage at the U.S. 
Embassy for more than a year. ``I had a lot of unfulfilled 
expectations.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Carter said he's drawn strength from his religious beliefs.  
Apparent setbacks have consistently provided him with new 
opportunities, he said. 
</P>
<P>
	``I've had ups and downs, but almost invariably the downs have  
become some of the most fortunate things in my life,'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	As an example, Carter pointed to his work in founding the Carter  
Center after he left Washington. Since then, he's become known as 
the most active former president in modern U.S. history, monitoring 
elections worldwide, championing peace and human rights and working 
to improve living conditions in developing nations. 
</P>
<P>
	Among the speakers at the event were ABC television analyst Sam  
Donaldson and senior White House correspondent Helen Thomas of 
United Press International. Both covered Carter's campaign and 
presidency. 
</P>
<P>
	The party also served as a fund-raiser for the Rylander Theatre,  
which was built in 1921 as a cinema, closed in disrepair in 1951 
and was reopened this summer after $4 million in refurbishments. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
