<HEADLINE> Air Force Baseball Coach Fired </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	AIR FORCE ACADEMY, Colo. (AP) -- Air Force baseball coach Joe  
Giarratano, who led the Falcons to their best winning percentage in 
four years, has been fired after one season, academy officials 
confirmed Friday. 
</P>
<P>
	Air Force spokeswoman Helen Littlejohn verified Giarratano's  
firing but said she could not give any other details. 
</P>
<P>
	Under Giarratano, Air Force went 19-32 last year for a .372  
winning percentage -- the team's best since 1995. The Falcons 
finished 5-20 in the Western Athletic Conference. 
</P>
<P>
	Giarratano, a Denver native, came to Air Force in 1998 after  
spending four seasons as the head coach at Mesa State, which went 
141-85 under him and advanced to the NCAA Division II West 
Regionals in 1997. 
</P>
<P>
	Prior to his stint at Mesa State, Giarratano went 189-90 as the  
head coach at Colby (Kan.) Junior College. 
</P>
<P>
	Giarratano went to high school in Pueblo and played baseball at  
the University of Northern Colorado. He also worked as a scout for 
the Kansas City Royals and coached at two Colorado high schools. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
