<CATEGORY> political </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Reform Party Aims to Reunite </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Top Reform Party officials worked Saturday to  
coax a splinter group of their own to return. But organizers of the 
split said they first needed guarantees that Republican 
presidential candidate Pat Buchanan would not become the party's 
nominee. 
</P>
<P>
	``The presidential candidate of the Reform Party is almost the  
single hinge that will bring us back together,'' Ted Muga, chairman 
of the splinter group known as the American Reform Party, said at a 
meeting of 100 supporters. 
</P>
<P>
	``We would never associate ourselves with any organization in  
which a person like that whose religious, political or moral views 
are of his nature,'' Muga said of Buchanan. 
</P>
<P>
	``It sure would be nice to have ya'll back,'' implored Jack  
Gargan, chairman-elect of the Reform Party. ``We've got to put 
aside those things we disagree on.'' On a possible Buchanan run, 
Gargan said he had to remain ``neutral.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The efforts to reunify came as the party dealt with another  
brouhaha involving comments made by Minnesota Gov. Jesse Ventura, 
the Reform Party's top elected official, in an interview with 
Playboy magazine. 
</P>
<P>
	Ventura, whose frank talk got him elected in a November upset,  
told Playboy that organized religious ``is a sham,'' the Navy 
Tailhook scandal was ``much ado about nothing'' and fat people 
``can't push away from the table.'' 
</P>
<P>
	On being governor, he said: ``It's good to be king.''  
</P>
<P>
	Reform Party chairman Russell Verney demanded Friday that  
Ventura resign from the party, saying the former professional 
wrestler ``brought shame'' to himself. 
</P>
<P>
	But Gargan told the American Reform Party leaders Saturday,  
``Let's cut him some slack.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``I'm not ready to throw him out the party,'' Gargan said. He  
added: ``I'm not letting him off the hook. I think he's learned a 
very valuable lesson from it. I think we need to judge him by what 
he has done as governor.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Still, former Connecticut Gov. Lowell Weicker, who is weighing  
running for the Reform Party presidential nomination, seemed to 
take a jab at Ventura telling delegates, ``Whether of our making or 
not, the current flamboyance, zaniness and brouhahas reflect on all 
of us as independents.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Afterwards, when asked by reporters if he was referring to  
Ventura, Weicker said, ``I went out of my way not to mention names. 
I don't want to do that. But hey . . . if the shoe fits wear it.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Delegates, however, did not seem too disturbed about Ventura.  
Instead, they were more concerned over the Reform Party's possible 
candidates for president, Muga said. 
</P>
<P>
	Ventura is trying to head off the possible candidacy of the  
conservative Buchanan, who may leave the GOP for a Reform Party 
bid. 
</P>
<P>
	Ventura has urged real estate tycoon Donald Trump to run, but  
aides said Saturday he also would be open to Weicker. 
</P>
<P>
	Trump, who spoke with the group Friday night and had political  
operatives mingling with delegates, is probably not a viable 
candidate for the party, Muga said. 
</P>
<P>
	``The reaction (to Trump) was very unreceptive on a number of  
issues,'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	Trump is expected to announce a decision in December. Weicker  
said he would make up his mind this month. 
</P>
<P>
	Also, Perot has not ruled out a third presidential race,  
although members of the American Reform party already have voiced 
opposition. Perot and Buchanan are expected to talk soon by 
telephone about Buchanan's plans. 
</P>
<P>
	Buchanan plans to announce his intentions by mid-October.  
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
