<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> IOC: No Need To Punish Atlanta </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	ATHENS, Greece (AP) -- The IOC official who led the internal  
investigation into the Salt Lake City scandal said Saturday he saw 
no need for punitive action in connection with Atlanta's winning 
bid for the 1996 Summer Games. 
</P>
<P>
	International Olympic Committee vice president Dick Pound said  
the excesses related to Atlanta did not compare with those stemming 
from Salt Lake City's successful bid for the 2002 Winter Games. 
</P>
<P>
	Pound led an inquiry which led to the expulsion or resignation  
of 10 IOC members in connection with gifts, cash, college 
scholarships and other favors accepted by members and their 
families during the Salt Lake City bid. 
</P>
<P>
	A report submitted to Congress last month detailed a similar  
pattern of gift-giving during the Atlanta bid. 
</P>
<P>
	But Pound, attending an IOC executive board meeting in Athens,  
said: ``I don't believe there's anything in that report that would 
lead to any further action against any members.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Pound said the IOC would rely on the findings of its new ethics  
commission, which announced last week it would review the Atlanta 
report for any possible misconduct by IOC members. 
</P>
<P>
	Pound complained that no IOC members were contacted to give  
their version of events before the Atlanta report, prepared by 
former Attorney General Griffin Bell, was made public. 
</P>
<P>
	``The report detailed a lot of offers that were pushed upon IOC  
members and were not accepted,'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	Rep. Fred Upton, R-Mich., has said the report showed ``votes  
were for sale'' and said the Atlanta bid was surrounded by a 
``culture of corruption.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Upton has scheduled a House hearing on the Atlanta bid Oct. 14  
and requested that IOC president Juan Antonio Samaranch appear as a 
witness. He has threatened to subpoena Samaranch if he declines to 
testify voluntarily. 
</P>
<P>
	IOC director general Francois Carrard said Samaranch was  
expected to announce Sunday whether he would go to Washington. 
</P>
<P>
	In addition to the pressures from Congress, IOC members are  
reluctant to travel to the United States because they could face 
questioning by the FBI in connection with its Salt Lake City 
investigation. 
</P>
<P>
	``There is a concern on the part of some of the members,'' Pound  
said. ``They don't understand how the Justice Department and the 
FBI works. They're nervous.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19991002.0051 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-02 11:50:15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Poor Workers Grope for Prosperity </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WILKES-BARRE, Pa. (AP) -- Like it or not, Andrea Cooper is doing  
her bit to fuel the economic boom. She is 3 months old and heading 
to a day-care program so her mother can replace welfare payments 
with a $6.75-an-hour hospital paycheck. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's going to be tough,'' says Tonya Cooper, single mother of  
Andrea and three older children. ``I feel bad leaving her so young, 
but I truly believe God is not going to put my children in the way 
of any harm.'' 
</P>
<P>
	There is nothing new about poverty in America. But never before  
have poor families like the Coopers had to wage their daily 
struggles amid such pervasive chatter about unprecedented 
prosperity. 
</P>
<P>
	While the wealthy grow steadily richer riding the stock market  
surges, millions of working Americans grope for their infinitesimal 
share of the boom. 
</P>
<P>
	Many have been forced off welfare as part of nationwide reforms;  
others are victims of layoffs or lack the skills now in demand. 
Wages often are too meager to allow self-sufficiency; work is often 
grueling or mind-numbing, on night shifts, without health insurance 
or other benefits. 
</P>
<P>
	Ms. Cooper and other hard-pressed Wilkes-Barre residents sound  
more fatalistic than angry as they discuss their lives. But 
anti-poverty workers in the city of 48,000 express outrage on their 
behalf. 
</P>
<P>
	Sister Marie Larkin, a Roman Catholic nun who came from Ireland  
to Pennsylvania nine years ago, is still shocked that such a 
prosperous nation is home to such widespread poverty. 
</P>
<P>
	``The CEOs of these companies are making millions,'' she says.  
``They're making it because some poor worker is earning a pittance 
... I think it's criminal.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Sister Larkin, who runs a shelter for disadvantaged women, has  
compared experiences with friends working in the impoverished 
African country of Zambia. 
</P>
<P>
	``I believe the poor here are in a worse situation,'' she says.  
``In Zambia, they don't know what they're missing.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Decades ago, Wilkes-Barre was a thriving city in northeast  
Pennsylvania's coal belt. As the mines gradually closed, the 
jobless rate rose. Then it soared into double-digits after many 
manufacturers -- notably in the garment industry -- pulled out. 
</P>
<P>
	More than eight years into the national economic boom,  
Wilkes-Barre has gradually whittled its jobless rate to 5.7 
percent, the lowest this decade although well above the national 
rate of 4.2 percent. 
</P>
<P>
	Civic leaders herald the new jobs as evidence of a turnaround,  
but many are low-level service jobs in health care, retailing and 
telemarketing that pay less than $7 per hour. 
</P>
<P>
	``They're not family-sustaining jobs,'' says Joe Capece, an  
official of an electrical workers union and the regional trade 
union council. ``We've got to have jobs that people could raise a 
family on, buy a house on. Instead, you're asking people to live in 
poverty.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Capece echoes a complaint heard often around Wilkes-Barre: Some  
retailers and other employers were hiring people to work 30 to 34 
hours a week, just under the 35-hour limit needed for workers to 
qualify for the benefits of full-time status. Nationally, according 
to the Bureau of Labor Statistics, 3.2 million people involuntarily 
work at part-time jobs. 
</P>
<P>
	Wilkes-Barre used to be a labor stronghold, but union strength  
has ebbed with the loss of manufacturing jobs. Local figures 
closely mirror the national trend: Union members now comprise about 
14 percent of the American workforce, compared with 20 percent in 
1983. 
</P>
<P>
	Many of the unionized manufacturing jobs lost in Wilkes-Barre  
paid twice as much as the new service jobs. Some major 
service-sector employers, such as Wal-Mart and McDonald's, have 
resisted union organizing efforts nationwide with almost total 
success. ``People are scared to organize,'' Capece says. 
</P>
<P>
	A worker like Jay Miscavage doesn't have a chance to contemplate  
union membership. Homeless, and gaunt from a 25-pound weight loss, 
Miscavage has been taking temporary jobs, skimping on meals and 
sleeping in his pickup in motel parking lot. 
</P>
<P>
	``I'm lucky I've got a truck,'' he says. ``The guys I'm working  
with are sleeping in the woods.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Miscavage, 39, discusses his predicament after finishing a  
serving of pizza at the St. Vincent de Paul Kitchen, a storefront 
charity meal program in a rundown section of downtown. The kitchen 
serves 300 to 400 lunches daily, up from less than 100 a decade 
ago. 
</P>
<P>
	For weeks during the summer, Miscavage resisted going to the  
kitchen even though he was nearly broke. ``I felt there were people 
who deserved the food more.'' 
</P>
<P>
	What changed his mind? ``I was hungry,'' he says.  
</P>
<P>
	Miscavage worked for 12 years as a landscaper, earning $12 an  
hour -- good by local standards -- but he was unhappy with his boss 
and quit. 
</P>
<P>
	``I thought I'd be able to find something better, but it didn't  
work out that way,'' he says, describing recent temporary jobs that 
paid barely above the $5.15-an-hour minimum wage. 
</P>
<P>
	``They say the economy is going up, but you have to work for  
$5.50 an hour,'' he says. ``You can't save nothing. It's the rich 
that get richer.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Statistics support Miscavage's gripe. Recent figures from the  
Congressional Budget Office show that the poorest 20 percent of 
U.S. households will average $8,800 in after-tax income this year, 
down from $10,000 in 1977, while at the same time the average 
income of the richest 1 percent has more than doubled to $515,600 
after taxes. 
</P>
<P>
	Jared Bernstein, an economist with the Economic Policy  
Institute, a Washington think tank, says the trends in Wilkes-Barre 
reflect worrisome national problems. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's a place where blue-collar guys in the past could find  
decent middle-class jobs,'' he says. ``The quality of the jobs 
they've lost are obviously far superior to the jobs that are being 
created.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Despite the boom, the nation has lost 1 million manufacturing  
jobs in the past decade. Average pay for top executives has 
quadrupled since 1990, but roughly 45 million Americans --including 
many in low-paid service jobs -- lack health insurance. 
</P>
<P>
	Along with health-care coverage, child care and transportation  
are often cited in Wilkes-Barre as the toughest challenges facing 
low-income workers. The city bus system doesn't run at night, 
making it difficult for workers without cars to handle nightshift 
jobs. 
</P>
<P>
	Those who do work at night, or attend night school, have created  
a need for off-hour child care. The Catholic Youth Center has 
extended its day-care program from 5:30 p.m. until midnight and may 
operate round-the-clock. 
</P>
<P>
	``The parents are really grateful,'' says Laura Bozinski, the  
center's director of child care. Nap-time in the evening session 
starts at 9 p.m., and the kids often are sound asleep when their 
parents collect them. 
</P>
<P>
	For single mothers targeted by welfare reform programs, child  
care can be a huge obstacle. 
</P>
<P>
	Nikiki Blake, 28, has five children, ages 2 to 11. She is now  
surviving solely on child-support payments after going off welfare, 
quitting a low-paying job as a nursing assistant, and failing to 
find other work that would mesh with family demands. 
</P>
<P>
	She is glad to have escaped the bureaucratic regimen of welfare  
yet is pessimistic about the chances of completing one more year of 
school that would qualify her as a registered nurse. 
</P>
<P>
	Welfare officials often lack patience, she says. ``They want you  
to take the first little crummy job that comes along. But $6 an 
hour is not going to cut it.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``The one good thing about not being on welfare is there's no  
one on your back,'' she says. ``But it's also a struggle if you're 
off welfare ... . Unless you find somebody rich to marry or win the 
lottery, it's really hard.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Since Pennsylvania's welfare reform program was enacted in early  
1997, the number of families receiving cash assistance in 
Wilkes-Barre's Luzerne County has dropped from 3,157 to 1,589. 
</P>
<P>
	A spokesman for Pennsylvania's welfare department, Jay Pagni,  
says the state recognizes the need to train former recipients for 
better jobs. 
</P>
<P>
	But in Wilkes-Barre, there are relatively few semiskilled jobs  
that pay more than $9 an hour. Anti-poverty advocates say that's 
the minimum needed in the region for a single parent with one child 
to be self-sufficient. 
</P>
<P>
	Sister Larkin tells of one single mother from her shelter who  
proudly got off welfare and took a restaurant job that produced a 
combination of wages and tips far too meager to support her family. 
</P>
<P>
	``I said to her, 'Forget it. You can't do this. Go back on  
welfare until you can get a better job,''' Sister Larkin recalls. 
</P>
<P>
	``You shouldn't have to put up with such conditions,'' the nun  
says. ``But the poor seem to have no voice anymore.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Gene Brady, head of a Luzerne County anti-poverty organization  
called the Commission on Economic Opportunity, is a daily witness 
to the consequences of low-wage jobs. But he says there is little 
use blaming the employers, since they generally adjust their wages 
up or down based on the competition. 
</P>
<P>
	Brady expresses hope that Wilkes-Barre's labor market will  
tighten enough so employers will have to offer higher wages to 
attract workers. In the meantime, he worries about the toll on 
families when parents have to work two jobs or on night shifts. 
</P>
<P>
	``Who's left out of this?'' he asks. ``It may be the children.  
Are they getting the nurturing they need? Are they getting proper 
nutrition?'' 
</P>
<P>
	Tonya Cooper asks herself those same questions as she braces for  
the working-day separation from little Andrea. The new hospital job 
also requires Ms. Cooper to work every other weekend, so she must 
find someone to keep an eye on her three school-age children on 
those days. 
</P>
<P>
	To fulfill her dream of completing a college degree at night,  
Ms. Cooper will eventually have to decide whether to spend even 
more time away from her children. 
</P>
<P>
	``I get frustrated a lot of times,'' she says, softly and  
calmly. ``It seems like it's so hard to get ahead. And when you 
finally are succeeding, you get knocked down. 
</P>
<P>
	``You have to get out there and be motivated and try to get what  
you want. I'm doing the best that I can.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19991002.0052 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-02 12:20:20 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Rockies' Leyland Unemotional Finale </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	DENVER (AP) -- Jim Leyland wept openly April 17 when the Colorado  
Rockies presented him with his 1,000th managerial victory. He 
doesn't expect a similar flow of emotion Sunday when he carries out 
his final lineup card before the Rockies' game against the San 
Francisco Giants. 
</P>
<P>
	``I'm sure there are going to be some moments where I have a  
tough time, but I think everybody is tired at the end of the season 
whether teams are going good or bad,'' Leyland said. ``The way I'll 
look at it is the season is over and I'm going home.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Leyland, 54, who signed a three-year $6 million contract to  
manage the Rockies on Oct. 5, 1998, will end his 11-year managerial 
career Sunday. Going into Saturday's game against the Giants, he 
had a 1,066-1,127 record with Pittsburgh, Florida and Colorado. 
</P>
<P>
	After much speculation surrounding his future with the Rockies,  
he told his players Sept. 6 that he wouldn't be returning in 2000. 
Leyland admitted he would miss the regimen he'd become accustomed 
to, but was elusive about his future. 
</P>
<P>
	``I am hoping to stay in the game, but I don't know when that's  
going to happen or if that's going to happen,'' he said. ``It will 
be different going home knowing I won't be planning spring training 
for the first time in 15 years.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Leyland and Colorado ownership have discussed a role with the  
team, but none of the talk has resulted in anything of substance. 
He acknowledged Saturday that finding a position probably wasn't a 
high priority of newly hired general manager Dan O'Dowd. 
</P>
<P>
	``Dan's got so many things to do to get all his soldiers in  
order for next year,'' Leyland said. ``I'm not sure it's best for 
me to stay in the organization or just move on. I remember when 
they offered a job to Don Baylor and he said he felt strange about 
it. 
</P>
<P>
	``I don't know if I want to tag along. I'm not sure whether it  
is not best for everybody to make a new start and turn the page.'' 
</P>
<P>
	One thing is certain: Leyland is leaving the game to be closer  
to his family. He never moved his family from Pittsburgh and lived 
at Coors Field after converting a conference room into an 
apartment. 
</P>
<P>
	``I want to spend time with my family,'' Leyland said. ``I was  
home on Easter Sunday maybe once or twice in the last 14 or 15 
years, make that 30 years.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Leyland's Marlins won the World Series in 1997 and his Pirates  
won three division titles. None rank as his No. 1 accomplishment of 
becoming a major league manager. 
</P>
<P>
	``The fact I never played in the big leagues and was able to get  
over the minor league syndrome,'' said Leyland, who signed with the 
Detroit Tigers Sept. 21, 1963, but never played above Double A from 
1964-69. ``I think to get over that syndrome and earn the respect 
of most of the players, that's No. 1 for me. 
</P>
<P>
	``It was an honor to get the job with the Pirates and the chance  
to take a team to the playoffs and the World Series. I'll always 
appreciate that I got that chance.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Leyland also is proud of his relationship with Barry Bonds.  
</P>
<P>
	``I love Barry and we had a great relationship,'' Leyland said.  
``We were two people that demanded respect for one another and gave 
it to each other. 
</P>
<P>
	``Barry was a gifted player and it took me a while to earn his  
respect. I was from the era of his dad (Bobby), but his dad was a 
star major leaguer and I was a minor league guy.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Of his teams, Leyland rated the Pirates of the early '90s and  
the 1997 Marlins as his favorites. 
</P>
<P>
	``We had all of the pieces together in Pittsburgh and were very  
good and had a chance to be very good for a long time,'' Leyland 
said. ``The Florida team was the best team in baseball at the end 
and you can't take that away because we beat the Atlanta Braves 
10-out-of-12 in the regular season and 4-of-6 in the playoffs. 
</P>
<P>
	``I'm still bothered by people that accused us of buying a World  
Series. We had all the players in place, but nobody picked us to 
win in spring training.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Leyland listed Bonds, Kirk Gibson, Andy Van Slyke and Kevin  
Brown among the greatest players he's managed. 
</P>
<P>
	``I think Bonds was one of the greatest players to play the game  
and Gibson was unbelievable at rising to the occasion,'' Leyland 
said. ``Larry Walker was the most instinctive I've managed. Kevin 
Brown, Jack Morris, Doug Drabek ... but my favorite was Bob Walk. 
</P>
<P>
	``Bob would always take the ball and do whatever he was asked to  
do.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
