<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Farm Aid Spurs Look at New Program </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- It is harvest time again, and Congress is  
passing another multibillion-dollar bailout to keep farmers in 
business. Many lawmakers say it also is time to find a cheaper, 
more effective way to support farmers. 
</P>
<P>
	The idea getting the most attention is a new subsidy program  
proposed by Rep. Charles Stenholm of Texas, the senior Democrat on 
the House Agriculture Committee. 
</P>
<P>
	His plan would provide payments to farmers when prices for crops  
fall significantly below average. The size of the checks would be 
tied to local crop yields. The idea is to guarantee farmers a 
minimum level of income each year, and ensure the cash goes to 
farmers, not landowners, as some subsidies now do. 
</P>
<P>
	``The payments would go directly to actual producers in time of  
need,'' Stenholm said. ``It's the kind of long-term approach we 
should be using to address agriculture's cyclical problems.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The 1996 ``Freedom to Farm'' law was supposed to wean growers  
from their dependence on government programs. But market prices 
collapsed last year and economists see little improvement ahead. 
</P>
<P>
	Lawmakers rushed out $6 billion in emergency relief last fall,  
and the Senate is expected to give final approval this week to $8.7 
billion more. 
</P>
<P>
	``Our current farm law doesn't provide the necessary safety net  
for our producers,'' said Rep. Jo Ann Emerson, R-Mo. Stenholm's 
plan deserves ``close scrutiny,'' she said. 
</P>
<P>
	The 1996 law provides growers with crop subsidies that are tied  
to fluctuations in prices, not yields, and fixed ``market 
transition'' payments that decline each year. 
</P>
<P>
	Groups such as the National Farmers Union that think the  
government should do more to assist smaller-scale farms are 
interested in Stenholm's idea because it would provide more 
protection when prices are low or crops are poor. 
</P>
<P>
	The much bigger American Farm Bureau Federation and others like  
Stenholm's plan because it would not require controls on 
production, a key feature of the Depression-era farm policy 
Congress tossed out in 1996. 
</P>
<P>
	``It looks like an idea that has strong possibility and merit,''  
said Dick Newpher, executive director of the Farm Bureau's 
Washington office. 
</P>
<P>
	The House Agriculture Committee chairman, Republican Larry  
Combest of Texas, also has expressed interest. He plans a 
comprehensive review of government farm programs next year. 
</P>
<P>
	Agriculture Secretary Dan Glickman wanted to use something like  
Stenholm's plan to distribute $5.5 billion in emergency relief 
included in the latest bailout. Farm groups balked at that 
suggestion because they feared it would delay the assistance. 
Instead, the money will go to recipients of the market transition 
checks, some of whom are not farming anymore. 
</P>
<P>
	Stenholm's plan, which was originally proposed by economists at  
the Agriculture Department and Ohio State University in the early 
1990s, is not without its critics. 
</P>
<P>
	The payments could worsen the worldwide grain glut by  
encouraging farmers to plant crops in areas where they do not do 
well, such as parts of Stenholm's west Texas district, said Neil 
Harl, an agricultural economist at Iowa State University. The 1996 
farm law was designed to do just the opposite. 
</P>
<P>
	Harl, who believes the government should go back to controlling  
production and paying farmers to hold grain off the market, said 
the law is ``fatally flawed.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Sen. Pat Roberts, R-Kan., wonders where the government would get  
the money for Stenholm's payments. 
</P>
<P>
	Rep. Marcy Kaptur, an Ohio Democrat who heads the House  
agricultural appropriations subcommittee, is concerned that the 
program could wind up steering still more farm subsidies to Texas 
to the detriment of other regions. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
