<DOCNO> APW19991002.0057 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-02 07:50:12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> 'Doping Passport' Issue Pushed </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	ATHENS, Greece (AP) -- Athletes should be ineligible to compete  
in future Olympics unless they carry a ``doping passport'' proving 
they have undergone regular out-of-competition drug tests, an 
Olympic athletes' group said Saturday. 
</P>
<P>
	The International Olympic Committee executive board, meanwhile,  
endorsed proposals for 15 athletes to be appointed as members of a 
reformed IOC. 
</P>
<P>
	The IOC athletes' commission met with the executive board  
Saturday to push for a bigger role in the running of the Olympics 
and press for stronger measures to fight performance-enhancing 
drugs. 
</P>
<P>
	Commission member Johann Olav Koss, the Norwegian speed skater  
who won three gold medals at the 1994 Lillehammer Games, said all 
Olympic athletes should carry a ``doping passport'' requiring them 
to be available for out-of-competition controls 365 days a year. 
</P>
<P>
	The passport would be stamped each time the athlete is tested.  
Details would be forwarded to a new international anti-doping 
agency, which would keep records of who had been tested, where and 
when. 
</P>
<P>
	If approved, passports would start to be issued before next  
year's Sydney Games, but the project would only go into full effect 
in time for the 2004 Summer Games in Athens. 
</P>
<P>
	``The goal is to have testing of at least 20,000 athletes before  
Athens,'' Koss said. ``In 2004, you will need to have a passport, 
or you will not be able to participate.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The passport initiative emerged from a working group of the IOC  
2000 commission, a special panel studying a series of reforms in 
the wake of bidding and drug scandals. 
</P>
<P>
	Another central proposal of the reform panel, the appointment of  
15 athletes to the IOC, was formally backed Saturday by the 
executive board. 
</P>
<P>
	The athletes would be elected by their peers. To be eligible,  
they would have to be current Olympic athletes or have competed 
within the past eight years. 
</P>
<P>
	The athletes' group recommended that eight members come from  
summer sports and four from winter sports, with three others 
selected on a geographical basis. 
</P>
<P>
	The athletes would be elected to an eight-year term. At least  
one would serve on the decision-making executive board. 
</P>
<P>
	The proposal will be submitted for ratification along with other  
reform measures at the special IOC session in Lausanne, 
Switzerland, on Dec. 11-12. 
</P>
<P>
	The athletes' group backed the IOC's proposal for a world  
anti-doping agency, a project which has been attacked by White 
House drug policy adviser Barry McCaffrey. He and other critics say 
the agency should be totally independent of the IOC. 
</P>
<P>
	Koss said the athletes are satisfied that the agency, due to be  
set up by the of this year with initial IOC funding of $25 million, 
will gradually become fully independent. 
</P>
<P>
	Koss expressed doubts about the feasibility of McCaffrey's  
proposal for athletes' drug samples to be preserved so they can be 
tested years later when better detection methods become available. 
</P>
<P>
	Instead, Koss urged the United States to commit funds to help  
scientists develop reliable tests for human growth hormone, EPO and 
other drugs which can't be detected in standard urine controls. 
</P>
<P>
	Koss also said he would like the IOC athletes' group to be  
represented at the Oct. 20 hearing called by U.S. Sen. John McCain 
into doping in Olympic sports. 
</P>
<P>
	The athletes raised several concerns about the IOC's proposed  
anti-doping code, a document which sets out drug rules and 
sanctions for all Olympic sports. 
</P>
<P>
	Koss said the group was particularly unclear about the code's  
distinction between ``intentional doping'' and non-intentional 
doping. The athletes will review that and other issues with IOC 
leaders again later this month. 
</P>
<P>
	Robert Ctvrtlik, a former U.S. Olympic volleyball player who is  
on the athletes' panel, said critics of the IOC's anti-doping 
policies should give the organization a break. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's easy when you are outside the IOC to be critical,'' he  
said. ``We have the same goals, the same objectives. It's not 
helpful to pull in different directions.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
