<HEADLINE> AP Top News at 8 p.m. EDT  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 *Saturday, Oct. 2, 1999    	

</P>
<P>
	Police Head Off Belgrade March  
</P>
<P>
	BELGRADE, Yugoslavia (AP) -- Armed riot police stopped a group of  
about 15,000 protesters marching toward President Slobodan 
Milosevic's villa Saturday in Belgrade. A tense standoff ensued, 
but the police didn't start wielding their clubs as they had 
earlier this week. Instead, they pushed the protesters back to the 
city's main square, where the crowds listened to fiery speeches by 
opposition leaders. Saturday marks the 12th consecutive day of 
protests against Milosevic. 

</P>
<P>
	Killings Continue on Eve of India Election  
</P>
<P>
	NEW DELHI, India (AP) -- Suspected guerrillas pushing villagers  
to boycott India's elections gunned down a local politician in the 
state Saturday. The guerrillas have been fighting security forces 
for several years, seeking more autonomy. The guerrillas also set 
off a land mine, killing five people and wounding three others in 
Assam state on the eve of the last round of India's five-phase 
ballot, police said. 

</P>
<P>
	Gore Campaign Stands Behind Manager  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- The Al Gore 2000 presidential campaign issued  
a statement defending campaign manager Tony Coelho, who is facing 
scrutiny for financial irregularities during a previous job. ``Tony 
Coelho does a great job as general chair of Gore 2000,'' the 
statement said. Stanley Brand, Coelho's personal lawyer, said his 
client did not violate any laws in a job that did not pay him a 
salary. State Department investigators say Coelho made the 
government liable for a $300,000 personal loan while directing the 
U.S. pavilion at the 1998 world's fair in Portugal. 

</P>
<P>
	White House Hurries To Save Test Ban  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- WASHINGTON (AP) -- The White House launched an  
effort today to save a global nuclear test ban treaty. Trying to 
build support, President Clinton will speak about the treaty 
Tuesday when he signs a major defense bill at the Pentagon. Senate 
GOP leaders abruptly decided Thursday to hold a vote on the treaty 
Oct. 12. 

</P>
<P>
	Five Deputies Charged in Chicago  
</P>
<P>
	CHICAGO (AP) -- Five white sheriff's deputies face criminal  
charges for allegedly chasing and opening fire on a black couple in 
their car while the officers were off-duty. Two of the deputies 
were charged yesterday with attempted murder and aggravated 
discharge of a firearm. All five also were charged with obstruction 
of justice, prosecutors said. An attorney for Cory Simmons, 23, and 
his girlfriend, Dominique Mapp, 20, had alleged the June 2 
confrontation was racially motivated, but Devine said there was no 
such evidence. 

</P>
<P>
	Myanmar Embassy Hostages Released  
</P>
<P>
	BANGKOK, Thailand (AP) -- Thailand engineered a peaceful end  
Saturday to the armed takeover of the Myanmar Embassy by five 
pro-democracy activists, flying the rebels by helicopter to the 
Thai-Myanmar border, where they were allowed to go free. After 
holing up in the embassy for 26 hours, the raiders released all 38 
hostages, Thai Interior Minister Sanan Kachornprasart said at a 
news conference. 

</P>
<P>
	Russians Clash With Rebels in Chechen Village  
</P>
<P>
	GROZNY, Russia (AP) -- Russian troops clashed with rebels in  
several parts of the breakaway republic as they took control of a 
village in Chechnya Saturday. Chechnya's vice president vowed his 
people would fight off the Russians -- but also called for 
negotiations. Vakha Arsanov suggested Georgian President Eduard 
Shevardnadze could organize talks between Russian and Chechen 
authorities. Russia began air raids on Chechnya last month after 
Muslim militants based in the territory invaded neighboring 
Dagestan, seeking to create an Islamic state. 

</P>
<P>
	No. 21 Alabama Upsets No. 3 Fla. 40-39  
</P>
<P>
	GAINESVILLE, Fla. (AP) -- Chris Kemp hit on his second attempt at  
an extra point in overtime today, lifting No. 21 Alabama to a 40-39 
victory and snapping No. 3 Florida's 30-game home winning streak. 
Kemp got his second chance after Bennie Alexander of Florida jumped 
offsides following Shaun Alexander's 25-yard touchdown run on the 
first play of Alabama's overtime possession. Alexander furthered 
his Heisman Trophy candidacy, finishing with 106 yards rushing, 94 
yards receiving and four touchdowns. Quarterback Andrew Zow threw 
for 336 yards and two scores. 

</P>
<P>
	Toms Has 3-Stroke Lead at Buick  
</P>
<P>
	PINE MOUNTAIN, Ga. (AP) -- David Toms overcame a bogey on the  
first hole for another 6-under 66 today that gave him a 
three-stroke lead going into the final round of the Buick 
Challenge. Toms answered his bogey with a 5-wood to 18 feet for an 
eagle on the second hole, and the rest of the day was a breeze. He 
never came close to another bogey and finished at 16-under 200, in 
good position for his second PGA Tour victory this year. 

</P>
<P>
	AP NewsBrief by KELLY GRUEL  
  	   	
