<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Blood Vessels Targeted in Research </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	BOSTON (AP) -- Cancer gets most of the attention, but any disease  
that involves the unwanted growth of blood vessels could be a 
target for the new angiogenesis-blocking medicines. 
</P>
<P>
	For instance, the inappropriate spread of blood vessels inside  
the eye is a common cause of blindness. Some speculate that the 
same blood vessel inhibitors being developed for cancer could be 
important drugs for eye disease. 
</P>
<P>
	Other illnesses where the drugs might help include hardening of  
the arteries; arthritis; endometriosis, the uterine disorder; and 
Crohn's disease, a digestive system inflammation. 
</P>
<P>
	It is still too soon to know whether angiogenesis blockers will  
do anything for these disorders, but one encouraging patient 
experience raises the possibility of a role against Von 
Hippel-Lindau syndrome. This rare, inherited condition involves the 
growth of small knots of blood vessels, called angiomas, throughout 
the body. 
</P>
<P>
	Linda Williams, 47, a medical secretary from Roanoke, Va., had  
already lost her left eye to the disease when she was diagnosed 
with an angioma on the optic nerve of her right eye. With her 
vision failing, she went to Boston in April to receive an 
angiogenesis-blocking drug at the Dana-Farber Cancer Institute. 
</P>
<P>
	``I was wearing glasses,'' she said. ``After my fourth  
treatment, my glasses came off. I haven't worn them since. My 
vision is better than perfect.'' 
</P>
<P>
	A larger study is getting under way to test the drug, Sugen's  
SU5416, in others with Von Hippel-Lindau syndrome. 
</P>
<P>
	 *End Adv Sunday, Oct. 3, and thereafter    	
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19991002.0062 </DOCNO>
