<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Mets In Control of Their Destiny </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Just one day ago, the New York Mets' playoff  
hopes were on life support following a disastrous 10-day stretch 
that saw them go from four games ahead in the wild-card chase to 
two games back. 
</P>
<P>
	One dramatic win and a little outside help later let the Mets  
take the field Saturday night against Pittsburgh in control of 
their playoff destiny. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's back in our hands again,'' Matt Franco said after  
Cincinnati lost to Milwaukee 10-6, bringing the Mets within a 
half-game of the wild-card lead with two games to play. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's amazing how you can go from out of it to back in it so  
suddenly.'' 
</P>
<P>
	All it took was a 3-2 win in 11 innings over the Pirates on  
Friday night -- New York's second victory in 10 games -- and losses 
by Houston and Cincinnati to bring the Mets within a game of the 
wild-card leaders. 
</P>
<P>
	The Reds' loss Saturday guaranteed that the Mets would have a  
chance to at least force a wild-card playoff on Sunday. That was 
quite a trip in less than 48 hours after a devastating 4-3, 
11-inning loss to Atlanta on Thursday night. 
</P>
<P>
	``You get hot, then you're not,'' manager Bobby Valentine said.  
``You can't stay hot. That's how this game is.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Fortunately for the Mets, the Reds did not stay hot, losing  
three straight games. Many of the Mets gathered early Saturday to 
follow the Reds' game. 
</P>
<P>
	When the game was unavailable on their satellite, a group of  
them gathered around a computer screen in manager Bobby Valentine's 
office, watching pitch-by-pitch updates come over the Internet. 
</P>
<P>
	That's baseball fever in the high-tech, wild-card age.  
</P>
<P>
	``I was doing a little managing, but mostly rooting,'' Valentine  
said. ``It's much more nerve-wrecking watching a game when you have 
no control.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Before taking the field, the Mets were gathered in their  
clubhouse watching the Astros finish off a 3-0 win over Los 
Angeles. 
</P>
<P>
	That meant there would be no one-game playoff Monday at Shea  
Stadium between the Mets and Astros. The Mets and Reds would have a 
one-game playoff in Cincinnati if they finish in a two-way tie. 
</P>
<P>
	If there is a three-way tie, New York is automatically in and  
the Reds and Astros play one game in Cincinnati to decide the NL 
Central champion -- the loser would be out of the playoffs because 
it would finish a half-game behind the Mets. 
</P>
<P>
	``You can play in a tough division and win more games than  
another team that wins their division and not make the playoffs,'' 
Valentine said defending the system. 
</P>
<P>
	``One of them happens to play another game. Being that we are  
the ones who benefit, then it's really fair. But when did we start 
dealing with what's fair?'' 
</P>
<P>
	If the Mets win twice and Cincinnati loses, New York is also in  
as the wild card. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's neat for baseball with all the different possibilities  
going into the last weekend,'' Valentine said. ``I'd rather have it 
neat for us.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Whatever happens, Valentine knows he probably needs a win  
Sunday. And he decided to stick with Orel Hershiser instead of 
using Al Leiter on three days' rest. 
</P>
<P>
	Valentine took Leiter out after seven innings on Wednesday to  
leave open that option, but with his lack of experience on short 
rest decided to stick with Hershiser. 
</P>
<P>
	``He's only done it once and that was in 1994 in May, not after  
200 innings,'' Valentine said. ``This is not the time to experiment 
with something you haven't done all year. Especially when we have a 
good option in a well-rested Orel.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19991002.0069 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-02 13:36:23 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Probe Checks Mental Hospital Deaths </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- No one knows how many patients have died at  
mental health facilities after being restrained or put into 
seclusion because most centers are not required to report such 
deaths, congressional investigators say. 
</P>
<P>
	The General Accounting Office, Congress' investigative arm, said  
in a report released Friday it determined that at least 24 people 
died and 1,000 were injured or abused in 1998, but the actual 
numbers probably are much higher. Only 15 states have reporting 
systems, it said, and most facilities are not required to report. 
</P>
<P>
	``While restraint and seclusion use can injure patients and  
staff, the full extent of that risk is not known because reporting 
is so fragmentary,'' the study said. 
</P>
<P>
	Lawmakers in the House and the Senate, following Hartford  
Courant investigative articles in Connecticut, have introduced 
bills that would require better reporting, better training of 
mental health care workers and a doctor's authorization before a 
patient is restrained. 
</P>
<P>
	The Senate will hold hearings on the issue before Congress  
adjourns for the year, said Sen. William Roth, the Delaware 
Republican who chairs the Finance Committee. 
</P>
<P>
	``I don't have to tell you that hospitals should be places of  
safety and healing,'' Roth said. The GAO report and the newspaper 
articles suggest an urgent need to ``rededicate ourselves to 
continued improvement,'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	Mental health experts generally agree that a patient must be  
restrained or put into seclusion on an emergency basis when he is a 
danger to himself or to others, the GAO said. 
</P>
<P>
	``Far less agreement exists about the use of restraint and  
seclusion in any other situation,'' such as punishment or staff 
convenience, the report said. 
</P>
<P>
	``The random use of restraints cited by the GAO suggests bad  
luck, more than medical science, determines which patients end up 
restrained, secluded or even dead,'' said Sen. Joseph Lieberman, 
D-Conn. 
</P>
<P>
	The GAO said 240,000 people require either inpatient treatment  
in mental hospitals or residential treatment in centers or group 
homes each year. About 120,000 people with mental retardation lived 
in intermediate care facilities and 240,000 others lived in smaller 
residential settings in 1998. 
</P>
<P>
	No federal regulations governed the use of restraint and  
seclusion in those facilities until July 1999, when the Health Care 
Financing Administration put new restrictions on hospitals that 
received federal Medicare money. 
</P>
<P>
	``Although this is a positive step, people in residential  
treatment centers and group homes participating in the Medicaid 
Home and Community-Based Waiver program have limited federal 
protection,'' the GAO report said. ``While some states have 
regulations in place governing the use of restraint and seclusion, 
often these regulations do not apply to privately operated 
facilities.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``This is about protecting our loved ones from deadly  
restraint,'' said Rep. Rosa DeLauro, D-Conn. ``They should not fear 
for their lives -- and their families should not fear for their 
lives -- when they check into a hospital.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19991002.0070 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-02 13:50:13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Gordon's Crew Chief Sitting Duck </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	MARTINSVILLE, Va. (AP) -- Brian Whitesell is a sitting duck, and  
he knows it. 
</P>
<P>
	Whitesell, who replaced Ray Evernham as Jeff Gordon's crew chief  
Wednesday, knows if the Hendrick Motorsports team continues winning 
it will be assumed that Evernham left him a winning combination. 
And if the team loses, it will be because he couldn't match 
Evernham's ability. 
</P>
<P>
	``I'm not trying to replace Ray Evernham,'' said Whitesell, who  
was the hand-picked successor for the man who guided Gordon to 
three Winston Cup championship in the last four seasons. ``I just 
want to make sure the team performs.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Asked about the perception that he has been set up to fail by  
Evernham's surprising departure, Whitesell said, ``Is it unfair? 
No. It's my responsibility to get it done. 
</P>
<P>
	``We are basically still intact. What Ray has taught us, we are  
prepared to carry on.'' 
</P>
<P>
	So far, so good. Gordon qualified a solid fifth for Sunday's  
NAPA AutoCare 500 at Martinsville Speedway. 
</P>
<P>
	``That was a good start,'' said Whitesell, who at 35 is the same  
age as Evernham was when he came to the Hendrick team. ``It's what 
we wanted to accomplish -- a top five. Now we'd like to do the same 
on Sunday.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Gordon expressed confidence in Whitesell and the rest of the  
Rainbow Warriors crew. 
</P>
<P>
	``This is a great race team with a lot of depth,'' Gordon said.  
``I really don't feel like we should skip much of a beat.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Evernham was always the man talking on the radio with Gordon  
during the race. Now that duty falls to Whitesell, who has 
monitored those conversations over the years. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's going to be different,'' Gordon said. ``We miss him. If I  
had my choice, I'd love for him to be there. But I support him in 
wanting to do something else.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Evernham has said he will try to form his own Winston Cup team.  
Talk in the garage area has him doing that with the support of 
Chrysler, which is expected to return to Winston Cup racing with 
Dodge race cars in 2001. 
</P>
<P>
                            	 *------	 
</P>
<P>
	SECOND DAY LEADER: Hut Stricklin was the only driver who managed  
to qualify on Saturday for the Martinsville race. 
</P>
<P>
	Stricklin, one of only nine drivers who made qualifying attempts  
in the second round, turned a lap of 93.576 mph to take the 35th 
starting spot in the 43-car field. 
</P>
<P>
	Only the top 36 make the lineup on speed and all the other  
second-day qualifiers stood on their Friday laps. 
</P>
<P>
	Added to the lineup as provisional starters, based on team-owner  
points, were rookie Tony Stewart, seven-time Winston Cup champion 
Dale Earnhardt, Chad Little, Johnny Benson, rookie Elliott Sadler, 
Jerry Nadeau and Dave Marcis. 
</P>
<P>
	Sent home were Dick Trickle, Ron Hornaday, Tim Fedewa and Morgan  
Shepherd. 
</P>
<P>
                            	 *------	 
</P>
<P>
	THE PITS: Sunday will be the second test for the new pit road,  
which will have cars pitting all the way from the middle of turn 
four through the middle of turn one. 
</P>
<P>
	Martinsville officials decided to make the change, eliminating  
the backstretch pits, in the interests of competition. But the new, 
narrow road could cause one heck of a traffic jam. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's a one-lane pit road now,'' said Ted Musgrave, who will  
start second, alongside pole-winner Joe Nemechek, on Sunday. 
</P>
<P>
	``Now, as long as that pit road is, pit position is very  
important,'' Musgrave said. ``Joe is on the pole, so he picked the 
first pit stall. We picked further back in line, where there's an 
opening in front of us and a straight shot in and out of the pits. 
That will be an advantage in not getting blocked in. 
</P>
<P>
	``I sure wouldn't want to be in that very first pit stall (in  
turn four),'' he added. ``That's going to hurt whoever that is or 
anybody in that area.'' 
</P>
<P>
                            	 *------	 
</P>
<P>
	SPARK PLUGS: Darrell Waltrip, who will start 22nd on Sunday,  
leads all active drivers with 11 Martinsville wins ... Only 14 of 
92 Martinsville races have been won from the pole, but 75 have been 
won from the top 10 ... Posted awards for the race at NASCAR's 
smallest track are $1,930,531 ... Gordon has finished eighth or 
better, including two wins, in his last nine Martinsville starts. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
