<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19991002.0071 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-02 09:10:10 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> AP Top News at Noon EDT  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 *Saturday, Oct. 2, 1999    	

</P>
<P>
	Clinton Pushes Patients' Rights  
</P>
<P>
	PALO ALTO, Calif. (AP) -- Praising broad protections written into  
California's new health care reform law, President Clinton urged 
voters today to press Congress to ``do the same for every 
American'' as the House votes this week on a national patients' 
bill of rights. In his weekly radio address, Clinton decried as 
``simply unacceptable'' a provision in a Senate budget bill that 
effectively would take away the right to a timely appeal when a 
health plan denies coverage. He urged the House to reject the 
provision, which he said lawmakers are likely to do if their 
constituents speak up. 

</P>
<P>
	Ex-Student Radical Freed From Jail  
</P>
<P>
	FRAMINGHAM, Mass. (AP) -- Katherine Ann Power, the student  
radical who spent 23 years underground after taking part in an 
armed robbery that ended with the death of a police officer, was 
released from prison today. Power, 49, said nothing to reporters as 
she left MCI-Framingham, where she has spent the last six years. In 
a statement, Power said she ``will always carry my human 
responsibility for the sorrow my actions have caused.'' Power and 
four others robbed a Boston bank to fund radical efforts against 
the Vietnam war. She was waiting in the getaway car when another 
member of the group shot the officer in the back. 

</P>
<P>
	Kosovo Albanians Put Up Barricade  
</P>
<P>
	KOSOVO POLJE, Yugoslavia (AP) -- Dozens of ethnic Albanians threw  
up a barricade today in front of this Serb town's municipal 
building, vowing to stay until a nearby Serb roadblock was removed. 
The Albanians also returned to a previously erected roadblock on 
Kosovo's main road, which they had abandoned yesterday in line with 
a U.N.-brokered deal calling for both sides to dismantle their 
barricades. But the talks, in which the deal was made, broke down 
in the afternoon when the United Nations refused to give full 
control of one school in town to the Serbs. 

</P>
<P>
	Russia, U.S. Sign Nuclear Accord  
</P>
<P>
	MOSCOW (AP) -- The United States and Russia today agreed to  
cooperate in the monitoring and safeguarding of nuclear materials. 
The deal was signed by visiting Energy Secretary Bill Richardson 
and his Russian counterpart, Yevgeny Adamov, after the unveiling of 
a crisis situation center at the Russian Nuclear Power Ministry, 
the ITAR-Tass news agency said. The agreement envisages a Russian 
national program of registration, monitoring and protection of 
nuclear materials, including their transportation, ITAR-Tass said. 

</P>
<P>
	Japan Lifts Nuclear Plant Advisory  
</P>
<P>
	TOKAIMURA, Japan -- The Japanese government today lifted an  
evacuation order for more than 160 residents living near a 
uranium-processing plant that caused the nation's worst nuclear 
accident. Since the Thursday morning accident, which set off an 
atomic reaction and sent three workers to the hospital, people 
living in a 385-yard radius had been evacuated to a nearby 
community center. ``Safety has been confirmed,'' top government 
spokesman Hiromu Nonaka said in a nationally televised news 
conference. 

</P>
<P>
	Rebels Free Hostages in Thailand  
</P>
<P>
	BANGKOK, Thailand (AP) -- Five armed rebels who seized the  
Myanmar Embassy released dozens of hostages today and flew in a 
helicopter to the Thai-Myanmar border, where they were allowed to 
go free, Thailand's interior minister said. The pro-democracy 
rebels released all 38 hostages, and another 51 Myanmar citizens 
who had hidden inside the walled embassy compound were able to come 
out, said Interior Minister Sanan Kachornprasart. 

</P>
<P>
	Controversial NYC Art Exhibit Opens  
</P>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- ``Sensation,'' the controversial art exhibit  
that set New York on its ear even before it arrived, opened today 
at the Brooklyn Museum of Art amid cheers of First Amendment 
advocates and jeers of disgusted detractors. Visitors lined up this 
morning to get into the museum, and about three dozen protesters 
showed up, too. They included protesters from the conservative 
Catholic League and from animal rights groups. One demonstrator 
protesting Mayor Rudolph Giuliani's efforts to stop the show was 
arrested. 

</P>
<P>
	Athletes Back 'Doping Passport'  
</P>
<P>
	ATHENS, Greece (AP) -- Athletes should be ineligible to compete  
in future Olympics unless they carry a ``doping passport'' proving 
they have undergone regular out-of-competition drug tests, an 
Olympic athletes' group said today. The International Olympic 
Committee executive board, meanwhile, endorsed proposals for 15 
athletes to be appointed as members of a reformed IOC. The IOC 
athletes' commission met with the executive board today to push for 
a bigger role in the running of the Olympics. 

</P>
<P>
	AP NewsBrief by DAVID GOODMAN  
  	   	
</P>
