<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Ferret Helps Fix High-Tech Problem </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	PETERSON AIR FORCE BASE, Colo. (AP) -- The U.S. Space Command has  
millions of dollars worth of all the latest computers and other 
electronic gear, and plenty of highly trained employees. 
</P>
<P>
	But when it ran into a problem at its new Year 2000 missile  
warning center, the solution didn't come from an engineer, a 
computer wiz or a physicist. 
</P>
<P>
	Instead, Misty saved the day. Misty is a ferret, a four-legged,  
furry, inquisitive relative of minks. 
</P>
<P>
	To connect new computers at the center, wires had to be threaded  
through 40-foot-long, narrow conduits that already contained other 
wires. 
</P>
<P>
	The job would have driven a human loopy, but Lt. Col. Randy  
Blaisdell, who supervised the building of the center, volunteered 
Misty, his pet for six years. He recalled that ferrets had been 
used to pull wires through tight spaces in World War II-era 
airplanes. 
</P>
<P>
	Blaisdell tied a piece of yarn around the one-pound ferret's  
midsection. Misty dashed through the conduit, towing the yarn, and 
then the yarn was used to pull a wire. Misty made several trips and 
her work was done in an hour. 
</P>
<P>
	All it cost was a promise of strawberry Pop Tarts, Misty's  
favorite treat. 
</P>
<P>
	``She really enjoys going through the conduits,'' Blaisdell  
said. ``And she definitely works cheap.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19991002.0087 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-02 04:00:07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> weather </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> The Nation's Weather  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	Light to moderate showers fell in parts of the western Great  
Lakes and northern Plains today while skies were clear from the 
Northeast to the Gulf Coast. 
</P>
<P>
	The southern and central Plains were expected to stay dry today.  
Moisture behind a cold front entering the central Plains is 
forecast to bring freezing rain tonight from parts of northern 
Nebraska to the Dakotas and Minnesota, with snow in higher 
elevations. Some accumulations could total as much as 6 inches. 
</P>
<P>
	A cold front pushing through the Great Lakes is expected to drop  
temperatures into the 30s overnight. Partly cloudy skies were 
expected to develop ahead of the system in parts of New England. 
</P>
<P>
	In Florida, thunderstorms were expected to develop, then  
dissipate in the evening as temperatures drop. 
</P>
<P>
	The West is expected to remain mostly clear and dry as an upper  
level ridge builds in the Pacific Ocean. 
</P>
<P>
	Highs today were forecast in the 30s in the northern Plains; 40s  
and 50s in the western Great Lakes; 60s in the Northeast; 70s and 
80s in the West and Southwest; and 80s in the Southeast. 
</P>
<P>
	Extremes on Friday across the continental United States ranged  
from a high of 103 degrees in Palm Springs, Calif. to a low of 21 
at Craig, Colo. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19991002.0088 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-02 21:00:10 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> political </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Hatch, Keyes Address GOP Conference </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	GRAND TETON NATIONAL PARK, Wyo. (AP) -- Presidential candidates'  
demands for drastic tax reform drew applause and cheers during the 
Western States Republican Leadership Conference on Saturday. 
</P>
<P>
	``We have got to simplify our tax returns. And we've got to make  
it so we don't need the IRS any more,'' said Sen. Orrin Hatch, 
R-Utah. 
</P>
<P>
	Hatch came in second to no-show George W. Bush in a straw poll  
of nearly 500 paid participants at the conference. Bush received 34 
percent of the votes, organizers said, while Hatch got 29 percent 
and Steve Forbes 24 percent. 
</P>
<P>
	On taxes, Alan Keyes said the issue is neither that income taxes  
are too progressive nor that they should be flat. 
</P>
<P>
	``The problem with the income tax is that it's there,'' he said.  
</P>
<P>
	Although all the Republican presidential candidates were  
invited, only three attended the conference at Jackson Lake Lodge. 
</P>
<P>
	Forbes spoke Friday before heading to a Christian Coalition  
conference attended by George W. Bush, Elizabeth Dole and others. 
</P>
<P>
	Hatch described himself as the only Western candidate, a  
colleague and admirer of Ronald Reagan who would get tough on drugs 
and crime and rebuild the military. 
</P>
<P>
	``The fact of the matter is, we have a more dangerous world  
today than when we had two superpowers,'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	Hatch promised to support Western causes, such as preserving  
private land rights that he said environmentalists would like to 
take away. 
</P>
<P>
	``I've got to tell you, they're a rough bunch. And they don't  
have any conception of what it takes to run this country,'' he 
said. ``It's time we take it back from them.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Saving Social Security and Medicare, he said, will require ``a  
conservative president with guts.'' And parents should have the 
right ``to walk their children away from poor, bad schools.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Keyes warned of a dire ``moral crisis'' brought on by the  
Clinton presidency that is destroying the nation. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19991002.0089 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-02 13:34:51 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Ryder Loss Blamed on James  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	LONDON (AP) -- European Ryder Cup player Jean Van de Velde has  
blamed European captain Mark James for last weekend's stunning loss 
to the United States. 
</P>
<P>
	Instead of lashing out at the behavior of the American team and  
their fans, Van de Velde said it was ``morally wrong'' that three 
players were left on the sidelines by James until the singles 
competition on the final day. 
</P>
<P>
	``You don't make good use of nine players and put three in the  
bin,'' Van de Velde said in Saturday's The Daily Telegraph. 
</P>
<P>
	``Maybe I'm not the best player in the world, but I did finish  
ninth on the Ryder Cup points list, and if you qualify you should 
play,'' added Van de Velde, who blew a three-stroke lead on the 
72nd hole of this year's British Open. 
</P>
<P>
	Van de Velde said James did not speak to him after the match.  
</P>
<P>
	``I would expect him to come to me in the near future and talk  
about it,'' Van de Velde said. 
</P>
<P>
	Van de Velde, who spoke openly after he lost the British Open,  
said Europe lost the Ryder Cup because its top players were 
exhausted. 
</P>
<P>
	``Everyone has been focusing on the Americans' bad behavior,''  
he said. ``But to me the result had nothing to do with that. We 
lost because we asked too much of most of the guys and because we 
didn't put enough trust in three.'' 
</P>
<P>
	In addition to Van de Velde, Jarmo Sandelin and Andrew Coltart  
also sat out until the final day. 
</P>
<P>
	Van de Velde was beaten easily, 6 and 5, by Davis Love III in  
Sunday's singles. Sandelin and Coltart also lost their matches. 
</P>
<P>
	The Frenchman, a member of the European Tour Players' committee,  
said he would suggest that European players in future Ryder Cups 
play every day. 
</P>
<P>
	``I feel I haven't really taken part in the match. It has made  
me feel so bad.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
