<DOCNO> APW19991002.0090 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-02 12:10:18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Ruth Calls Big Shot in 1932 Series </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	Babe Ruth lived in his own little world, blithely oblivious to  
rules and regulations, anything that might have interfered with his 
carefree approach to life. Call it simply being Babe. 
</P>
<P>
	This occasionally caused problems for the defining figure of  
baseball's first 50 years. There was, for example, the matter of 
his called home run in the 1932 World Series, one of the great 
sports moments of the century. 
</P>
<P>
	Now, anybody who has ever tried to hit a baseball knows how  
difficult it is. It's even more complicated when the pitcher is 
angry. 
</P>
<P>
	Ruth never found this much of a problem. He had a lifetime  
batting average of .342 with 714 home runs. In his prime, he 
sometimes hit more home runs by himself than whole teams. He was 
convinced that he could do just about anything he wanted, whenever 
he wanted. 
</P>
<P>
	So, when the New York Yankees reached the 1932 World Series  
against the Chicago Cubs, he put that theory to the supreme test. 
In Game 3 of that Series, on Oct. 1, he got into an ultimate battle 
of one-upmanship with Cubs bench jockeys, a confrontation that 
concluded with the Babe standing at home plate, apparently 
predicting that he was about to hit one over the fence. 
</P>
<P>
	A called shot.  
</P>
<P>
	Right there, in the middle of a World Series game.  
</P>
<P>
	With a ballpark full of Cubs fans booing him.  
</P>
<P>
	And a dugout full of Cubs players needling him.  
</P>
<P>
	Sounds outrageous, doesn't it?  
</P>
<P>
	Ruth thought so, too.  
</P>
<P>
	``Nobody but a blankety-blank fool would have done what I did  
that day,'' he told writer John P. Carmichael. ``When I think of 
what an idiot I could have been if I had struck out. And I could 
have, too, just as well as not because I had made up my mind to 
swing at the next pitch if I could reach it with my bat.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The called shot had its origins in a minor league player  
transaction during the season when Chicago purchased shortstop Mark 
Koenig, who had played four full seasons and parts of two others in 
New York. 
</P>
<P>
	Koenig played brilliantly, batting .353 in 33 games. But the  
penurious Cubs thought the contribution was worth no more than a 
half-share of World Series money. Don't forget, there was a 
Depression going on. 
</P>
<P>
	Koenig was the Yankees shortstop in 1927 when Ruth electrified  
baseball by hitting 60 home runs. He still had plenty of friends in 
the New York dugout and when the Yankees decided he was being 
shortchanged, the seeds were planted for a dandy feud. 
</P>
<P>
	The Series opened in New York, and right from the start players  
from both benches were insulting each other. The loudest Cubs were 
pitchers Pat Malone, Burleigh Grimes and trainer Andy Lotshaw, who 
shouted at Ruth, ``If I had you, I'd hitch you to a wagon, you 
potbelly.'' 
</P>
<P>
	It had been a difficult season for the Babe. He missed about  
three weeks with a pulled muscle in his right thigh and there was 
an appendicitis scare in September when he was out again. 
</P>
<P>
	For the first time in seven years, he did not lead the league in  
homers, finishing with 41, well short of Jimmie Foxx's 58. He was 
not in the mood to be razzed, certainly not by some guy who dealt 
in liniment and adhesive tape instead of balls and strikes. 
</P>
<P>
	``I don't mind no ballplayers yellin' at me,'' he said. ``But  
the trainer cuttin' in, ... that made me sore.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Ruth gave the abuse right back to the Cubs. And on the  
scoreboard, where it counted, the Yankees dominated. They won the 
opener 12-6 with Ruth and Lou Gehrig homering. In Game 2, New York 
won again, 5-2. 
</P>
<P>
	With the Series moving to Chicago, Ruth now faced a hostile  
crowd as well as the Cubs bench. The abuse was nonstop and the Babe 
gave as good as he got. In the first inning, he hit a three-run 
homer on his first swing and chugged around the bases with a huge 
grin on his moon face. 
</P>
<P>
	By the fifth, the score was tied 4-4 and the taunting had  
reached a fever pitch. Charlie Root was on the mound for the Cubs 
and his first pitch was a called strike. Ruth, holding the bat with 
his left hand, raised his right as if to acknowledge strike one. 
</P>
<P>
	The next two pitches were balls, then another called strike.  
Again Ruth raised his right hand, for strike two. 
</P>
<P>
	A fan, Matt Kandle, filmed a home movie of Ruth's at-bat. The  
fuzzy first frame shows the slugger pointing, but it's not clear at 
what. It could be at Root. It could be at the Cubs dugout, which by 
this time was howling. Or it could be at the fence. 
</P>
<P>
	Ruth gave this account to Carmichael: ``I didn't exactly point  
to any one spot, like the flagpole. I just sort of waved to the 
whole fence, but that was foolish enough. 
</P>
<P>
	``I took two strikes and after each one I held up my finger and  
said, `That's one,' and `That's two.' Then's when I waved to the 
fence. 
</P>
<P>
	``I didn't point to any spot, but as long as I'd called the  
first two strikes on myself, I had to go through with it. It was 
dammed foolishness, but I just felt like doing it.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Ruth hit Root's next pitch into the bleachers and chortled as he  
circled the bases, clasping his hands over his head like a 
triumphant fighter. 
</P>
<P>
	``I just laughed to myself going around the bases,'' he said.  
``I was thinking to myself, `You lucky bum ... lucky, lucky.' '' 
</P>
<P>
	Did he really call his shot? Could he have been that audacious?  
</P>
<P>
	An air of mystery surrounded the event because only one writer,  
Joe Williams, sports editor of Scripps-Howard Newspapers, mentioned 
it the next day. Later, others picked up on it. 
</P>
<P>
	Those in the ballpark that day had divided opinions.  
</P>
<P>
	Root was angry at the suggestion that Ruth had shown him up that  
way. His reaction was pitcher-typical. ``If he had made a gesture 
like that, I'd have put one in his ear,'' he said cheerfully. 
</P>
<P>
	Catcher Gabby Hartnett said the Babe was gesturing to the Cubs  
bench, not pointing to the bleachers. 
</P>
<P>
	Gehrig, who followed Ruth's homer with one of his own, said,  
``What do you think of that big monkey? Calling his shot and 
getting away with it.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The debate never stopped and Ruth often was coy about it, adding  
to the mystery. There were times, as in the interview with 
Carmichael, when he took credit for the called shot, and other 
times when he was elusive. 
</P>
<P>
	In the end, though, that home run remains one of the most  
talked-about moments in World Series history. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19991002.0091 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-02 19:30:25 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Ripken Hopes To Return Next Year </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	BALTIMORE (AP) -- Cal Ripken returned to Camden Yards on Saturday  
for the first time since season-ending surgery nine days ago and 
said he hopes to resume baseball activities by the end of November. 
</P>
<P>
	``I'm pleasantly surprised. ... I don't want to get ahead of  
myself, but the plan is to spend four, maybe six weeks to let the 
soft tissue heal,'' said the Baltimore star, who underwent surgery 
to a nerve irritation in his lower back on Sept. 23 in Cleveland. 
</P>
<P>
	``I'll slowly start a general exercise program. Then I'll pick  
up a bat and a baseball, I would assume, maybe Dec. 1 or late 
November.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Ripken, speaking publicly for the first time since the  
procedure, said his decision was made with his offseason 
rehabilitation regimen in mind. 
</P>
<P>
	``That's not too far off my regular schedule,'' the third  
baseman said. ``I have a full offseason to recover.'' 
</P>
<P>
	By opting for surgery 11 days before the end of the season,  
Ripken temporarily halted his pursuit of 3,000 hits. He is nine 
hits shy of that plateau. 
</P>
<P>
	Ripken hit his 400th home run Sept. 2 and batted a career-high  
.340 in 86 games. 
</P>
<P>
	``It was a great year and it was a discouraging year,'' said  
Ripken. 
</P>
<P>
	Ripken's father, Cal Sr., died late in spring training. Later,  
the Orioles star went on the disabled list for the first two times 
in his career. 
</P>
<P>
	``Mentally, it was uplifting and also the worst,'' he added. ``I  
rediscovered a swing I hadn't had. ... I'd like to what would have 
happened if I had that swing over 650 at-bats.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Ripken left the Orioles after experiencing pain in his back  
Sept. 21 in Texas and traveled the next day to Cleveland, where Dr. 
Henry Bohlman performed the 2 1/2-hour procedure after Ripken briefly 
deliberated his options. 
</P>
<P>
	``Maybe I've been worn down. ... The fact that I'm walking  
around and feeling good are good indicators. I don't have a fear of 
trying it again. The only way you find out is to do it.'' 
</P>
<P>
	While his pain may be subsiding, Ripken has maintained a sense  
of humor through his ordeal. 
</P>
<P>
	``You want to see the scar?'' he asked reporters, pulling up his  
black warmup jersey to reveal a six-inch scar on the middle of his 
lower back, just above his waistline. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19991002.0092 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-02 13:34:51 </DATE_TIME>
