<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Mets In Control of Their Destiny </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Just one day ago, the New York Mets' playoff  
hopes were on life support following a disastrous 10-day stretch 
that saw them go from four games ahead in the wild-card chase to 
two games back. 
</P>
<P>
	One dramatic win and a little outside help later let the Mets  
take the field Saturday night against Pittsburgh in control of 
their playoff destiny. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's back in our hands again,'' Matt Franco said after  
Cincinnati lost to Milwaukee 10-6, bringing the Mets within a 
half-game of the wild-card lead with two games to play. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's amazing how you can go from out of it to back in it so  
suddenly.'' 
</P>
<P>
	All it took was a 3-2 win in 11 innings over the Pirates on  
Friday night -- New York's second victory in 10 games -- and losses 
by Houston and Cincinnati to bring the Mets within a game of the 
wild-card leaders. 
</P>
<P>
	The Reds' loss Saturday guaranteed that the Mets would have a  
chance to at least force a wild-card playoff on Sunday. That was 
quite a trip in less than 48 hours after a devastating 4-3, 
11-inning loss to Atlanta on Thursday night. 
</P>
<P>
	``You get hot, then you're not,'' manager Bobby Valentine said.  
``You can't stay hot. That's how this game is.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Fortunately for the Mets, the Reds did not stay hot, losing  
three straight games. Many of the Mets gathered early Saturday to 
follow the Reds' game. 
</P>
<P>
	When the game was unavailable on their satellite, a group of  
them gathered around a computer screen in manager Bobby Valentine's 
office, watching pitch-by-pitch updates come over the Internet. 
</P>
<P>
	That's baseball fever in the high-tech, wild-card age.  
</P>
<P>
	``I was doing a little managing, but mostly rooting,'' Valentine  
said. ``It's much more nerve-wrecking watching a game when you have 
no control.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Before taking the field, the Mets were gathered in their  
clubhouse watching the Astros finish off a 3-0 win over Los 
Angeles. 
</P>
<P>
	That meant there would be no one-game playoff Monday at Shea  
Stadium between the Mets and Astros. The Mets and Reds would have a 
one-game playoff in Cincinnati if they finish in a two-way tie. 
</P>
<P>
	If there is a three-way tie, New York is automatically in and  
the Reds and Astros play one game in Cincinnati to decide the NL 
Central champion -- the loser would be out of the playoffs because 
it would finish a half-game behind the Mets. 
</P>
<P>
	``You can play in a tough division and win more games than  
another team that wins their division and not make the playoffs,'' 
Valentine said defending the system. 
</P>
<P>
	``One of them happens to play another game. Being that we are  
the ones who benefit, then it's really fair. But when did we start 
dealing with what's fair?'' 
</P>
<P>
	If the Mets win twice and Cincinnati loses, New York is also in  
as the wild card. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's neat for baseball with all the different possibilities  
going into the last weekend,'' Valentine said. ``I'd rather have it 
neat for us.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Whatever happens, Valentine knows he probably needs a win  
Sunday. And he decided to stick with Orel Hershiser instead of 
using Al Leiter on three days' rest. 
</P>
<P>
	Valentine took Leiter out after seven innings on Wednesday to  
leave open that option, but with his lack of experience on short 
rest decided to stick with Hershiser. 
</P>
<P>
	``He's only done it once and that was in 1994 in May, not after  
200 innings,'' Valentine said. ``This is not the time to experiment 
with something you haven't done all year. Especially when we have a 
good option in a well-rested Orel.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
