<HEADLINE> Ex N.J. Police Chief Sues </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	CHERRY HILL, N.J. (AP) -- A State Police superintendent who was  
fired for saying minorities were more likely to be involved in 
cocaine and marijuana trafficking is suing the state for 
discrimination. 
</P>
<P>
	Carl Williams' lawsuit, filed Friday, seeks more than $21  
million. 
</P>
<P>
	It claims that Gov. Christine Todd Whitman and former Attorney  
General Peter Verniero, now a state Supreme Court justice, fired 
Williams in February ``because of his status as a white male, age 
59, in order to replace him with a black superintendent.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``The governor and the attorney general hung me out to dry,''  
Williams said Saturday from his attorney's office. 
</P>
<P>
	Spokesmen for the governor and the attorney general's office  
said they had not seen the lawsuit and declined to comment on it. 
</P>
<P>
	``We don't, as a rule, comment on litigation, no matter how  
baseless or pathetic it is,'' Whitman spokesman Peter McDonough 
said. 
</P>
<P>
	One day before Williams' lawsuit was filed, FBI agent Carson  
Dunbar was confirmed by the state Senate as his replacement. 
</P>
<P>
	The controversy stemmed from an interview Williams gave the  
Star-Ledger of Newark in which the 35-year veteran trooper 
discussed drug arrests and why certain drivers are pulled over. 
</P>
<P>
	He denied that racial profiling was involved and said statistics  
showing that 75 percent of people arrested on the New Jersey 
Turnpike over a two-month period were minorities was not unexpected 
because minorities were more likely to be involved in cocaine and 
marijuana trafficking. Eighty-three percent of the people arrested 
in that same period were convicted, he said. 
</P>
<P>
	The Black Ministers Council of New Jersey was outraged and  
demanded he be fired. 
</P>
<P>
	Williams defended his comments again on Saturday.  
</P>
<P>
	``I told the truth then, I'd tell the truth now,'' he said.  
</P>
<P>
	Since Williams' firing, two reports from the attorney general's  
office have acknowledged racial profiling by the State Police and 
detailed changes to end it. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
