<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Man Proposes to Woman on Death Row </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	PHOENIX (AP) -- The only woman on death row in Arizona plans to  
marry a former German neo-Nazi convicted in the 1992 fire bombing 
of a Berlin cafe. 
</P>
<P>
	Officials with the Arizona Department of Corrections said a  
German national named Ingo Hasselbach had proposed to Debra Milke 
in a letter. 
</P>
<P>
	The two have never met or even spoken by phone.  
</P>
<P>
	Department spokeswoman Camilla Strongin said a signature on  
faxes sent to the prison requesting information about marrying 
Milke match the signature of a German journalist by the same name 
who requested an interview with Milke last year but was denied. 
</P>
<P>
	Hasselbach, reached Saturday at a home in Goodyear, about 20  
miles west of Phoenix, confirmed his interest in marrying Milke and 
his conviction for the 1992 cafe attack. 
</P>
<P>
	``I love her,'' he said. ``I don't think it's crazy. I feel she  
is an innocent woman. I feel she will be freed someday. That's the 
hope I have.'' 
</P>
<P>
	He began writing her last year, and around December they began  
to express feelings for each other. 
</P>
<P>
	``It took time to fall in love with her,'' he said.  
</P>
<P>
	He proposed in writing about four months ago. She said yes about  
a month ago. But she refuses to see him because she doesn't want to 
endure the strip-searches and other security precautions that come 
with visits. 
</P>
<P>
	The 32-year-old journalist, who wrote ``Fuhrer-Ex: Memoirs of a  
Former Neo-Nazi'' after cutting ties with the extremist group in 
1993, was credited with founding East Germany's first neo-Nazi 
party. 
</P>
<P>
	Milke, 35, was convicted of ordering a man to kill her  
4-year-old son in 1989 for a share of a $5,000 life insurance 
policy she had taken out on the boy. 
</P>
<P>
	She spends 23 hours a day in her cell waiting for her appeal.  
</P>
<P>
	Strongin said Milke had applied for permission to marry but both  
bride and groom still need to complete their marriage applications 
and return all the necessary documents. 
</P>
<P>
	Once the documents are in, prison officials will have 70 days to  
approve or deny the marriage. Even if they approve it, prison rules 
prohibit overnight conjugal visits. 
</P>
<P>
	``In many cases, as soon as the ceremony is completed and the 'I  
do's' are said, the inmate goes back to his cell and the spouse 
goes home,'' said Michael Linderman, a chaplain at the Arizona 
Prison Complex in Perryville, where Milke is behind bars. 
</P>
<P>
	Hasselbach said he left the neo-Nazi lifestyle after a 1992  
arson attack near Hamburg that killed a grandmother and two young 
girls. His book was one of the most forthcoming accounts of the 
neo-Nazi lifestyle, telling of bored youths drinking beer and 
attacking foreigners for sport. 
</P>
<P>
	He has been in Arizona for several weeks and is working to get  
Milke's conviction overturned. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
