<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Garciaparra's Right Wrist Bruised </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WORCESTER, Mass. (AP) -- American League batting leader Nomar  
Garciaparra should be ready when the Boston Red Sox start the 
playoffs Wednesday after learning his right wrist is bruised and 
not broken. 
</P>
<P>
	Garciaparra, who was hit by a pitch Sept. 25 against the  
Baltimore Orioles, was examined Friday by Red Sox team physician 
Arthur Pappas at the University of Massachusetts Medical Center in 
Worcester. 
</P>
<P>
	``The bone looks fine,'' Pappas said, ``but there is a tendon  
that travels under the bone that is bruised and that tendon is 
swollen.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Garciaparra left the team before Thursday night's game in  
Chicago, where he hit a two-run homer the night before when Boston 
clinched a wild-card berth. 
</P>
<P>
	There was a chance he would miss the entire three-game series in  
Baltimore that ends the regular season. Red Sox manager Jimy 
Williams said he wasn't concerned if that happened. 
</P>
<P>
	``We still have that workout day Tuesday which will allow him to  
evaluate himself,'' Williams said. 
</P>
<P>
	The Red Sox begin the best-of-5 division series Wednesday at  
Cleveland or Texas, whichever has a better record. 
</P>
<P>
	Garciaparra, who is batting .357, had asked to return home to be  
examined. 
</P>
<P>
	``It alleviates the concern that (he) had,'' Williams said. ``It  
was a good suggestion by Nomar to go back to Boston.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
