<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-02 11:00:17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> political </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Bradley: Campaign Starts Growing </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	REDFIELD, Iowa (AP) -- Former New Jersey Sen. Bill Bradley said  
his bid for the Democratic presidential nomination is ``beginning 
to grow'' as voters begin to draw distinctions between him and Vice 
President Al Gore. 
</P>
<P>
	``People say we have momentum, but I say no. We just have a  
little traction,'' Bradley said. ``We want momentum in January.'' 
</P>
<P>
	In visits to a rural clinic and American Legion post at this  
central Iowa town west of Des Moines, Bradley focused on his 
just-unveiled health-care proposal. 
</P>
<P>
	His campaign has begun to get new attention because of  
increasing signs that he is narrowing the gap with Gore, who until 
recently was assumed to have a lock on the nomination. Polls have 
shown Bradley within striking distance in Iowa, where precinct 
caucuses launch the nominating season early next year. 
</P>
<P>
	While conceding he's picked up steam, Bradley is working hard to  
lower expectations. Meeting with reporters, he noted that Gore has 
the full weight of the White House at his disposal. 
</P>
<P>
	``If you have the president of the United States right by your  
side, willing to help you every step of the way, you have 
entrenched powers in the Democratic National Committee, you arrive 
on Air Force Two and you are ahead nationally,'' he said. ``To me 
that's the favorite.'' 
</P>
<P>
	But that also works the other way. As vice president, Gore must  
campaign with a large entourage and a security shield, while 
Bradley can run a much lower-keyed and more grass-roots effort. 
Saturday's swing underscored that difference. 
</P>
<P>
	Bradley sat with a handful of people at a rural health clinic to  
talk about health care and spoke to 65 folks at a down-home 
breakfast. 
</P>
<P>
	``I think that people are beginning to learn more about how I'm  
running the campaign, respecting the voters, reaching out to 
people, telling them what I believe. I think that it's beginning to 
grow,'' Bradley said. 
</P>
<P>
	``People are looking for politicians to lead from their core  
convictions.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
