<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Glance at New Supreme Court Cases </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	Some other cases to be decided by the Supreme Court in its  
1999-2000 term: 
</P>
<P>
	--Can patients sue and collect damages from health-maintenance  
organizations (HMOs) on the theory that financial bonuses offered 
to doctors who keep costs down can deprive them of adequate care? A 
federal appeals court said yes in an Illinois case. 
</P>
<P>
	--May states block release of police records and other government  
documents to those who would sell the information, even when the 
records routinely are released to the news media? A federal appeals 
court said no in a California case. 
</P>
<P>
	--Can Hawaii limit by their race the voters who elect a  
nine-member board that oversees a program benefiting only residents 
of Hawaiian blood? A federal appeals court said yes. 
</P>
<P>
	--May police chase, stop and question someone for running away  
after seeing them? The Illinois Supreme Court said no. 
</P>
<P>
	--Can public universities use mandatory student activity fees to  
subsidize campus groups that pursue political goals. A federal 
appeals court said no in a University of Wisconsin case. 
</P>
<P>
	--Does a federal law aimed at protecting children from glimpses  
and earfuls of sex-oriented material on inadequately scrambled 
cable TV channels violate cable operators' free-speech rights? A 
federal judge in Delaware said yes. 
</P>
<P>
	--Can states set rules for staffing and operation of oceangoing  
oil tankers even though national and international standards are in 
place? A federal appeals court said yes in a case from Washington 
state. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
