<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Yankees' Hernandez To Pitch First </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	ST. PETERSBURG, Fla. (AP) -- Orlando Hernandez, and not Roger  
Clemens, will start Game 1 of the AL playoffs for the New York 
Yankees. 
</P>
<P>
	Andy Pettitte will pitch Game 2, followed by Roger Clemens in  
Game 3 on the road. David Cone will start the fourth game, if 
necessary. 
</P>
<P>
	Manager Joe Torre announced his rotation for the best-of-5 first  
round before Saturday's game against Tampa Bay. 
</P>
<P>
	It's still uncertain whether the World Series champions will  
face Cleveland or Texas when the playoffs begin Tuesday night at 
Yankee Stadium. 
</P>
<P>
	Also unknown was whether Hideki Irabu, who went 11-7 with a 4.89  
ERA as the Yankees' No. 5 starter, will be included on the 
postseason roster. Torre said he will release the 25-man squad on 
Monday. 
</P>
<P>
	Torre said there was no one main reason why he picked ``El  
Duque'' over Clemens, a five-time Cy Young Award winner. He called 
Hernandez the Yankees' most consistent starter this season. 
</P>
<P>
	``They all can't pitch on one day,'' Torre said. ``I could have  
put the names into a hat.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Hernandez, who won the pivotal fourth game of the 1998 ALCS  
against Cleveland after not pitching for two weeks, is 17-9 with a 
4.12 ERA. 
</P>
<P>
	``For me, it was a big surprise because of the pitching staff we  
have here,'' Hernandez said through a translator. ``I'm pretty 
happy, pretty excited.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``I'm not afraid because I'm positive in the way I approach the  
game. The pressure is there, but I'm not afraid. The most important 
thing is to win the whole thing.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Hernandez joined the Yankees last season and won his postseason  
starts against Cleveland in the ALCS and San Diego in the World 
Series. 
</P>
<P>
	Clemens was expected to become the staff ace after he was  
acquired for David Wells in a four-player trade with Toronto during 
spring training. The right-hander has struggled, going 14-10 with a 
4.60 ERA. 
</P>
<P>
	Asked if he was disappointed at not starting the opener, Clemens  
said: ``No, not at all.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``It could have gone either way. We have the luxury of having  
four guys that can be a No. 1 guy at anytime. We're all excited for 
him.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Clemens has reported being too strong when he has pitched with  
extra days off. His Game 4 start will take place four days after 
his normal spot. 
</P>
<P>
	``We'll have to work backwards from that day,'' Clemens said.  
``I'll probably throw a couple extra long bullpen session.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The set-up does give the Yankees' two veterans pitchers for the  
games away from Yankee Stadium. 
</P>
<P>
	``I don't think Joe could go wrong,'' Cone said. ``How many  
teams have Roger Clemens and me in Games 3 and 4.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19991002.0108 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-02 12:40:19 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> political </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Gore Employee May Have Misused Fund </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Tony Coelho, Vice President Al Gore's campaign  
manager, approved questionable contractor payments, hired his niece 
for a job and may have stuck the government with repayment of a 
$300,000 personal loan while directing the U.S. pavilion at the 
1998 world's fair in Portugal, State Department investigators 
found. 
</P>
<P>
	Their report said Coelho and his staff also misused donated  
airline tickets, hired two stepsons of the U.S. ambassador to 
Portugal and had the government reimburse $26,000 in expenses to a 
consultant who worked in Coelho's New York City office. Coelho's 
rental of a chauffeur-driven Mercedes ``was especially 
troublesome'' because the cost exceeded a $500 ceiling while a 
fleet of six vans for the pavilion were under used. 
</P>
<P>
	The inspector general's report was released by the Center for  
Public Integrity, a nonprofit organization that tracks government 
fraud, waste and abuse and ethical conflicts involving public 
officials. 
</P>
<P>
	The center said Coelho's actions may have violated federal laws  
governing use of federal funds for international expositions. 
</P>
<P>
	A Gore spokesman, Chris Lehane, declined immediate comment on  
Saturday. 
</P>
<P>
	The allegations surfaced at a difficult time for the Gore  
campaign. Reeling from Democratic presidential challenger Bill 
Bradley's surge in the polls and fundraising, Gore several days ago 
shook up his campaign and moved it to Tennessee. 
</P>
<P>
	Coelho, then House Democratic whip, left Congress in 1989 amid  
questions about his personal financial dealings. A legendary fund 
raiser, Coelho once headed his party's congressional money-raising 
operation. 
</P>
<P>
	Coelho was appointed U.S. commissioner general for the world's  
fair in Lisbon in June 1996, with responsibility for fund raising, 
as well as the design, fabrication and operation of the U.S. 
pavilion. The expo was estimated to cost $8 million, but the figure 
jumped to $9.8 million and ``will likely cost more'' because of 
pending lawsuits, the inspector general said. 
</P>
<P>
	Federal law says government funds should not be spent unless  
``expressly authorized and appropriated'' for pavilions at the 
international fair. The report said no authorization was granted 
for Expo 98, ``yet U.S. government funds accounted for over 80 
percent of the total U.S. pavilion funding...'' The report 
concluded that the United States Information Agency ``may have 
violated the spirit, if not the letter'' of that law. 
</P>
<P>
	That agency, the report said, turned over control of the  
operation to Coelho who, the Center for Public Integrity reported, 
lived in an $18,000-a-month luxury apartment billed to the USIA and 
used free donated airline tickets. 
</P>
<P>
	The inspector general said Coelho obtained a personal loan of  
$300,000 from a Portuguese bank so that a private foundation could 
construct a memorial wall in the shape of a wave. 
</P>
<P>
	The loan was listed on pavilion records as a liability and the  
foundation hadn't made any payments as of December 1998. The U.S. 
government could be obligated to pay for the sculpture, the report 
said. 
</P>
<P>
	The report and further information developed by the center said  
that Coelho and his staff: 
</P>
<P>
	--Directed the USIA to reimburse a New York contractor $26,000  
even though officials ``could not find a legal basis'' for expenses 
such as travel, office space and relocation. The contractor was 
project manager for the pavilion. Other ``questionable payments'' 
initiated by Coelho included dinner for Portuguese guides, laundry 
services, the luxury apartment, and a dry-run reception that cost 
$294 for food and flowers. 
</P>
<P>
	--Hired his niece, Debra Coelho, in violation of USIA  
regulations, at $2,500 a month as an assistant to his deputy. He 
also hired two stepsons of Gerald McGowan, the U.S. ambassador to 
Portugal, at inflated salaries. One stepson received $2,700 a month 
and the other $3,200 a month. The contract ``did not identify any 
duties'' for McGowan's stepsons, the IG said. 
</P>
<P>
	--Did not ``adequately manage and control'' use of airline  
tickets, hotel accommodations and other lodging, free Expo tickets, 
motor vehicles, computers and VIP gifts. 
</P>
<P>
	Elaborating on the IG's report, the center reported that Coelho  
also was involved in business ventures in Portugal with at least 
three corporate underwriters of the U.S. Pavilion. Ethics rules 
prohibit special government employees from working on matters that 
would affect their financial interests. 
</P>
<P>
	The center also described Coelho's efforts to gain public  
funding after private fund raising failed. 
</P>
<P>
	It said Coelho first secured support of a friend, then-Navy  
Secretary John Dalton. A House-Senate conference report strongly 
suggested that the service participate as a sponsor of the U.S. 
exhibit on ocean research and technology. 
</P>
<P>
	Coelho then worked out a pledge from the National Institute of  
Environmental Health Sciences. As in the Navy's case, a paragraph 
in a conference report urged NIEHS ``to lend its expertise and 
provide technical assistance'' to the exposition. 
</P>
<P>
	Shortly before the Expo opened, the IG said the two agencies --  
armed with the legislative encouragement -- kicked in some $6.5 
million, or 82 percent of the funding. 
</P>
<P>
	Samuel Wilson, the institute's deputy director, said the agency  
originally wanted to contribute $500,000 -- not the $4 million 
donated. 
</P>
<P>
	``I don't know the origin of the idea of our involvement,''  
Wilson told the center. ``It's safe to say it wasn't an 
institute-developed idea.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
