<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Schott Hands Over Control of Reds </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	CINCINNATI (AP) -- Marge Schott said she wouldn't change anything  
about the way she ran the Cincinnati Reds as controlling partner 
for 15 years. 
</P>
<P>
	``I don't know what I would have done differently, except for  
stood up and fought with the boys a little more,'' Schott, 71, said 
in a telephone interview Friday after completing a $67 million deal 
to pass control of the Reds to their new chief executive officer, 
Carl Lindner. 
</P>
<P>
	She said she still enjoys seeing fans, especially children, at  
her front-row box seat in Cinergy Field. She plans to keep the box 
seat and wants to stay involved in the annual parade that marks 
baseball's opening day in Cincinnati. 
</P>
<P>
	``Baseball's history in this country,'' Schott said. ``The fans  
are the most important thing. It's nothing without the fans.'' 
</P>
<P>
	During her time in charge of the sport's oldest professional  
team, baseball officials suspended and scolded the feisty 
businesswoman for making remarks that offended minorities and 
women. 
</P>
<P>
	She offended several Reds players and employees, including a  
former team controller who sued her. But she said they all are part 
of fond memories. 
</P>
<P>
	``I always cared about my people who work for me,'' she said.  
``The Reds have been a very dear thing to me.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Schott, a Cincinnati auto dealer, became a limited partner of  
the team in 1981, bought the controlling share in 1984 and was in 
charge when the Reds won the 1990 World Series. She said selling 
the Reds while the team is in contention for the playoffs is 
particularly difficult. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's a sad day. Yes, it is, honey. I don't like to sell  
things. I'm a keeper, not a seller,'' she said. 
</P>
<P>
	``I was very much hands-on. I did try and bring some good  
players in and everything.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Asked what she plans to do next, she replied, ``I don't know,  
honey.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Baseball's owners approved the sale on Sept. 15, clearing the  
way for the official closing of the deal Friday. 
</P>
<P>
	Lindner, who has known Schott for a number of years, said she  
accomplished many things as managing partner. 
</P>
<P>
	``She has always kept the fans first in her mind,'' Lindner  
said. ``For that, all of Cincinnati should thank her and join me in 
wishing her the very best.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Schott remains a limited partner, holding one of the Reds' 13  
ownership shares. The other partners are Cincinnati businessman 
George L. Strike; Wall Street money manager William Reik Jr.; 
Multimedia of Cincinnati Inc., a subsidiary of Gannett Co. Inc.; 
the Louise Nippert Trust, the Carl A. Kroch Trust and the 
Lindner-controlled Great American Insurance Co. 
</P>
<P>
	John Allen, installed by baseball to run the team's daily  
operations while Schott was suspended, remains the team's managing 
executive. 




  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
