<CATEGORY> international </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Ecuador Farmers Unfazed by Volcano </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	LLOA, Ecuador (AP) -- For the past year, the Guagua Pichincha  
volcano has menaced the small villages and dairy farms on its upper 
slopes. 
</P>
<P>
	But when authorities announced this week that an eruption could  
be just days away and warned villagers to get out, many refused. 
How could they leave behind their prized dairy cows, their only 
source of income? 
</P>
<P>
	``We don't have jobs, just our cows. They're all we have,''  
60-year-old Enriqueta Maygua explained in anguish as she milked one 
of her 10 cows under the volcano's shadow. 
</P>
<P>
	Her graying hair pulled into a long braid down her back, Maygua  
told how the villagers of Lloa, just outside Quito, used to work as 
``huasipungueros'' -- Quechua for ``sharecroppers'' -- on a sprawling 
hacienda. Land reform in 1973 broke it up and distributed small 
plots of land to the estate's workers. 
</P>
<P>
	Talking about how much it meant to the villagers to become  
property owners themselves, she said, ``If we don't milk our cows, 
they will become ill and soon die, and we will have nothing.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Lloa's farmers were relieved when seismic activity in the  
volcano waned Friday. But scientists warned that the 15,840-foot 
mountain may be gathering strength for renewed activity. 
</P>
<P>
	Officials say Quito's 1.4 million inhabitants are not exposed to  
lava flows, since the volcano's crater faces away from the city and 
another peak of the mountain stands as a natural barrier. 
</P>
<P>
	But authorities warn that heavy ash from an eruption mixed with  
rain could cause mudslides in Quito neighborhoods built high up on 
the eastern slopes of Pichincha. 
</P>
<P>
	And villages located on the southern, western and northern  
slopes of the mountain could be directly threatened by lava flows. 
Officials say Lloa -- just 3,600 feet below Pichincha's active peak 
-- is the most exposed. 
</P>
<P>
	Located amid green pastures and yellow fields of barley on  
Pichincha's southern slope, Lloa is a prosperous village of 650 
residents with concrete-block homes and clean streets. About 2,200 
more people live in outlying hamlets and isolated farm houses. 
</P>
<P>
	Army troops moved into town Tuesday and urged people to evacuate  
to Quito. Many did, especially women with small children, moving 
into the shelters or into homes of relatives. 
</P>
<P>
	But at least 150 people have stayed in Lloa to look after the  
community's farm animals. Hundreds more are believed to be hanging 
on in outlying hamlets, said Abraham Viracucha, 53, president of 
Lloa's governing board. 
</P>
<P>
	``Women who have gone to Quito to stay in shelters with their  
children return early each day to help milk cows,'' Viracucha said, 
standing in a pasture surrounded by villagers who had herded cows 
together to be milked. 
</P>
<P>
	Viracucha says the area's poor farmers have 1,800 to 2,000 dairy  
cows, most of them still pasturing high up on the slopes of the 
volcano. 
</P>
<P>
	A government-run experimental farm with 2,500 head of sheep is  
allowing villagers to keep 350 cows in pastures lower down on the 
slopes, on a plateau better situated to escape the flow of lava. 
</P>
<P>
	But a worried Viracucha says the farm's administrators have  
refused to allow more cattle to be kept on the farm even though 
there is sufficient pasture. 
</P>
<P>
	A cousin, Marcia Viracucha, 37, owns a small storefront grocery  
a block from the village plaza. Hers is the only shop that is not 
locked and boarded up. 
</P>
<P>
	Asked why she had not left when soldiers urged her to evacuate,  
she shrugged and said, ``Who knows when one is going to die. It's 
in God's hands.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
