<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-02 15:40:13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Orioles Manager's Future Uncertain </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	BALTIMORE (AP) -- For Ray Miller, the writing is on the warehouse  
wall at Camden Yards: In all likelihood, he will be fired as 
manager of the Baltimore Orioles soon after the season ends Sunday. 
</P>
<P>
	But Miller said Saturday that he has absolutely no idea about  
his future. 
</P>
<P>
	Despite carrying one of the highest payrolls in baseball over  
the past two years, the Orioles have endured two straight losing 
seasons under Miller's direction. This, after advancing to the 
American League championship series in each of the previous two 
seasons. 
</P>
<P>
	According to the terms of Miller's contract, the Orioles have 72  
hours after Sunday's finale to decide whether to retain him. He 
expects to learn his fate during a meeting with owner Peter 
Angelos. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's the club option. Either it will be taken or it won't,''  
he said Saturday. ``I've talked to the owner quite a bit this week. 
It's been amicable and we've talked about a lot of things. I don't 
know what's going to happen. I'll talk to him probably Monday and 
find out.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Saturday afternoon, Miller was more concerned with getting the  
Orioles by the final two games without a host of injured players. 
After finding emergency replacements for injured starting pitchers 
Friday and Saturday, he learned that Sunday's scheduled starter, 
Sidney Ponson, can't pitch because of a sore shoulder. 
</P>
<P>
	It's been that kind of season. First baseman Will Clark, third  
baseman Cal Ripken and second baseman Delino DeShields all had 
multiple stints on this disabled list. Pitchers Mike Mussina, 
Arthur Rhodes and Scott Kamieniecki were lost for extended periods 
of time. 
</P>
<P>
	The pitching was horrid during the first half of the season,  
dooming Baltimore to a 36-51 record at the All-Star break. A 
sparkling second half, highlighted by a 13-game winning streak in 
September, has given Miller a spark of hope that he might be around 
to guide a younger team in 2000. 
</P>
<P>
	``I've been very proud of this club. This club should have  
folded three times this year, absolutely folded,'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	If nothing else, the surge convinced Miller that he maintained  
the respect of a club comprised heavily of veterans with sizable 
contracts. 
</P>
<P>
	``I've never had any problem with anybody out here, other than  
the time with Albert (Belle) in Florida,'' Miller said, referring 
to an argument with Belle after the manager removed him in a 
double-switch. 
</P>
<P>
	``I've never had anybody (complaining) because they're not in  
the lineup or want to play more,'' Miller contended. ``I try to do 
the best I can to talk to a guy when he's struggling.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Baltimore fans, he said, have been behind him despite the  
Orioles' fourth-place finish in the AL East. 
</P>
<P>
	``The thing I've been most proud of is the fan response has been  
great for me,'' he said. ``My mail's been great, and I've only been 
booed two or three times at length, and most of the times it's been 
when I've gone out to pull somebody and they want him to stay in. 
They don't the guy's got 130 pitches or whatever.'' 
</P>
<P>
	It's easy to cite injuries, bad pitching and poor chemistry for  
the Orioles' woes. But Miller knows where the blame ultimately 
lies. 
</P>
<P>
	``Somebody has to be responsible, so if you're the guy, I guess  
you've got to be responsible,'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	That may be what Angelos tells him Monday. Either way, Miller  
has already thought about life after managing. 
</P>
<P>
	``I wouldn't say I'm done (with baseball), but I'm not going to  
go looking for a job,'' he said. ``This is where I wanted to be, 
this is where I'd like to stay. If it doesn't work out, I'm going 
to do some normal things. I've been doing this since 1963.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
