<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> AP Top News at 5 a.m. EDT  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 *Saturday, Oct. 2, 1999    	

</P>
<P>
	Rebels Appear To Have Freed Hostages  
</P>
<P>
	BANGKOK, Thailand (AP) -- Some 40 diplomats and foreigners who  
were taken hostage by rebels at the Myanmar Embassy in Bangkok 
appear to have been released today, police said. However, a full 
accounting of the hostages was not available from authorities. 
Meanwhile, a helicopter carrying rebels who seized the embassy on 
Friday flew out of Bangkok with two senior Thai officials. The 
rebels had earlier had demanded to be flown to the Thai-Myanmar 
border, officials said. Interior Minister Sanan Kachornprasart said 
Deputy Foreign Minister Sukhumbhand Paribatra and a senior refugee 
official, Chaiyapruek Sawaengcharoen, had volunteered to take the 
place of the hostages and fly with the rebels. 

</P>
<P>
	Workers Confirm Bodies in E.Timor  
</P>
<P>
	DILI, East Timor (AP) -- Faced with daunting challenges, U.N.  
forensics experts are preparing to investigate alleged atrocities 
in East Timor, despite Indonesia's complaints that it should be 
allowed to conduct its own probe. There is no police force or 
justice system to hold onto suspects, the rainy season is looming, 
and Indonesia's unwillingness to cooperate will further complicate 
matters. Despite fears that hundreds, maybe thousands of people 
were killed during a rampage by anti-independence militias, 
evidence of possible war crimes has been scarce so far. 
Peacekeepers today indicated they had found 13 more bodies near the 
capital's airport only to issue a clarification later that they 
were confirming the earlier discovery along with three new bodies. 

</P>
<P>
	Study: Race Has Powerful Role in U.S.  
</P>
<P>
	BOSTON (AP) -- Blacks still end up at the bottom of the pack when  
it comes to opportunities ranging from jobs to housing, according 
to a new study that indicates race continues to play an enormous 
role in the success of Americans. Fifty researchers studied the 
cities of Atlanta, Boston, Detroit and Los Angeles and found that 
race is deeply entrenched in the country's cultural landscape -- 
perhaps even more than many Americans realize or are willing to 
admit. 

</P>
<P>
	Cooler Weather To Help Firefighters  
</P>
<P>
	CORONA, Calif. (AP) -- Firefighters surrounded a blaze that  
destroyed one home and threatened hundreds more, while cooler 
temperatures elsewhere became an ally in knocking down blazes that 
scorched tens of thousands of acres. ``All evacuations have been 
canceled and all evacuation centers closed,'' Becky Luther, a 
California Department of Forestry-Riverside County fire 
spokeswoman, said Friday as firefighters were encircled the 
440-acre Corona fire. Firefighters made some progress against two 
fires in San Diego County that had burned close to 3,000 acres. 

</P>
<P>
	U.S. Probe Welcomed in Korea  
</P>
<P>
	SEOUL, South Korea (AP) -- South Korean demonstrators held a  
two-hour rally and welcomed a U.S. promise to investigate 
allegations American forces killed several hundred refugees with 
machine-gun fire at the start of the Korean War. ``We throw up both 
of our hands to welcome the U.S. decision,'' said Chung Eun-yong, 
spokesman for a group of aging South Koreans who say they survived 
the alleged killings at No Gun Ri in July 1950. During a peaceful 
two-hour rally yesterday in front of the U.S. 8th Army headquarters 
in Seoul, dozens of activists praised Washington's decision to 
formally review the No Gun Ri case. 

</P>
<P>
	Milosevic Facing Heat from Opponents  
</P>
<P>
	BELGRADE, Yugoslavia (AP) -- Slobodan Milosevic's pro-democracy  
opponents are calling for more protests against the Yugoslav 
president, defying possible legal action against the opposition 
leaders and a growing government crackdown. The leaders of daily 
demonstrations demanding Milosevic's ouster announced another 
protest march toward Belgrade's main hospital today in support of 
dozens of opposition protesters injured in two police interventions 
against the protesters earlier this week. Signaling further 
crackdown, a government-controlled public prosecutor yesterday 
demanded an investigation into the clashes between the police and 
the demonstrators. 

</P>
<P>
	Japan Remains Wary on Nuclear Accident  
</P>
<P>
	TOKAIMURA, Japan (AP) -- Recovering from its worst nuclear  
accident ever, the Japanese government yesterday lifted an advisory 
that had urged residents near a hobbled uranium reprocessing plant 
to stay home and shut their windows. But even as officials at the 
plant northeast of Tokyo said danger from radiation released 
Thursday was subsiding, fears persisted that people near the 
Tokaimura facility may suffer long-term effects from the accident. 

</P>
<P>
	Rockets To Trade Pippen to Portland  
</P>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Scottie Pippen is about to be traded, but not to  
the team he wanted -- the Los Angeles Lakers. In a six-for-one deal 
expected to be announced today, Pippen will be traded from the 
Houston Rockets to the Portland Trail Blazers, The Associated Press 
learned. The deal, first reported earlier this week by media 
outlets in Houston and Portland, will send Kelvin Cato, Stacey 
Augmon, Walt Williams, Ed Gray, Brian Shaw and Carlos Rogers to 
Houston. 


</P>
<P>
	AP NewsBrief by BRADLEY BROOKS  
  	   	
</P>
