<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> S. Korean Plans New Industrial Park </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	SEOUL, South Korea (AP) -- South Korea's richest man said  
Saturday that North Korean leader Kim Jong Il has personally 
approved his plan to build a large-scale industrial park in the 
reclusive communist country. 
</P>
<P>
	Chung Ju-yung, founder and honorary chairman of the Hyundai  
group, made the remarks upon returning from an extended five-day 
visit to North Korea, during which he met the country's top leader. 
</P>
<P>
	Chung's trip, originally scheduled for three days, was extended  
by two days for a meeting with Kim on Friday. Chung said his 
meeting with Kim at the latter's countryside resort also covered 
other subjects, but he declined to elaborate. 
</P>
<P>
	``He basically has accepted our proposal to build an industrial  
park there,'' Chung said. 
</P>
<P>
	Hyundai plans to relocate 800 to 900 garment and other plants to  
the industrial park on North Korea's southwest coast, close to the 
border with South Korea, and use surplus South Korean electricity 
for the factories. 
</P>
<P>
	The plan also includes construction of car assembly lines with  
an annual capacity of 50,000, as well as television and other 
electronic assembly plants. 
</P>
<P>
	Chung said the North Korean leader looked healthy and tanned.  
</P>
<P>
	Relations between the two Koreas remain largely frozen because  
of political and military tensions. They are still technically at 
war, having signed no peace treaty at the end of the 1950-53 Korean 
War. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
