<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-02 02:30:06 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Thrashers Return NHL To Atlanta </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	ATLANTA (AP) -- The wait is over.  
</P>
<P>
	After a 19-year absence, Atlanta makes its re-entry into the NHL  
when the expansion Thrashers play their inaugural game against the 
New Jersey Devils at the $213 million Philips Arena. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's been so long since the Flames were here,'' left wing  
Denny Lambert said. ``These people have been waiting for hockey to 
return. You can tell already that they want to be a part of this 
team. They're eager to learn the game.'' 
</P>
<P>
	After the Flames moved to Calgary in 1980, the city went more  
than a decade without a team. The minor-league Knights rekindled 
interest when they were launched in 1992, winning the IHL 
championship and playing before several sellout crowds at the old 
Omni. 
</P>
<P>
	The Knights left, too, when it became apparent the city was  
moving toward bigger and better things. The Omni was torn down to 
make way for the new 18,559-seat arena, which will be filled to 
capacity for the Thrashers' debut. 
</P>
<P>
	``Everybody wants to do well and make it a memorable night,''  
center Ray Ferraro said. 
</P>
<P>
	The Thrashers were part of a four-team, three-year expansion  
phase for the NHL. The Nashville Predators started play last 
season, while the Minnesota Wild and Columbus Blue Jackets will 
enter the league in 2000. 
</P>
<P>
	``First-year teams are a lot of fun,'' said Lambert, part of a  
Predators team that surprisingly won 28 games last season. 
``There's no pressure on you. No one expects you to win any games. 
But if you do win, everyone jumps on the bandwagon.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The bandwagon already is crowded. The Thrashers have about  
13,000 season ticket holders and have sold out their first three 
games. 
</P>
<P>
	On opening night, the team plans to close off an adjacent street  
and set up ``Thrasherville,'' a collection of games and interactive 
exhibits for early-arriving fans. 
</P>
<P>
	Officials were secretive about some elements of the pregame  
festivities, such as who will sing the national anthem and take 
part in the ceremonial puck drop. 
</P>
<P>
	As for the players, they tried to maintain as much normality as  
possible with all the excitement swirling around them. 
</P>
<P>
	``You don't want to make it too big a deal,'' Ferraro said.  
``You might end up tightening yourself up and not play as well as 
you should.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Rookie coach Curt Fraser also figures to be nervous.  
</P>
<P>
	``There's certainly going to be a lot of distractions,'' he  
said. ``I want to find something for us to do so we don't have to 
think about that. A lot of these guys have been through it. They 
can help me with it.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Two of those players are Lambert and left wing Andrew Brunette.  
</P>
<P>
	Teammates a year ago in Nashville, they are going through the  
expansion process all over again with the Thrashers, who acquired 
them in separate trades. 
</P>
<P>
	``Of course, there was a little regret when I left Nashville,''  
said Brunette, doing his part to fit in with his new city by 
wearing an Atlanta Braves cap after a recent practice. ``I thought 
I would be there a long time. Now, hopefully, I'll be here a long 
time.'' 
</P>
<P>
	As with all expansion teams, the Thrashers are desperately short  
on scorers. With a roster that includes no one with more than 13 
NHL goals last season, the team was shut out in its final two 
exhibition games. 
</P>
<P>
	``When it comes to natural goal scorers, there's probably only  
10 in the league,'' said Ferraro, one of the players who must score 
about 20 goals for the Thrashers to be successful. ``We don't have 
a Brett Hull who can bury goals on the power play. We don't have a 
(Joe) Sakic or a (Peter) Forsberg. Then again, a lot of other teams 
don't, either.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The Thrashers will play an aggressive, forechecking style,  
hoping to outwork their opponents and create scoring chances off 
turnovers. But, as the preseason showed, there aren't many players 
outside of Ferraro, Nelson Emerson and top draft pick Patrik Stefan 
who look comfortable with the puck on their stick. 
</P>
<P>
	``We're producing a lot of chances,'' Fraser said. ``We've got  
to work on finishing around the net.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
