<DOCNO> APW19991002.0132 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-02 13:40:02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Rockets Trade Pippen to Portland </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	Scottie Pippen was traded today, and the Trail Blazers said he's  
happy to be headed to Portland. 
</P>
<P>
	In a six-for-one deal, Pippen was sent from the Houston Rockets  
to the Portland Trail Blazers for Kelvin Cato, Stacey Augmon, Walt 
Williams, Ed Gray, Brian Shaw and Carlos Rogers. 
</P>
<P>
	Pippen wanted out of Houston, as evidenced by his highly  
critical remarks Wednesday about Rockets teammate Charles Barkley, 
but would have preferred to go to the Lakers so he could be 
reunited with Phil Jackson, his coach in Chicago when Pippen and 
the Bulls won six championships. 
</P>
<P>
	Trail Blazers president and general manager Bob Whitsitt said  
that in a phone conversation with Pippen, the player downplayed 
reports that he wanted to go to the Lakers. 
</P>
<P>
	``He's looking forward to being a Trail Blazer,'' Whitsitt said.  
</P>
<P>
	``He said `That Los Angeles stuff is blown out or porportion. I  
like Portland. I like what's going on.' '' 
</P>
<P>
	The Lakers and Rockets discussed a deal early in the summer that  
would have sent Glen Rice and Robert Horry to the Rockets for 
Pippen, but Houston ultimately declined. 
</P>
<P>
	Now, the Rockets are willing to take back six reserves -- none of  
whom averaged double figures in points last season. 
</P>
<P>
	The Blazers had to give up six players in order to make the  
trade work under NBA salary cap guidelines. Pippen will make more 
than $14 million this season, and Portland had to put that amount 
of salaries together. 
</P>
<P>
	Pippen will join Steve Smith and Detlef Schrempf as additions to  
an improved Trail Blazers team that made it to the Western 
Conference finals last season. 
</P>
<P>
	The Rockets were eager to part with Pippen and his $67 million  
five-year contract, which still has four seasons remaining, 
following a poor 1999 season. 
</P>
<P>
	Pippen was somewhat of a disappointment, averaging 14.5 points  
and shooting just 43 percent from the field while complaining 
throughout the season that the Rockets' slow-down style of offense 
hindered his game. 
</P>
<P>
	Pippen blasted Barkley on Wednesday in an ESPN interview, saying  
he ``doesn't show the desire to want to win.'' The attack came 
after Barkley criticized Pippen in August for publicly lobbying for 
a trade to the Lakers. 
</P>
<P>
	Barkley complained he had sacrificed greatly in February to make  
salary-cap room in order for the Rockets to acquire Pippen from the 
Bulls in a sign-and-trade deal. 
</P>
<P>
	``He's creating all this controversy just to get traded,''  
Barkley said Thursday. ``He wants to get traded so bad that he'll 
just say anything to make it happen.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Pippen, 34, is a seven-time All-Star and two-time Olympian who  
won his six titles with the Bulls as the second option behind 
Michael Jordan. 
</P>
<P>
	Williams, a seven-year veteran, will be joining his fifth NBA  
team. The 6-foot-8 forward averaged between 10.3 and 17.0 points in 
his first six seasons before dropping to 9.3 last season as a 
reserve. 
</P>
<P>
	Augmon, a defensive specialist, will be entering his eighth NBA  
season with his fourth team. Cato, a 6-foot-11 center, is entering 
his third season. 
</P>
<P>
	Gray, acquired by Portland in the Steve Smith-Isaiah Rider trade  
over the summer, averaged 4.9 points for the Hawks last season. 
Shaw and Rogers barely played last season and might not even make 
the Rockets' roster for the regular season. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19991002.0133 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-02 21:20:10 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> President Urges Tolerance of Others </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	LOS ANGELES (AP) -- Urging Americans to ``purge the darkness in  
our hearts,'' President Clinton called on the nation Saturday to 
reject the type of hatred that led to shootings in California and 
the Midwest. 
</P>
<P>
	The president delivered his message of tolerance before gay and  
lesbian supporters at a black-tie dinner that raised $850,000 for 
Democratic congressional candidates -- the largest amount of 
Clinton's three-day West Coast swing. 
</P>
<P>
	``The biggest problem we've got is the primitive age-old fear  
and dehumanization of the other people who are not like us,'' 
Clinton said to extended applause. ``I'm going to do everything I 
can, every day that I have, to remind people of that.'' 
</P>
<P>
	He said it is expected for Americans to disagree over specific  
issues. But he said there should be no disagreement over ``whether 
we share a common humanity'' despite differences in race, religion, 
ethnicity or sexual orientation. 
</P>
<P>
	``We have to be one America,'' Clinton said. ``And we cannot be  
under the illusion that either material prosperity or technological 
breakthroughs alone can purge the darkness in our hearts.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Serving as host for Saturday's dinner was ANGLE, or Access Now  
for Gay and Lesbian Equality, which initially met with Clinton 
eight years ago. ANGLE was the first gay rights organization to 
endorse his candidacy then, and remained supportive despite 
disappointments from his ``don't ask, don't tell'' policy for gays 
in the military and his 1996 decision to sign a law denying federal 
recognition of same sex marriages. 
</P>
<P>
	The president alluded to those disappointments even as he  
appealed for continued support. 
</P>
<P>
	``I wish I could have done better. But we've done pretty well,  
and we're a long way from where we were,'' he said. ``I still 
believe in the future of America, and you are a part of it.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Organizers said the dinner was one of the largest events of its  
kind outside Washington. About 1,000 guests attended, each making 
contributions ranging from $250 to $50,000; Besides Clinton, 
California Gov. Gray Davis, House Minority Leader Dick Gephardt, 
D-Mo.; and Reps. Patrick Kennedy, D-R.I., and Tammy Baldwin, 
D-Wis., were scheduled speakers. 
</P>
<P>
	Afterward, Clinton was addressing a separate dinner at the home  
of director Rob Reiner, which was raising $550,000 for the 
Democratic National Committee. 
</P>
<P>
	The president tested themes at two smaller events Friday night  
with Silicon Valley executives. 
</P>
<P>
	He repeated his support for legislation barring job  
discrimination against gays and hate crimes. Clinton urged the 
crowd to fight for ``the innate dignity and equality of every human 
being'' and work to ensure ``a place at the American family table'' 
for all, regardless of race, ethnicity, religion or income. 
</P>
<P>
	The president noted that technology offers vast potential for  
transforming American society, but cannot deliver as long as some 
segments of the population cling to prejudices because they are 
afraid of change. 
</P>
<P>
	``Here you are out here, all you think about is the new  
millennium,'' Clinton said. ``Isn't it ironic that the thing that's 
holding us back most ... is our inability to form a community 
around our common humanity because of our vulnerability to 
mankind's most ancient fear, the fear of the other?'' 
</P>
<P>
	``I think we need to deal with that,'' he continued. ``I believe  
my party is on the right side of all those issues.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Clinton said he has devoted much of his time in office to  
dealing with ``the emotional and practical and national security 
demands'' of international conflicts spurred by hatreds. 
</P>
<P>
	The same elements in those problems, he said, have appeared in  
America over the past two years. 
</P>
<P>
	Specifically, he recalled the slayings of gay college student  
Matthew Shepard in Wyoming; James Byrd, a black man, in Texas; a 
Korean student and a former college basketball coach in a shooting 
spree by ``a crazy guy'' in Illinois; and the death of a Filipino 
postman and wounding of a Jewish child in shootings in California. 
</P>
<P>
	``I see people in this so-called modern world, where we're  
celebrating all of your modern ideas and your modern achievements, 
and what is the biggest problem in the world in America? We are 
dragged down by the most primitive of hatreds,'' Clinton said. 
``It's bizarre.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Earlier Saturday, the president spent time in Palo Alto visiting  
with his daughter Chelsea, a junior at Stanford University, and 
doing some work on his presidential library. 
</P>
<P>
	Clinton was returning to Washington early Monday.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19991002.0134 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-02 14:50:14 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Rockets Trade Pippen to Portland </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	PORTLAND, Ore. (AP) -- The Trail Blazers were thrilled to get  
him, the Rockets were equally glad to get rid of him. 
</P>
<P>
	As for Scottie Pippen himself, others were left to do the  
talking. 
</P>
<P>
	In a deal that had been rumored for days, the six-time NBA  
champion and seven-time All-Star was traded to Portland on Saturday 
for Kelvin Cato, Stacey Augmon, Walt Williams, Ed Gray, Brian Shaw 
and Carlos Rogers. 
</P>
<P>
	Blazers president and general manager Bob Whitsitt said Pippen  
was ``extremely excited'' about the deal, and Pippen's agent, Jimmy 
Sexton, concurred. 
</P>
<P>
	Pippen, however, said nothing publicly from his home in  
Arkansas. 
</P>
<P>
	``Don't read anything into that,'' Sexton said of Pippen's  
silence. ``After Scottie evaluated the situation in Portland, 
looked at their roster, what they did last year and the pieces 
they've added, he was excited. They'll have a legitimate chance to 
win the NBA championship.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Pippen's first choice for a new team was the Los Angeles Lakers,  
where he would have rejoined former Bulls coach Phil Jackson. There 
was speculation that Portland might turn around and trade Pippen to 
the Lakers for Glen Rice and other players -- speculation that 
figures to continue through the season -- but on Saturday the 
Blazers were talking about Pippen being a part of their drive for a 
title. 
</P>
<P>
	``I talked with Scottie on the phone, and he said, 'That L.A.  
stuff was blown out of proportion. I love Portland and I like 
what's going on,' '' Whitsitt said. 
</P>
<P>
	The deal, finalized Saturday morning during a conference call  
with the Rockets and the NBA, was hastened when Pippen lambasted 
Barkley in an ESPN interview aired Wednesday. Pippen called his 
teammate ``fat'' and ``selfish,'' and said he wanted out of Houston 
because Barkley didn't have enough desire to win. 
</P>
<P>
	Other teams, including the Milwaukee Bucks and New Jersey Nets,  
made late offers that were rejected. The Lakers considered offering 
Rice, Robert Horry and Travis Knight, but ultimately declined. 
</P>
<P>
	``We're moving forward,'' Rockets coach Rudy Tomjanovich said.  
``I think we've taken a negative situation and tried to turn it 
into a positive.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Pippen, 34, signed a five-year, $67 million contract with the  
Rockets before the lockout-shorted 1999 season began. But he never 
fit into Houston's low-post oriented offense, and competed with 
stars Hakeem Olajuwon and Barkley for looks at the basket. 
</P>
<P>
	``When you play that style of basketball (with the Bulls), I  
understood it would take some time to adjust,'' Tomjanovich said at 
a news conference in Houston. The coach said he talked with Pippen 
on the phone and told him he was sorry it didn't work out. 
</P>
<P>
	``It was very professional. We wished each other luck,'' he  
said. 
</P>
<P>
	Pippen is due to make $14.8 million this season, which nearly  
equals the combined salaries of the six players Portland traded. 
</P>
<P>
	Last season Pippen averaged 14.5 points, his lowest output since  
1988-89, his second season with the Bulls and two years before the 
Bulls won the first of their six titles. He also shot a career-low 
43 percent, but averaged 6.5 rebounds and 5.9 assists and made the 
NBA's All-Defensive first team for the eighth straight year. 
</P>
<P>
	The Blazers, already loaded with talented players like Brian  
Grant, Rasheed Wallace, Damon Stoudamire and new acquisitions 
Detlef Schrempf and Steve Smith, don't care if he ever returns to 
the scoring level that made him a selection on the NBA's 50 
all-time greatest players. 
</P>
<P>
	``If Scottie averages 14, seven rebounds, seven assists and two  
steals ever year for the next four years, perfect,'' Whitsitt said. 
``We'll take that in a heartbeat.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Pippen has been one of the NBA's most dominant forwards the last  
decade, but he has not proved he can effectively lead a team 
without Michael Jordan around. In the 1994 playoffs, with Jordan 
off playing minor-league baseball, Pippen refused to enter a game 
in the final seconds against the Knicks when Jackson had drawn up 
the final shot for Toni Kukoc instead of him. 
</P>
<P>
	In Houston, it was clear from Wednesday's interview, Pippen did  
not get along with Barkley, his teammate on the Dream Team that won 
the 1992 Olympics in Barcelona. Pippen complained that he was not 
getting the ball enough, and Barkley complained that he had given 
up part of his salary so the Rockets could afford Pippen. 
</P>
<P>
	The falling out between the two intensified over the summer when  
they traveled together on a tour for Nike, the athletic footwear 
maker. 
</P>
<P>
	There's no telling how Pippen will fit in with the Blazers, who  
are deep at every position despite unloading six players. Last 
season, Stoudamire groused about not getting enough minutes, even 
during the Blazers' four-game series loss to San Antonio in the 
Western Conference finals. 
</P>
<P>
	The Rockets, meanwhile, likely will jettison at least three of  
their new players. The team had 18 players under contract without 
Pippen before the trade. Tomjanovich sounded most interested in 
Williams, a good outside shooter, and Cato, a 6-foot-11 center who 
showed promise backing up Arvydas Sabonis. 
</P>
<P>
	That means the Rockets could cut Augmon, Gray, Shaw and Rogers  
during training camp, which begins Tuesday. The Blazers might be 
interested in re-signing Augmon, a defensive specialist, to a 
contract considerably less than his $3.2 million salary. 



  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19991002.0135 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-02 13:34:51 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> $20M Needed To Keep Reds Together </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	MILWAUKEE (AP) -- On the day Marge Schott became a part of the  
Cincinnati Reds' past, general manager Jim Bowden issued a grave 
warning about his overachieving team's future. 
</P>
<P>
	Bowden, in Milwaukee on Friday to watch the Reds attempt to  
clinch a playoff berth in a three-game series with the Brewers, 
decried the gaps in baseball's economic structure while praising 
his current team's improbable run to the postseason. 
</P>
<P>
	Bowden thinks Cincinnati would need a $20 million payroll  
increase to keep the current team intact for next year. 
</P>
<P>
	``A small-market team just can't do what we've done,'' Bowden  
said. ``What we've done doesn't change the economic problems of 
baseball.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The Reds' payroll is $35 million and is the lowest among the  
nine teams still in contention for a postseason berth. That bottom 
line was even lower before Bowden acquired starting pitcher Juan 
Guzman at the trading deadline. 
</P>
<P>
	Bowden figures he would need at least a $55 million payroll to  
keep intact the solid nucleus he has built in the past 18 months 
through trades, the maturation of young players and good fortune. 
</P>
<P>
	The Reds would be able to generate a large amount of revenue  
with an extended postseason run, but even a trip to the World 
Series and the resulting increases in season-ticket sales for 2000 
might not bring in the funds Bowden said he will need. 
</P>
<P>
	``Anything's possible, but right now it's unlikely,'' he said.  
``It's almost impossible to keep all these elements together.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Bowden has ample experience in building teams and watching them  
be destroyed. His Cincinnati teams in 1994 and 1995 won NL Central 
Division championships, but the team's payroll edged up higher than 
the small-market Reds could afford, particularly when the 
free-spending Schott was forced to stop running the team. 
</P>
<P>
	So Bowden dismantled the Reds, jettisoning Ron Gant, David  
Wells, Benito Santiago, Tony Fernandez and Mike Jackson, among 
others. He tried to patch the lineup with fill-ins like Eric Davis. 
</P>
<P>
	But Cincinnati fell to .500 in 1996, and played 1997 and 1998 at  
18 games under .500, not finishing higher than third place in the 
division. So the Reds decided to tear down the team and rebuild, 
starting with the trade of starter John Smiley to Cleveland in July 
1997. 
</P>
<P>
	``We had to turn it over to young, talented kids, and we had to  
do it at the expense of our best players,'' Bowden said. 
</P>
<P>
	In the next 16 months, Jeff Brantley, Dave Burba, Jeff Shaw,  
Mike Remlinger, Paul Konerko and Bret Boone left as Bowden built a 
core of youngsters for the future. But even Bowden couldn't have 
predicted how quickly the team would come together -- and how much 
fun they would have doing it. 
</P>
<P>
	The addition of veterans Greg Vaughn, Denny Neagle and others  
have complemented and provided leadership to Cincinnati's 
youngsters such as Sean Casey and Pokey Reese. 
</P>
<P>
	``I've never seen a team that has such a good time,'' Bowden  
said. ``In '94, '95, we had trouble in the clubhouse. This year 
we've had nothing but peace.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Bowden had no intention of tracing that peace back to Schott's  
departure from involvement in the day-to-day operations of the 
club, though he did praise the limited partnership controlled by 
Carl Lindner and two others which formally took over the team 
Friday. 
</P>
<P>
	``This ownership group lets employees do their jobs,'' Bowden  
said. ``How much revenue we generate will determine what kind of 
team we can put on the field.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Though he's perennially a contender for other jobs in bigger  
markets, Bowden thinks his future is in Cincinnati. He and Reds 
managing executive John Allen appear to have smoothed over any 
differences they might have had, and the once-dismal farm system 
finally is showing promise. 
</P>
<P>
	Bowden, who was a candidate for GM jobs in Los Angeles and  
Baltimore during the last offseason, signed a three-year contract 
extension last October that will keep him in Cincinnati through 
2003, the same year the Reds' new ballpark is scheduled to open. 
</P>
<P>
	And though he doesn't expect his surprising team to return  
intact in 2000, he'll go back to work anyway. 
</P>
<P>
	``We'll try to figure out another way to win,'' Bowden said.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19991002.0136 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-02 19:14:18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> international </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Police Shoot at S. African Funeral </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	MAZIZINI, South Africa (AP) -- The funeral of a racist army  
lieutenant turned violent Saturday when mourners insisted on giving 
the man a 12-gun salute over the orders of police. At least three 
people were wounded as the crowd of 2,000 screamed and scattered. 
</P>
<P>
	Police fired live ammunition and tear gas at the funeral of Lt.  
Sibusiso Madubela, a black soldier who killed seven white military 
officers and a white civilian in a killing spree last month. 
</P>
<P>
	The mayhem followed the firing of two shots by funeral-goers who  
were starting a 12-gun salute. Army helicopters hovered overhead 
and landed to unload police reinforcements in this small village 
near Umtata, 35 miles inland from the Indian Ocean on the 
southeastern coast. 
</P>
<P>
	Police Superintendent Wayne Hackert said the live shots were  
fired into the air, not at the crowd, and claimed the three 
injuries could have happened as the crowd panicked. 
</P>
<P>
	``We cannot allow the blatant defiance of law and order in front  
of everybody,'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	In funeral speeches before the violence, officials from the Pan  
Africanist Congress vowed to slay whites and claimed that Madubela 
went on his killing spree to teach whites a lesson. 
</P>
<P>
	The killings last month at Tempe military base in Bloemfontein --  
finally stopped by a fatal bullet -- emphasized racial tensions in 
the armed forces as former black guerrillas and their white 
military enemies have been melded into a common force after the end 
of apartheid in 1994. 
</P>
<P>
	Hackert said PAC officials made it clear earlier in the week  
that they were determined to fire an honors salute for Madubela. 
The military had refused the PAC's request for an honorary burial. 
</P>
<P>
	Swayi Mqojana, an official of the PAC, a small, militant black  
group, charged that police had disarmed funeral-goers during 
weapons searches in order to set them up for the attack. 
</P>
<P>
	``This is the day the government has declared war on the PAC,''  
he said in an interview. 
</P>
<P>
	In a speech at the graveside earlier, Lethlata Mphahleli, former  
head of operations for PAC guerrillas, encouraged blacks to imitate 
Madubela's massacre. 
</P>
<P>
	``Go and liberate this country the way Madubela did,'' Mphahleli  
said. 
</P>
<P>
	Tension began building before the ceremony, when police armed  
with rifles and shotguns stopped about 30 PAC supporters who were 
chanting ``one settler, one bullet.'' The activists wanted police 
to stop searching mourners as they arrived. 
</P>
<P>
	A mix of personal and political factors appeared to have  
motivated Madubela -- a former member of the PAC armed wing -- to 
kill his colleagues. He was demoted from captain in the guerrilla 
group to lieutenant, and family members have said he nurtured 
resentment over his demotion. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19991002.0137 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-02 13:40:18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Church Shooter Spoke Often With Cops </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	FORT WORTH, Texas (AP) -- The gunman who killed seven people  
inside a Baptist church, then sat down in a pew and shot himself, 
had talked regularly with the city's police chief for nearly a 
decade. 
</P>
<P>
	Fort Worth Police Chief Thomas Windham told the Fort Worth  
Star-Telegram on Saturday that Larry Gene Ashbrook had called his 
office at least four or five times since 1990, typically rambling 
about unemployment and his years in the Navy. 
</P>
<P>
	``I didn't make anything out of it other than here's a guy who  
lost his job,'' Windham said. ``He always seemed like a nice-enough 
guy to me. It's an understatement now to say that's a misperception 
of him, but nothing in those conversations would ever signal he was 
a violent individual.'' 
</P>
<P>
	In his first call, nine years ago, Ashbrook complained that he  
had lost his job because police were following him, Windham said. 
He said he assured Ashbrook that wasn't true. 
</P>
<P>
	Such calls aren't unusual. Windham said about half a dozen  
people regularly call his office to complain or talk. 
</P>
<P>
	The last time he spoke with Ashbrook was a few months before the  
shootings. 
</P>
<P>
	``I said: `How are you doing?'  
</P>
<P>
	``He said: `Not too good. My father died.'  
</P>
<P>
	``I said: `I'm very sorry to hear that.'  
</P>
<P>
	``He said: `All he left me was debts. I don't have a job. I  
haven't worked for years and I guess I'm going to lose my house 
because it's not paid for, and I don't have any way to pay for 
it.''' 
</P>
<P>
	``He wasn't angry, and he really wasn't distraught. It was just  
a voice of concern,'' Windham said. 
</P>
<P>
	On Sept. 15, Ashbrook walked into Wedgwood Baptist Church and  
opened fire during a youth meeting, shooting 14 people before 
taking his own life. 
</P>
<P>
	Windham said Ashbrook never mentioned guns or religion, and he  
said he didn't consider urging Ashbrook to seek professional help. 
</P>
<P>
	``The only advice I ever gave him was, just because he lost one  
job doesn't mean he couldn't get another,'' Windham said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19991002.0138 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-02 13:40:06 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> political </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Forbes Woos Christian Conservatives </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Republican presidential candidate Steve Forbes  
asked Christian conservatives Saturday to follow him and not GOP 
front-runner George W. Bush. ``We don't have to settle for mush,'' 
Forbes said. 
</P>
<P>
	Forbes tried to rally support at the Christian Coalition's  
annual ``Road to Victory'' conference by painting his agenda as 
more conservative -- and more defined -- than that of Bush, the Texas 
governor who is the runaway favorite in polls and among Republican 
campaign contributors. 
</P>
<P>
	``The front-runner won't promise to appoint pro-life judges, but  
I have and will. The front-runner won't promise to appoint a 
pro-life running mate; I have and will,'' Forbes said to applause 
from some 3,500 coalition members at a downtown hotel. 
</P>
<P>
	``George W. Bush, it's time to debate. ... The Republican Party  
deserves to know its nominee,'' Forbes said. 
</P>
<P>
	He reiterated his support for school vouchers, school prayer and  
a flat tax. He stressed repeatedly that he would appoint to the 
federal bench only those judges ``who believe in the sanctity of 
the Constitution and in the sanctity of life.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Bush has said, without elaboration, that he would have ``no  
litmus test'' for judicial appointments. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's very tempting, with an election coming up, to muffle our  
principles,'' Forbes said Saturday. ``We don't have to settle for 
mush. We don't have to abandon the party of Reagan'' in order to 
win. 
</P>
<P>
	The wealthy publisher, his wife, Sabina, and three of their five  
daughters then mingled with coalition members over a picnic lunch 
paid for by Forbes. Members of his small army of young volunteers 
wore matching denim shirts with red bandannas knotted around their 
necks. 
</P>
<P>
	Forbes also castigated Minnesota Gov. Jesse Ventura, a former  
professional wrestler, for his published comments last week against 
organized religion. 
</P>
<P>
	``Bullies end up belittling themselves,'' Forbes said. ``Faith  
is not a crutch for the weak. It is a wellspring of hope and 
comfort for the humble.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19991002.0139 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-02 19:07:19 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE>  Asian Boycott of World Cup Settled </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	LAS VEGAS (AP) -- South Korea will play host to the opening match  
of the next World Cup on June 1, 2002, with the final to take place 
June 30 in Japan, international soccer officials said Saturday. 
</P>
<P>
	The dates for the World Cup were set at a FIFA executive  
committee meeting, at which Asian countries also formally agreed to 
accept a plan for the number of places per continent in the 
tournament. 
</P>
<P>
	Under the plan, Asia will get a chance for a fifth spot in the  
World Cup in a playoff with Europe, essentially the same terms that 
provoked a walkout by Asian delegates to a FIFA meeting in Los 
Angeles in July and threats of a possible World Cup boycott. 
</P>
<P>
	``The threat of any boycott has been set off with a red card  
somewhere and will not come up again,'' FIFA president Sepp Blatter 
said. 
</P>
<P>
	Blatter acknowledged, though, that Asian delegates were still  
not happy about the plan, and by the committee's decision to reject 
an Asian request that the Asian team have its playoff against the 
Oceania representative instead of one from Europe. 
</P>
<P>
	``You cannot have happiness for everybody, it is not possible,''  
Blatter said. ``But we have peace in the football family now.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Asia had three automatic berths in last year's tournament and  
got another spot when Iran won a playoff with Australia, the 
Oceania champion. The continent will get four automatic berths for 
2002, with its third team in qualifying playing Europe's 14th place 
team for a fifth berth. 
</P>
<P>
	The two-day meeting of the FIFA executive committee ended  
Saturday with soccer officials setting the dates for the next World 
Cup, which will be jointly hosted by South Korea and Japan. 
</P>
<P>
	The June 1 kickoff is the earliest since 1986 when the  
tournament was played in Mexico and started May 31. Last year's 
World Cup in France began June 10. 
</P>
<P>
	Committee officials had discussed starting the finals even  
earlier to try to avoid the area's rainy season, but European 
soccer officials protested successfully that a May kickoff was out 
of the question because the European soccer season would not end 
early enough. 
</P>
<P>
	``Who today can predict weather conditions in June 2002 in Korea  
and Japan?'' Blatter asked. 
</P>
<P>
	In other issues, Blatter said:  
</P>
<P>
	-- A record 172 entries for the next World Cup were in by the  
Sept. 30 deadline, with others expected by mail that will lift the 
number of entries to about 190. 
</P>
<P>
	-- The site of the 2006 World Cup will be decided at a July 5-6,  
2000, meeting of FIFA's 24-member executive committee in 
Switzerland. Brazil, Germany, South Africa, England and Morocco are 
the five finalists. 
</P>
<P>
	-- FIFA is making progress on a master calendar that would help  
solve scheduling conflicts among different soccer federations. 
</P>
<P>
	-- The prospect of the World Cup being held every two years,  
instead of every four years, has been shelved until after the 2002 
World Cup. ``It's not dead, it's just well guarded,'' Blatter said. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19991002.0140 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-02 19:07:19 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
