<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-02 21:20:10 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Campus Cops Handcuff Sportswriter </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	PULLMAN, Wash. (AP) -- Seattle Post-Intelligencer sportswriter  
Angelo Bruscas had a brush with the law while trying to cover 
Washington State's 31-7 victory over California on Saturday. 
</P>
<P>
	After crowding past a civilian security guard following the  
game, Bruscas failed to stop for a Washington State University 
police officer and was arrested. 
</P>
<P>
	``Pushing one of our kids was a major mistake. He compounded it  
when he didn't comply with the request to stop,'' Sgt. Steve Hansen 
said. ``We maybe could have straightened it out. He needed to stop 
and talk with the officer instead of walking away.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Bruscas didn't stop for the officer right away because he had to  
use the restroom. 
</P>
<P>
	She handcuffed him when he came out and he was taken to the  
campus police station, cited for fourth-degree assault, obstruction 
of an officer, and released. 
</P>
<P>
	If convicted in Whitman County District Court he could face a  
maximum sentence of a year in jail and a $5,000 fine, Hansen said. 
</P>
<P>
	Washington State sports information director Rod Commons said  
the security guard had been told to hold back the media for 10 
minutes. 
</P>
<P>
	``Most of the media began to argue strongly and somebody opened  
the door and they started charging up the stairs,'' Commons said. 
</P>
<P>
	Bruscas says he was just doing his job with the rest of the  
reporters hurrying to the media room. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's standard procedure. It's not like we were barging into  
the locker room,'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	Bruscas, who was wearing his press pass, said he couldn't  
believe his arrest, but he had the bruised wrist to prove it. 
</P>
<P>
	``I'm so flabbergasted. I'm still stunned. I may have to get  
something for my wrist,'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	``My editors were flabbergasted. I wrote my story off the quote  
sheet. I wasn't able to talk to players.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The newspaper said a lawyer has been contacted.  
</P>
<P>
	``I've never encountered anything like this in 20 years of  
reporting,'' Bruscas said. ``It's the equivalent of being arrested 
going into City Hall to cover the city council meeting.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Bruscas said his big mistake was choosing to use the toilet  
rather than talking to the officer. 
</P>
<P>
	``I certainly wasn't belligerent or anything like that other  
than having to go to the bathroom,'' he said. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
