<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Obituaries in the News  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 *Walter Bergman    	
</P>
<P>
	GRAND RAPIDS, Mich. (AP) -- Walter Bergman, a civil rights  
activist and a founder of the Michigan chapter of the ACLU and the 
Michigan Federation of Teachers, died Wednesday of congestive heart 
failure. He was 100. 
</P>
<P>
	A member of the Freedom Riders, Bergman was among those attacked  
on Mother's Day, 1961 by Ku Klux Klan members and other vigilantes 
in Anniston, Ala. 
</P>
<P>
	Bergman was knocked to the floor, pounded with fists and stomped  
on his head, neck and shoulders. Doctors believe a stroke he 
suffered months later stemmed from the beating. He was 61 at the 
time and spent the rest of his life in a wheelchair. 
</P>
<P>
	In 1977, the ACLU sued the government on behalf of Bergman after  
it was learned the FBI was aware of -- but did not stop -- the 
planned attack on the Freedom Riders. 
</P>
<P>
	Bergman, a professor at Wayne State and the University of  
Michigan, devoted himself to activism after retiring from an 
academic career in the early 1960s. 

</P>
<P>
 *Weldon W. Case    	
</P>
<P>
	AKRON, Ohio (AP) -- Weldon W. Case, the former chairman and chief  
executive officer of Alltel Corp., died Thursday of heart failure 
in Boca Raton, Fla. He was 78. 
</P>
<P>
	Case was 14 when he started as a line crew member in 1934 with  
the company, then known as Hudson Underground Telephone Co. He 
worked his way up to general manager and to president of the 
company known as Western Reserve Telephone Co. 
</P>
<P>
	After making several acquisitions, Case founded Mid-Continent  
Telephone Co., which merged in 1983 with Allied Telephone Co. to 
form Alltel Corp. He was chairman and chief executive until he 
retired in 1991 at age 70. 

</P>
<P>
                         *Dr. John J. Conley    	
</P>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Dr. John J. Conley, a surgeon who developed  
operations for improving the speech of patients who lost their 
voice boxes to cancer, died on Sept. 21. He was 87. 
</P>
<P>
	Conley, an otolaryngologist, also developed operations for  
rehabilitating the larynx, grafting facial nerves and 
reconstruction after the loss of the jaw to cancer. He developed 
the idea of single-stage rehabilitation after extensive head and 
neck surgery. 
</P>
<P>
	He pioneered reconstruction methods for the cheek and face as an  
Army surgeon in World War II, and developed further innovations in 
the 1960s and early 1970s. In the early 1990s, he founded the John 
Conley Foundation for Ethics and Philosophy in Medicine. 
</P>
<P>
	Conley retired at age 80, ending his long-standing professional  
ties to Columbia University's College of Physicians and Surgeons, 
Columbia-Presbyterian Medical Center, and St. Vincent's Hospital 
and Medical Center. 

</P>
<P>
 *Pat Davis    	
</P>
<P>
	SACRAMENTO, Calif. (AP) -- Pat Davis, a popular broadcast  
journalist who covered California politics and national news for 
three decades, died Friday of a heart attack during a bicycle ride. 
He was 58. 
</P>
<P>
	The 6-foot-4 Davis, an aggressive, physically imposing reporter  
with a skeptical demeanor and a biting sense of humor, often 
covered stories hundreds of miles apart in a day, feeding a stream 
of reports to his radio station as well stations in San Francisco 
and Los Angeles, and the CBS radio network in New York. 
</P>
<P>
	Davis, who was born in Wichita, Kan., also appeared in a weekly  
political broadcast for public television on station KVIE in 
Sacramento. 
</P>
<P>
	Davis' news reports were heard regularly on KFBK in Sacramento,  
his home station, as well as KNX in Los Angeles, KGO in San 
Francisco and on CBS and Associated Press Radio. 
</P>
<P>
	Since the 1970s, he has covered virtually every major national  
news story in northern and central California, as well as 
presidential, gubernatorial and U.S. Senate campaigns. 
</P>
<P>
	Survivors include his wife and two children.  

</P>
<P>
 *Charles A. Federer Jr.    	
</P>
<P>
	MYSTIC, Conn. (AP) -- Charles A. Federer Jr., the editor in chief  
of Sky and Telescope magazine, died Tuesday. He was 90. 
</P>
<P>
	Federer started the magazine for amateur astronomers in 1941 and  
retired in 1974. The magazine now has a circulation of about 
125,000. 
</P>
<P>
	Federer taught himself astronomy as a child growing up in  
Redding. He earned a physics degree from the City College of New 
York in the 1930s and founded his own magazine by combining two 
money-losing journals, The Sky and The Telescope. 

</P>
<P>
 *Norbert Gaughan    	
</P>
<P>
	CROWN POINT, Ind. (AP) -- Former Bishop Norbert Gaughan, who  
fought the Vatican's move to scale back his duties as bishop of the 
Roman Catholic Diocese of Gary after suffering a series of strokes, 
died Friday. He was 78. 
</P>
<P>
	Gaughan was installed as the second bishop of the Gary Diocese  
in July 1984. He moved the center of diocesan operations from the 
main cathedral in beleaguered Gary to a new $1.3 million ``pastoral 
center'' in nearby suburban Merrillville. 
</P>
<P>
	Gaughan suffered a stroke in April 1989, followed by a severe  
second stroke in February 1992 that kept him from his duties for 
three months. 
</P>
<P>
	That spring, Gaughan was visited twice by the late Cardinal  
Joseph Bernardin of Chicago. Bernardin assessed of Gaughan's 
abilities to administer to the diocese, which has about 181,000 
parishioners. 
</P>
<P>
	Based on those reports and medical reports, Pope John Paul II  
appointed Bishop Dale Melczek, then auxiliary bishop for the 
Archdiocese of Detroit, to handle the Gary diocese's administrative 
duties. 
</P>
<P>
	In March 1993, Gaughan traveled to Rome to appeal to the pope  
for the ``complete reinstatement'' of his job, but to no avail. 
</P>
<P>
	Gaughan retired from the active ministry on June 1, 1996.  

</P>
<P>
 *Sal Salvador    	
</P>
<P>
	STAMFORD, Conn. (AP) -- Sal Salvador, a guitarist who performed  
with some top jazz musicians, died of cancer on Sept. 22. He was 
73. 
</P>
<P>
	Born as Silvio Smiraglia, Salvador taught himself how to play  
guitar and became known as a be-bop improviser. 
</P>
<P>
	He performed with Stan Kenton, Bill Evans, Phil Woods and other  
jazz greats. 
</P>
<P>
	From 1970 until recently, Salvador taught jazz at the University  
of Bridgeport and Western Connecticut State University. He also 
gave private lessons in New York City. 


  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19991002.0145 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-02 17:30:24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Underwood Has Trouble With Pressure </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 *Associated Press Writer-    	
</P>
<P>
	LANSING, Mich. (AP) -- Dimitrius Underwood is massive -- 6-foot-6,  
270 pounds of muscle -- but the powerful NFL player has had a hard 
time dealing with pressure, in the eyes of some who know him. 
</P>
<P>
	It's one reason a relatively minor ankle sprain kept him from  
playing at Michigan State his senior year. It might have 
contributed to his decision to walk away from a $5.3 million, 
five-year contract with the Minnesota Vikings the first day of 
training camp. 
</P>
<P>
	And it could be part of the reason the defensive lineman for the  
Miami Dolphins slashed at his neck with two steak knives last 
Sunday after pacing around his girlfriend's apartment yelling, ``I 
am not worthy of God.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The pressure has come from many places, said his high school  
pastor, the Rev. Moses Townsend, who visited Underwood Friday at 
the inpatient mental health clinic where he is being treated. 
</P>
<P>
	He felt pressure living up to football's demands while at  
Michigan State. He had trouble dealing with the media spotlight 
when he got the Vikings contract, then spent four days in a 
Philadelphia hotel deciding if he should play football or serve 
God. 
</P>
<P>
	And he felt pressure from an unidentified man from Immanuel's  
Temple Community Church in Lansing, Townsend said. 
</P>
<P>
	``He was throwing him off course,'' Townsend said Saturday. ``He  
(Underwood) wasn't taking as much interest in his mother as he had 
in the past. Whatever this man said, that's what it looked like he 
wanted to do.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Underwood's mother, Eileen Underwood, an ordained minister who  
lives in Philadelphia, first said her son was being affected by ``a 
cult that's posing as a church.'' Then on Friday, she said that she 
and Immanuel's Temple's pastor, the Rev. Phillip Owens, both are 
born-again Christians. 
</P>
<P>
	``So it goes without saying that we should both be on the same  
accord, rather than creating conflict caused by 
misinterpretation,'' she said in a statement released by her son's 
agent, Craig Domann. 
</P>
<P>
	Underwood attended Immanuel's Temple on and off for about a  
year. He now has no interest in returning, Townsend said. 
</P>
<P>
	``The people who were around him seemed to have a lot of  
influence, and it didn't turn out well,'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	Owens has denied his church is a cult. He led a men's breakfast  
meeting Saturday but declined to speak to an Associated Press 
reporter about the church. He said a statement would be issued in 
the future. 
</P>
<P>
	The church got more attention Friday when Michigan State  
University police said a 23-year-old former Spartans student found 
dead Sept. 22 in an unused cooler in a dorm basement also had 
attended Immanuel's Temple for about a year. 
</P>
<P>
	For Underwood, some of his turmoil might have shown up in a  
series of traffic tickets. He had a clean driving record until June 
1998, when he failed to pay a ticket for not wearing a seat belt. 
</P>
<P>
	In December 1998, he was ticketed for going 74 mph in a 45 mph  
zone in Georgia. This June, he was ticketed for speeding 91 mph in 
a 70 mph zone near Grand Blanc. He disobeyed a traffic signal in 
East Lansing in August, causing his license to be suspended 
indefinitely Sept. 16. He has no car registered in his name, but 
was driving a Lexus in August. 
</P>
<P>
	Townsend said Underwood's struggles with pressure occasionally  
caused him to back away from football but never diminished his 
desire to make it a career. 
</P>
<P>
	In 1997, the junior was the co-winner of Michigan State's Iron  
Man Award for weight training. The telecommunications major from. 
Fayetteville, N.C., also had his best football year in 1997, 
starting all but one game and finishing second in tackles among 
defensive linemen. 
</P>
<P>
	But he seemed not to like the constant demand to perform.  
</P>
<P>
	``They (the coaches) wanted him to eat football, sleep  
football,'' Townsend said. ``So he called me and I said, `Just back 
off a year.' '' 
</P>
<P>
	In August of his senior year, Underwood sprained an ankle at the  
beginning of two-a-day drills. Doctors cleared him to play against 
Indiana Oct. 10, but he never asked to be put in. 
</P>
<P>
	``Here's a guy who elected not to play football,'' John  
Lewandowski, Michigan State sports information director, said. 
``Once he made that decision, he wasn't around a lot.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The Spartans red-shirted Underwood, expecting him to come back  
for a fifth year. But in late December, he said he wanted to be 
drafted. 
</P>
<P>
	``It caught all of us off guard,'' Lewandowski said. ``There  
aren't a lot of people who sit out their senior season, then go out 
for the draft.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The Vikings surprisingly made him their second first-round draft  
choice, 29th choice overall. 
</P>
<P>
	``Dimitrius Underwood is one of the most impressive guys as far  
as his height, weight, quickness and speed,'' Vikings coach Dennis 
Green said in April. 
</P>
<P>
	But the pressure of being a first-round draft pick might have  
gotten to Underwood. 
</P>
<P>
	``Nothing he accomplished on the field warranted him being  
thrown into the limelight,'' Lewandowski said. 
</P>
<P>
	No one from the Vikings organization contacted Michigan State  
coach Nick Saban, who would have told them of the concerns he had 
about Underwood's decision not to play after the ankle injury. 
</P>
<P>
	``Dimitrius' behavior over a little time here was a little  
unusual,'' Saban said last week, adding that coaches had tried to 
help Underwood his senior year. 
</P>
<P>
	Now, his brush with death might bring Underwood the treatment he  
needs. He said Friday he wants to return to the Dolphins, who this 
week put him on the reserved-nonfootball injury list. 
</P>
<P>
	If it hadn't been for an immediate call to 911 by his girlfriend  
and quick action by Lansing police and emergency workers, Underwood 
could have ended up in worse shape. 
</P>
<P>
	Shirtless, barefoot and covered in blood to his waist, he told  
police: ``You are Satan and you are going to hell'' and ``I want to 
be saved, I want to meet God.'' 
</P>
<P>
	He spent four days being treated at Sparrow Hospital. Now life  
appears better. 
</P>
<P>
	``He's up and around, he's talking and laughing,'' Townsend said  
Saturday. ``I encouraged him to fight and get himself together. I 
think he will.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
