<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-02 14:50:14 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Metric Ignorance Caused Mars Mishap </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	LOS ANGELES (AP) -- How does the United States measure up to the  
rest of the world in accepting the metric system? Look no farther 
than the doomed Mars Climate Orbiter, say proponents of meters, 
grams and liters. 
</P>
<P>
	The $125 million spacecraft was lost because NASA navigators  
mistakenly thought a contractor used metric measurements. The 
contractor had used English units, and the probe burned up in the 
Martian atmosphere Sept. 23. 
</P>
<P>
	``A stupid error like that could have been avoided if we had  
been on the metric system,'' said Valerie Antoine, executive 
director of the U.S. Metric Association. ``This is a very good 
reason Congress had better get busy and mandate we go metric.'' 
</P>
<P>
	In 1975, Congress approved a policy to ``coordinate and plan ...  
the voluntary conversion to the metric system.'' But it wasn't 
mandatory, and Americans still pump their gas in gallons and follow 
signs with distances marked in miles. 
</P>
<P>
	NASA went metric in 1996, and there have been other bumpy  
conversions. In 1983, a Canadian jetliner nearly ran out of fuel 
after someone pumped 22,300 pounds of fuel into its tanks rather 
than 22,300 kilograms. 
</P>
<P>
	Seaver Leslie, chairman of the Americans for Customary Weight  
and Measure, says conversion to the metric system is a waste of 
money. People can guess the length of a foot. But a meter? It's 
3.28083989501312 feet. 
</P>
<P>
	``NASA's interested in researching space and discovering the  
great unknown and getting there as safely as possible,'' he said. 
``We don't need errors created by people fumbling around with two 
measurement systems. 
</P>
<P>
	About 95 percent of the world uses the metric system. Some U.S.  
businesses that sell their products abroad relabel their products 
for overseas sales. Others, such as automakers, have switched to 
metric measurements. 
</P>
<P>
	There are other signs that the United States is inching toward  
acceptance of the metric system: supermarkets stock soda in 2-liter 
bottles, cameras take 35 mm film, and police regularly seize 
``kilos'' of drugs. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19991002.0147 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-02 12:00:16 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Indians' Smiley Throws Again </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	CLEVELAND (AP) -- John Smiley played catch this week and kept the  
ball as a souvenir. 
</P>
<P>
	Smiley had been waiting two years for the chance to throw a  
baseball again after breaking his left arm while warming up before 
a game in Kansas City in September, 1997. 
</P>
<P>
	``I was so juiced up I couldn't even go to sleep that night,''  
Smiley said of his Thursday workout. ``A year ago, it really didn't 
look to good. It's been a tough haul.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Smiley broke the humerus bone in his left arm while throwing in  
the visitors' bullpen at Kauffman Stadium before a scheduled start 
on Sept. 20, 1997. 
</P>
<P>
	The break was so severe that as he laid on the ground, Smiley  
remembered thinking his arm had fallen off and he searched in the 
dirt for it. It was the same injury sustained by former major 
league pitchers Dave Dravecky and Tom Browning. 
</P>
<P>
	Smiley, who won 20 games for Pittsburgh in 1991, decided to try  
and comeback from the injury and has spent the past two seasons 
undergoing extensive rehabilitation. 
</P>
<P>
	He came to the ballpark everyday to lift weights, run and  
undergo treatments in the hopes he could one day return to the 
mound. 
</P>
<P>
	And on Thursday, he made 25 throws at a distance of 40 feet  
while playing catch with outfielder Jacob Cruz. 
</P>
<P>
	``It was great.'' Smiley said. ``All the work has paid off. That  
was my goal before the end of the year.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Smiley played catch again on Saturday, throwing 25 more times at  
a distance of 45 feet. He hopes to back up five more feet next 
week, and another five a week later. 
</P>
<P>
	``Today was even better than the other day,'' said Smiley. ``The  
ball came out nice and straight. I don't know if I could have 
broken a pane of glass though.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Smiley will continue to rehab during the postseason, and said if  
he can keep progressing, he could begin throwing off a mound after 
Christmas. 
</P>
<P>
	The 35-year-old Smiley's contract expires this year with the  
Indians. However, he said he wants to pitch for the Indians and is 
confident he can get a minor league deal with the club before 
spring training. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's been tough coming in here and not being able to help the  
team,'' he said. ``I just want to pitch again for this team. I 
don't care if it's out of the bullpen. It would sure be great to 
get out there one more time.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
