<HEADLINE> Ovitz Pledges $25M for NFL Team </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	LOS ANGELES (AP) -- Hollywood dealmaker Michael Ovitz pledged $25  
million to demonstrate his interest in bringing an NFL expansion 
team to Los Angeles. 
</P>
<P>
	Ovitz and partners Ron Burkle and Tom Cruise will forfeit the  
money if they are selected to own the expansion franchise, but fail 
to hold up their end of an agreement with the NFL. 
</P>
<P>
	League officials originally suggested a down payment of $100  
million. But they lowered their request after meeting with Ovitz 
and said they were impressed with the group's commitment. 
</P>
<P>
	``You have to respect their resolve and responsiveness in the  
past few days,'' said Roger Goodell, the NFL's vice president of 
football operations. ``We will just have to see now how things play 
themselves out.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Burkle cut short a vacation to meet with FBI agents Friday as  
part of the NFL's background check in preparing to select an owner 
for the league's 32nd team at Tuesday and Wednesday's meetings in 
Atlanta. The league has finished its investigation of Ovitz's 
background. 
</P>
<P>
	Burkle, a self-made billionaire who owns supermarkets, is one of  
several backers Ovitz brought together for the deal. Another is 
Cruise, an actor. The group holds an option on a 97-acre parcel of 
land adjacent to Hollywood Park racetrack as a possible location 
for a new stadium. The track is located southwest of downtown Los 
Angeles. 
</P>
<P>
	The group's main opposition is Bob McNair of Houston, who said  
he would up his franchise bid, expected to be more than $625 
million, in response to Ovitz's offer. 
</P>
<P>
	Ovitz's bid is not expected to be much more than the $540  
million that the city of Cleveland paid for an expansion team. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
