<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-02 00:40:04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> McHale, Thompson Head to Hoops Hall </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	SPRINGFIELD, Mass. (AP) -- As part of a frontcourt that included  
Larry Bird and Robert Parish, Kevin McHale helped shape the 1980s 
as an era of greatness for the Boston Celtics. 
</P>
<P>
	They played with size, smarts and championship intensity,  
winning titles in 1981, 1984 and 1986. 
</P>
<P>
	At his induction Friday night into the Basketball Hall of Fame,  
McHale tipped his hat to his teammates on those championship teams. 
</P>
<P>
	``It was so effortless when you play the game and you play the  
game properly,'' McHale said. ``Playing with those guys was never 
an effort.'' 
</P>
<P>
	McHale, who as a player drove himself to edge, shared honors  
with John Thompson, a coach who pushed others to the limit, and 
sometimes beyond. 
</P>
<P>
	``He always thinks about what he says,'' Hall of Fame coach  
Clarence Gaines said of Thompson, the Georgetown coach. ``Then he 
goes ahead and says it anyway.'' 
</P>
<P>
	This year's other inductees were former NBA star Wayne Embry,  
women's college coach Billie Moore and the late NBA pioneer and 
owner Fred Zollner. 
</P>
<P>
	McHale arrived in 1980 from Minnesota as a gangly, 6-foot-10  
sixth man. He transformed himself into one of the most feared 
attackers in the game with his jump hook, fadeaway jumper and agile 
moves. He shot 55 percent from the field in 13 seasons. 
</P>
<P>
	``He was one of the best low-post scorers in the NBA I've ever  
seen. There were times he was unstoppable,'' Bird said. 
</P>
<P>
	``I was always a lot more concerned with how good I could be,''  
said McHale, who used to spend 10-15 minutes after each game going 
over his performance. ``I was always self-analyzing.'' 
</P>
<P>
	McHale also borrowed inspiration and ideas from Bird and others  
on the team. 
</P>
<P>
	``Larry helped everyone improve their games,'' McHale said. ``As  
you saw him do things, you thought, maybe I'm going to do that.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Like Bird, McHale was ready to play despite pain. In the 1987  
playoffs against the Los Angeles Lakers, McHale played despite a 
foot so badly battered he sometimes needed to lean on furniture to 
stand. 
</P>
<P>
	Another habitue of postseason play, Thompson was the backup  
center for Bill Russell on the Celtics championship teams of 1965 
and 1966. Later, with the hulking Thompson draping a towel over his 
shoulder, his 27 Georgetown teams made 24 postseason appearances. 
They went to three NCAA tournament Final Fours and captured the 
national championship in 1984, the first time a black coach won the 
national basketball title. 
</P>
<P>
	During his induction, Thompson again had a towel draped over his  
shoulder. As he got up on stage, he wept and waved his fist. 
</P>
<P>
	``This is not my image,'' he said. ``But who the hell cares  
about image today?'' He wiped the tears away from his eyes with the 
towel. 
</P>
<P>
	Thompson's unyielding standards for basketball and academics  
challenged and sometimes frustrated his players. His demands for 
greater minority access in sports gave him more than a few 
detractors. 
</P>
<P>
	He endured racial taunts when he first fielded a predominantly  
black team at Georgetown. He later boycotted two games in 1989 to 
protest NCAA Proposition 42, saying its financial limits hurt 
minority athletes. 
</P>
<P>
	He thinks such views hurt his two earlier nominations to the  
Hall of Fame. 
</P>
<P>
	``Somebody asked me what I think I'll be remembered most for,''  
he said Friday before the induction ceremony. ``I said, `The things 
that kept me out of the Hall of Fame.''' 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
