<DOCNO> APW19991002.0156 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-02 11:40:25 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> racing </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Rabbit Discovery Spurs Research </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	BOSTON (AP) -- Dr. Judah Folkman remembers well the moment the  
idea that became his life work first dawned on him. 
</P>
<P>
	It was 1961. Folkman was a physician draftee at the Navy  
hospital in Bethesda, Md. His duties included experiments on 
rabbits and mice. 
</P>
<P>
	Thyroid glands were kept alive outside the rabbits' bodies. One  
day, Folkman and his lab mate wondered: Would tissue grow in them? 
So they tried a small experiment, implanting bits of cancer into 
the glands. It turned out the cancers would grow, but not very 
well. 
</P>
<P>
	``They never got beyond the size of a pinhead,'' Folkman  
recalls. ``They all stopped at the same size. We thought they had 
died. But when we moved them back to a mouse, they grew huge and 
killed the mouse. It was one of those 'aha!' moments you don't 
forget.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Now the question was why. His colleague noticed that the mouse  
tumor was full of blood vessels. But there were none in the tiny 
cancerous growth in the thyroid. The thyroid tissue was just not 
healthy enough to respond to the cancer's call for new blood 
vessels. 
</P>
<P>
	``But we did not know that,'' he says. ``For the first time, we  
were looking at tumor growth that was halted, and the only thing we 
could see was no blood vessels.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Folkman put this exploration aside to do his residency training.  
Then, in the mid-1960s, he began working on a paper 
</P>
<P>
	to lay out his theory about the importance of new blood vessels  
to cancer. After several rejections, it was published in the New 
England Journal of Medicine in 1971. 
</P>
<P>
	``At the time, nobody believe that, that I knew of,'' he says.  
Folkman went to work trying to prove this at Harvard-affiliated 
Children's Hospital in Boston, where he was a surgeon. 
</P>
<P>
	The big breakthrough came in 1983, when his team discovered  
basic fibroblastic growth factor, the first natural substance shown 
to trigger blood vessel growth. ``After that, I would say that 
overnight, my critics were converted to competitors,'' Folkman 
says. 
</P>
<P>
	Several other teams began researching the basic machinery of  
blood vessel growth. However, the field became especially crowded 
about five years ago, when drug companies started to research 
chemicals that might stop the process as possible cancer 
treatments. 
</P>
<P>
	In the mid-1980s, about 40 or 50 scientific papers on the  
subject were published annually. During the past 12 months, Folkman 
counted almost 900. 
</P>
<P>
	Even though he is credited with founding and nurturing the field  
of angiogenesis research, Folkman is meticulous about crediting 
others outside his lab who have made key discoveries. Among 
colleagues, Folkman often seems to be mentioned as much for his 
approachable, down-to-earth manner as he is for his science. 
</P>
<P>
	``He is a wonderful man, and there are very few people I can say  
that about,'' says Dr. Dennis Lund, chief of pediatric surgery at 
the University of Wisconsin, who worked in Folkman's lab for two 
years. ``He is exactly what he appears to be -- very 
straightforward, very honest, very low-key and very willing to give 
credit where credit is due, which is a rare thing among 
scientists.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
