<DOCNO> APW19991002.0166 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-02 17:50:13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Mormon Head Opposes Gay Marriage </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	SALT LAKE CITY (AP) -- Gay marriage is morally wrong and Mormons  
should feel compelled to oppose it, church President Gordon B. 
Hinckley told the faith Saturday. 
</P>
<P>
	``Some portray legalization of so-called same-sex marriage as a  
civil right,'' Hinckley said at the faith's 169th Annual General 
Conference. ``This issue has nothing to do with civil rights. For 
men to marry men, or women to marry women, is a moral wrong.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Hinckley said the church's support of California's Knight  
Initiative, which would only allow marriages between men and women, 
is an attempt to safeguard God-sanctioned marriage -- and the moral 
fiber of society -- from forces trying to undermine it. 
</P>
<P>
	Even before Hinckley addressed the subject, local gay-rights  
groups announced plans to protest outside Temple Square during the 
second day of the conference Sunday. 
</P>
<P>
	Earlier this year, leaders of The Church of Jesus Christ of  
Latter-day Saints sent a letter to branches in California asking 
them to urge their 740,000 members ``to do all you can by donating 
your means and time to assure a successful vote'' on the March 2000 
measure. 
</P>
<P>
	The church conducted similar efforts in Alaska and Hawaii last  
year, and members raised $1.1 million for the successful campaigns 
to block same-sex marriages in those states. 
</P>
<P>
	Hinckley made it clear to the conference's priesthood session  
Saturday night that the money going to California has come from 
individual members; gay-rights groups have threatened to fight the 
faith's tax-exempt status if church institutions or foundations get 
involved. 
</P>
<P>
	Earlier in the day, Hinckley celebrated the growth of the  
church, announcing that it will nearly double its number of temples 
by the end of next year. 
</P>
<P>
	Ground will be broken in Nauvoo later this month, Hinckley said,  
and seven other temples will be dedicated before the end of the 
year, bringing the total to 68. 
</P>
<P>
	Temples, where marriages and other ordinances considered sacred  
to Mormons are performed by worthy members, are different from the 
12,000 chapels used for weekly worship. As many as 42 more could be 
complete by 2001. 
</P>
<P>
	Under Hinckley's guidance, the church has also constructed a new  
21,000-seat assembly hall in downtown Salt Lake City, which leaders 
decided Friday will be named the Conference Center. It is set to 
open by April to host the next conference, which has been held in 
the smaller Tabernacle for more than a century. 
</P>
<P>
	But not all of the church's growth involves new edifices,  
Hinckley said. It has also expanded its genealogical work, much of 
it via computer. 
</P>
<P>
	In May, the church opened its new genealogical Web site, which  
was so inundated, IBM had to shut it down for six hours. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's interesting to think we've all reduced ourselves to  
dot-coms,'' the 89-year-old church president joked in the afternoon 
session. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19991002.0167 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-02 12:40:19 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> political </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Health Care Union Endorses Gore </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- An edgier, more combative Al Gore -- who cast  
Democratic rival Bill Bradley as disloyal to the party -- won 
endorsement Saturday from an important health care workers' union. 
</P>
<P>
	``I respect Bill Bradley. I'm not downgrading him. But I've been  
fighting for working families for almost a quarter-century now as a 
public servant,'' the vice president said. 
</P>
<P>
	Apparently referring to Bradley's retirement from the Senate in  
1996, and his brief talks around that time with independents 
pushing to build a third party, Gore continued: 
</P>
<P>
	``I've never been tempted to leave the Democratic Party. I've  
never been tempted to turn my back on the Democratic party. I've 
never been tempted to run as an Independent and divide the 
progressive coalition.'' 
</P>
<P>
	In turn, Bradley had argued to union members they should endorse  
him because Gore cannot win without the independent and Republican 
support that Bradley appears to enjoy. 
</P>
<P>
	``The objective of nominating somebody is to win in the fall,''  
Bradley said. 
</P>
<P>
	AFL-CIO officials were watching the straw vote of Local 250 of  
the Service Employees International Union, the nation's 
second-largest health workers union with 46,000 members in Northern 
California, for signs of Gore's strength going into next week's 
crucial AFL-CIO convention. 
</P>
<P>
	Though Gore was the clear winner, taking 55 percent to Bradley's  
38 percent of the vote by some 500 elected leaders in Local 250, 
union president Sal Rosselli credited Bradley with surprising 
strength. 
</P>
<P>
	``It was closer than I imagined. Here in California, our members  
don't know Bill Bradley,'' Rosselli said. 
</P>
<P>
	Both Bradley, the former senator from New Jersey, and Gore made  
presentations to the group on Friday. Bradley's was pre-recorded 
while he was in California on Thursday. Gore spoke via satellite 
link. 
</P>
<P>
	``Their positions were comparable,'' Rosselli said. ``I would  
guess that Gore got the majority simply because he's the vice 
president and he's better well-known.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Also, Rosselli said, Gore's ``live interaction'' was perhaps  
more exciting than Bradley's taped presentation. 
</P>
<P>
	Thanks to the Bradley campaign's stealthy buildup of credibility  
among union leaders and in broader public opinion, the vice 
president, once considered a shoo-in for the Democratic 
presidential nomination, has been stymied in his bid for an early 
nod from the labor federation. 
</P>
<P>
	Last week, Gore turned his campaign inside out, declared himself  
the underdog and promised to aggressively beat back Bradley's 
insurgency. 
</P>
<P>
	In his remarks to Local 250, Gore enunciated points against  
Bradley's record that, previously, his aides would only quietly 
identify for reporters ``on background,'' including Bradley's vote 
for President Reagan's 1981 budget cuts to Medicaid, welfare, food 
stamps and school lunches. 
</P>
<P>
	``I stood up to the Reagan budget cuts in 1981 you know they  
hurt working families quite a bit, they hurt health care workers 
quite a bit -- I stood up to them,'' Gore said. 
</P>
<P>
	Bradley, a former New York Knick and nine-year shop steward for  
the NBA players' association, won huge favor by proposing that 
employers who illegally fire workers for organizing unions be 
forced to pay triple back-pay plus punitive damages. 
</P>
<P>
	Gore promised that, as president, he would guarantee to veto any  
``anti-union or anti-worker'' legislation. 
</P>
<P>
	Asked by a union member why she should pick him over Gore,  
Bradley cited their different histories and approaches. 
</P>
<P>
	``I had a life before I got into politics,'' Bradley said.  
</P>
<P>
	``I've gone to work many years in my life and never thought of  
the federal government and I think the vice president has a life 
that's been primarily based in Washington and I think that gives us 
a different idea of who the American people are and what we can 
do.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Using their rival health reform plans as an example, Bradley  
said his aims to cover 95 percent of the nation's uninsured while 
Gore's mostly covers just children. 
</P>
<P>
	``He's incremental around the edges, helping here and there,''  
Bradley said. 
</P>
<P>
	Gore countered that his own approach ``is realistic and  
achievable and can be passed into law.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
