<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Alleged Child Abductor Held in N.Y. </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- A man who allegedly told his wife he was taking  
their three children to an amusement park and then sent them to 
Syria was deemed a flight risk and a threat to the community by a 
judge who ordered him held without bail. 
</P>
<P>
	Viktor Petrov was charged Friday in a complaint under the  
International Parental Kidnapping Act of 1993. 
</P>
<P>
	The children, ages 11, 6 and 5, were returned from Syria late  
Tuesday after a trip that began when they were flown to Turkey on 
June 26, according to the FBI complaint. 
</P>
<P>
	Family Court of Westchester County ordered Petrov jail Aug. 19  
when he refused to return the children to the United States. The 
federal charges were brought just as he was about to be released 
because the children had been returned. 
</P>
<P>
	Dr. Petya Petrov, the children's mother, came home June 26 and  
found a telephone message from her husband saying he had taken the 
children on a two-day trip to a New Jersey amusement park, 
according to the complaint. 
</P>
<P>
	Two days later, Petrov left a message saying he had brought the  
children to Turkey to be turned over to his parents in his native 
Syria with instructions not to allow them to talk to their mother, 
the complaint said. 
</P>
<P>
	Petrov later told the mother she would never see her children  
unless she agreed to let him manage all of her income except $5 per 
day. He also insisted that she find him a job as a medical 
resident, and that she not make long distance phone calls, use the 
Internet or meet friends. 
</P>
<P>
	In an interview after the return of the children, Mrs. Petrov  
described their return as ``the happiest thing.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Jessica, 6, said she was glad to be home instead of in Syria.  
</P>
<P>
	``I like it here more than there because I have my mommy,'' she  
said. 
</P>
<P>
	Paul Davison, a lawyer for Petrov, did not return a telephone  
message for comment Friday. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
