<DOCNO> APW19991002.0178 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-02 19:29:22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> international </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE>  Japan Lifts Nuclear Plant Advisory </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	TOKAIMURA, Japan -- Life began returning to normal Sunday for  
townspeople living next to the site of Japan's worst nuclear 
disaster, with most spending the night at home after the government 
lifted an evacuation order. 
</P>
<P>
	The streets were quiet early Sunday, with a few couples taking  
morning strolls through the center of this mostly farming community 
under partly cloudy skies and occasional sprinkles of rain. 
</P>
<P>
	Late Saturday, more than two days after the accident sent three  
workers to the hospital, the government lifted an evacuation order 
for the more than 160 residents who had been holed up in a 
community center. 
</P>
<P>
	Many in Tokaimura, a town of 33,000 about 70 miles northeast of  
Tokyo, were still not convinced that it was safe to go home. 
</P>
<P>
	Their fears were far from put to rest as more unsettling details  
of the accident emerged, highlighting the shoddy safety precautions 
at the plant and its astonishingly primitive methods. 
</P>
<P>
	Instead of relying on the high-tech equipment expected at a  
nuclear facility, the workers were using their hands to pour the 
potentially deadly material into a bucket-like container, said 
officials of JCO Co., the private company that runs the plant. 
</P>
<P>
	They mistakenly put in too much uranium, setting off an  
uncontrolled atomic reaction that continued for hours, sending 
radioactive particles into the air. 
</P>
<P>
	The government said 49 people were exposed to the radiation,  
although none other than the three workers required 
hospitalization. One of the three, Hisashi Ouchi, was transferred 
to the University of Tokyo Hospital on Saturday to receive a blood 
transfusion. Ouchi had been exposed to about 17,000 times what is 
normal for annual exposure, Kyodo News said. 
</P>
<P>
	JCO had been ignoring the procedures set by Japanese law for the  
last four years, and was using its own manual to speed up the 
processing, the national Asahi newspaper reported in its Sunday 
editions, citing company official Hiroyuki Ogawa. 
</P>
<P>
	Japanese media reports also said that the workers had never  
received proper training. 
</P>
<P>
	``This is unforgivable. That's all I have to say,'' Masaru  
Hashimoto, the governor of Ibaraki prefecture, or state, told 
reporters. ``I'm outraged, and it's an insult.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Prime Minister Keizo Obuchi said he was astonished by what had  
been happening at the plant. 
</P>
<P>
	``The workers had used their hands and a stainless steel bucket  
or something,'' Kyodo reported Obuchi as saying. ``This is 
inconceivable.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Earlier Saturday, when JCO President Hiroharu Kitani visited the  
evacuation center, he was showered with shouts of anger. 
</P>
<P>
	The suit-clad Kitani got down on his knees on the wooden floor  
in front of the villagers and the media, and bowed deeply in 
apology. All he got were more shouts that an apology just wasn't 
enough. 
</P>
<P>
	Police have begun an investigation into the company for possible  
negligence. 
</P>
<P>
	``This accident contradicts what Japan is renowned for and its  
standing as a leader in technological development,'' top government 
spokesman Hiromu Nonaka said in a news conference. 
</P>
<P>
	The government was, however, quick to distance itself from the  
cause of the accident and push blame onto the company as well as on 
human error. 
</P>
<P>
	Tokyo has said that Japan's overall nuclear power policies stand  
unchanged despite the Tokaimura accident. Japan has few natural 
resources, and it relies on atomic energy for about a third of its 
electricity. 
</P>
<P>
	Still, the accident has shattered the myth of Japan's supersafe  
nuclear technology, and opposition is likely to grow, even in a 
harmony-oriented nation where loud, aggressive protests tend to be 
rare. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
