<BODY>
<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Man Arrested in University Bombing </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	TALLAHASSEE, Fla. (AP) -- A white man who reportedly admitted  
making a phone call tinged with racial slurs and profanity after 
two bombings at a black college has denied making either of the 
explosives. 
</P>
<P>
	Lawrence M. Lombardi, 41, an unemployed, married father of two,  
was arrested Friday and held without bail on two counts of making 
bombs. He could face up to 20 years in prison if convicted. 
</P>
<P>
	The first bomb exploded Aug. 31 in the restroom of an  
administration building at Florida A&AMP;M University. The second went 
off Sept. 22, damaging a restroom surrounded by classrooms and 
offices. 
</P>
<P>
	FBI officials said Lombardi admitted making a telephone call to  
a Tallahassee TV station after the second bomb, and warned, ``this 
is just the beginning, brother.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``I'm telling you, these ... n------ ... I've had enough of  
this,'' the caller said. ``They got no business having a college 
when there ain't nobody there smart enough to ... get a degree.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Lombardi's attorney, R. Tim Jansen, said, ``He is absolutely  
innocent.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Authorities were confident they had their man.  
</P>
<P>
	``FAMU today does not face the threat that it did yesterday,''  
said U.S. Attorney Michael Patterson, when Lombardi's arrest was 
announced. 
</P>
<P>
	No one was injured in either blast, but the explosions spread  
fear across the 12,000-student campus. Dozens of police officers 
searched every campus building each morning, and everyone had to 
show ID to enter. Surveillance cameras were installed at state 
expense. 
</P>
<P>
	Some of that security will remain intact, campus authorities  
said. The school has a big football game tonight -- and hundreds of 
parents are on campus for parents' weekend. 
</P>
<P>
	``It looks like our nightmare may be over,'' FAMU President  
Frederick S. Humphries told students at a rally Friday. 
</P>
<P>
	Investigators said they matched bomb fragments with an uncommon  
type of heavy-duty PVC pipe that Lombardi bought at a Lowe's home 
improvement store the day before the first explosion. 
</P>
<P>
	Investigators said three former co-workers identified Lombardi  
from a store surveillance tape and recognized his voice on a 
recording of the threatening phone calls. 
</P>
<P>
	One former co-worker told investigators Lombardi had talked  
about finding bomb-making instructions on the Internet, the FBI 
said. 
</P>
<P>
	Lombardi worked for a vending company and his route had included  
machines at the two buildings where the bombs exploded, the FBI 
said. An employee told investigators that Lombardi had been issued 
a university ID card and that he did not surrender the card when he 
left the company in July. 
</P>
<P>
	``The vending company employee described Lombardi as having no  
personality and as an individual who did not like blacks and has 
used the `N' word,'' the FBI wrote in its affidavit. 
</P>
<P>
	Jansen said that was not true. ``They did not find any  
identification card at his house. He did not have one at the time 
of this event,'' he said. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
