<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Ala. Governor Explores Ticket Scam </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	MONTGOMERY, Ala. (AP) -- A traffic ticket-fixing scandal that  
forced the head of Alabama's state troopers to quit widened 
Saturday with Gov. Don Siegelman suspending three top aides and 
ordering an investigation. 
</P>
<P>
	``Members of the governor's staff will be asked point blank:  
Have you engaged in this activity and what were the 
circumstances?'' the governor said. 
</P>
<P>
	Siegelman said he expects every part of state government to  
participate in the investigation. 
</P>
<P>
	The Associated Press reviewed dozens of traffic tickets and  
payments of fines over two years and interviewed drivers who said 
their fines disappeared after they asked for help. It found 
requests for favors with traffic tickets linked to the governor's 
office, legislators, and acquaintances of former Public Safety 
Director Mike Sullivan. 
</P>
<P>
	Siegelman said Saturday he suspended three members of his staff  
-- executive secretary Nick Bailey, constituent services aide Josh 
Hayes and deputy policy director Sabra Barnett -- without pay 
pending the outcome of the review. 
</P>
<P>
	``They will pay and they will be punished,'' Siegelman said.  
</P>
<P>
	Fixing a traffic ticket or asking an official to do so is a  
misdemeanor under Alabama law. 
</P>
<P>
	On Friday, Siegelman said he had asked for and received  
Sullivan's resignation. 
</P>
<P>
	``If anyone, anywhere in this government is involved, they will  
have their ticket reinstated, they will pay the fines and they will 
be punished,'' the governor said. 
</P>
<P>
	Siegelman wouldn't say what punishment he would recommend for  
state government officials or employees who admit they have been 
involved in asking for favors with traffic tickets. 
</P>
<P>
	But he said any state employee who lies when questioned about  
ticket fixing would be fired. 
</P>
<P>
	Siegelman said Sullivan was ``very forthright, very  
forthcoming,'' when asked about the ticket fixing. 
</P>
<P>
	And he said Sullivan, who had worked at the Department of Public  
Safety since 1966, was resigning from state government, not just 
the director's post. 
</P>
<P>
	Siegelman named Jim Alexander, a 27-year-veteran of the  
Alcoholic Beverage Control Board, to be acting public safety 
director. Alexander has been chief of the governor's security 
detail. 
</P>
<P>
	Sullivan could not be reached for comment Saturday. He  
accompanied the University of Alabama football team to a game at 
Gainesville, Fla. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
