<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Clinton Pushes Patients' Rights / Presidential Speech  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	PALO ALTO, Calif. (AP) -- Praising broad protections written into  
California's new health care reform law, President Clinton urged 
voters Saturday to press Congress to ``do the same for every 
American'' as the House votes this week on a national patients' 
bill of rights. 
</P>
<P>
	In his weekly radio address, Clinton decried as ``simply  
unacceptable'' a provision in a Senate budget bill that effectively 
would take away the right to a timely appeal when a health plan 
denies coverage. He urged the House to reject the provision, which 
he said lawmakers are likely to do if their constituents speak up. 
</P>
<P>
	``I'm convinced the votes are there to pass this patients' bill  
of rights this week,'' Clinton said. ``But we need your help to 
make it clear to the Republican leaders that we can't tolerate any 
attempt to kill this bill with legislative poison pills. Together, 
let's tell them to give this legislation the straight up or down 
vote it deserves.'' 
</P>
<P>
	He also announced that later this month, the Department of  
Health and Human Services would propose rules extending protections 
for poor children under the Children's Health Insurance Program. 
</P>
<P>
	The changes would require health care providers participating in  
the program to ensure their patients' access to specialists, 
emergency room services and unbiased, timely appeals. 
</P>
<P>
	``The children are from some of our hardest-pressed working  
families,'' Clinton said. ``That's why I feel so strongly about 
giving them not only access to health care, but also the guarantee 
of quality care.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Clinton noted that California Gov. Gray Davis signed an  
ambitious health care reform package that extends ``strong and 
enforceable'' patients' rights to the state's 20 million residents, 
and that he extended such protections to 85 million Americans 
covered by federal health care plans. Still, he said, those steps 
are not enough. 
</P>
<P>
	``Now, it's time to do the same for every American,'' Clinton  
said. ``For all of the steps this administration and many states 
have taken to extend patient rights, we don't have the authority to 
protect every family unless Congress acts.'' 
</P>
<P>
	In Washington, Rep. J.C. Watts, chairman of the House Republican  
Conference, said the president is pushing for a quick vote on 
health care ``just to get it done. The Republicans want to get it 
done right, not fast.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Watts said it's more important to get out of the way  
appropriations bills to keep the government running before turning 
to health care. ``We too are committed to meaningful reforms,'' 
Watts said in a statement. ``But as the president says, first 
things first.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Clinton taped his remarks in the midst of a three-day West Coast  
fund-raising swing that was expected to bring in $2.5 million for 
Democratic candidates. He also planned to spend time with daughter 
Chelsea, who is beginning her junior year at Stanford University in 
Palo Alto, and do some preparation work for his presidential 
library in Little Rock, Ark. 
</P>
<P>
	The health legislation coming before the House is sponsored by  
Reps. Charlie Norwood, R-Ga., and John Dingell, D-Mich. Among other 
things, it provides the right to coverage for emergency room care 
and to see specialists and allows patients to refuse to change 
doctors during pregnancy or cancer treatment. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
