<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Controversial NYC Art Exhibit Opens </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- At last, the day of reckoning.  
</P>
<P>
	``Sensation,'' the controversial art exhibit that set New York  
on its ear even before it arrived, opened today at the Brooklyn 
Museum of Art amid cheers of First Amendment advocates and jeers of 
disgusted detractors. 
</P>
<P>
	Visitors lined up this morning to get into the museum, and about  
three dozen protesters showed up, too. They included protesters 
from the conservative Catholic League and from animal rights 
groups. One demonstrator protesting Mayor Rudolph Giuliani's 
efforts to stop the show was arrested. 
</P>
<P>
	``Mayor Giuliani should be arrested!'' yelled Robert Lederman, a 	
longtime critic of the mayor who was wearing a T-shirt that said 
</P>
<P>
     ``Giuliani  police state.'' He was arrested after police asked him 	
to move and he  
refused.	   Giuliani has called the show ``sick'' and has vowed to cut the 
city's $7 million annual contribution to the museum because of it. 
</P>
<P>
	The exhibit includes a painting of the Virgin Mary decorated  
with elephant dung; another of a serial child-killer whose face is 
formed with hundreds of children's handprints; and a bisected pig 
floating in formaldehyde. 
</P>
<P>
	As they waited in line, some visitors held mimeographed sheets  
that said: ``Hey Rudy, I'm a taxpayer too.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``I thought it was a very provocative, enduring show,'' said  
Mimi Zahka, who viewed the exhibit in advance, and was among about 
600 pro-museum demonstrators that formed a sometimes raucous crowd 
at a rally in Brooklyn on Friday night. 
</P>
<P>
	Katie Browning said the exhibit is ``a little bit shocking,''  
adding: ``Some of the pieces made me feel kind of queasy -- (but) 
not in a moral way.'' 
</P>
<P>
	But hundreds voiced support of the museum, both in public  
opinion polls and at the rally. Homemade signs there featured 
pointed statements about the mayor's purported lack of respect for 
the First Amendment. 
</P>
<P>
	Actress and activist Susan Sarandon saluted the large crowd,  
urging them: ``don't roll over on this one, this is really a big 
deal.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Giuliani was unmoved.  
</P>
<P>
	``I don't want any money coming out of my pocket to pay for this  
kind of sick demonstration of clear psychological problems,'' he 
said at City Hall. ``This should happen in a psychiatric hospital, 
not in a (city-funded) museum.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Both BMA and the city have filed lawsuits over the conflict. The  
museum filed suit in federal court, responding to Giuliani's threat 
to withhold the museum's funding, which is about one-third of the 
museum's annual budget. 
</P>
<P>
	The city later filed a lawsuit in state court in an effort to  
evict the museum from its building for violating its lease. 
</P>
<P>
	In the latest addendum to the legal battle, attorneys for the  
museum filed papers Friday accusing Giuliani of violating the 
museum's equal protection privileges under the Fourteenth 
Amendment. 
</P>
<P>
	The papers also said the mayor isn't entitled to withhold funds  
already authorized by the city Council, named the mayor as an 
individual defendant and sought punitive damages. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's an outrageous, frivolous act,'' said Michael Hess, the  
city's top lawyer. ``It's a mean-spirited, outrageous maneuver.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Several demonstrations were expected today and police were to be  
in the vicinity of the museum. 
</P>
<P>
	But travel to and from the museum might not be as easy as usual.  
Due to work on three subway lines, the three stops closest to the 
museum will not have service on the Manhattan-bound tracks. Shuttle 
buses from the museum are scheduled to run to the nearest station 
with regular service. 
</P>
<P>
	``These things are planned months in advance. It in no way has  
anything to do with the museum,'' said Melissa Farley, Transit 
Authority spokesperson. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
