<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Bavasi Resigns As Angels GM </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	ANAHEIM, Calif. (AP) -- Bill Bavasi asked his boss to lunch the  
other day with one thing in mind -- to resign as general manager of 
the Anaheim Angels. 
</P>
<P>
	Resignation accepted.  
</P>
<P>
	``At lunch, it became apparent that we had different ways and  
different philosophies about how we were going to win,'' team 
president Tony Tavares said. ``Obviously, this is not a happy day. 
</P>
<P>
	``The change we're looking to cause is to try and get a team  
that's competitive year in and year out. We look at getting there 
in different ways.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The decision was announced at an Edison Field news conference  
Friday night -- an hour before the Angels faced the AL West champion 
Texas Rangers; a day after Bavasi and Tavares got together, and 
four weeks after manager Terry Collins resigned. 
</P>
<P>
	``I'm very relieved,'' Bavasi said. ``The season has been a  
disappointment, this change is not. When you get to this point, you 
know you're at a point where you should take your leave, you feel 
good. You move on.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Bavasi, 41, will become a special assistant to Tavares, who said  
he planned to start a search for a new general manager immediately. 
</P>
<P>
	``I'll put a list together (today), get on the phone, ask for  
permission to talk to people,'' Tavares said, adding he hoped to 
have a new GM in place as soon as possible, and that one will be 
hired before a new manager is selected. 
</P>
<P>
	Bench coach Joe Maddon replaced Collins on an interim basis.  
Collins had signed a two-year contract extension in June. 
</P>
<P>
	Tavares said he didn't meet with Bavasi convinced he would be  
changing GMs, but admitted he was considering such a move. 
</P>
<P>
	The Angels have endured a miserable year, falling below .500 for  
good on April 18, and dropping out of contention in the AL West 
when they lost 11 straight games starting July 16 to fall 16 games 
out of first place. 
</P>
<P>
	They have a 68-92 record and trail the Rangers by 27 games with  
two remaining. 
</P>
<P>
	The Angels entered the season with high hopes after signing  
high-priced free agent Mo Vaughn to a $80 million, six-year 
contract last November and making a couple other offseason moves. 
</P>
<P>
	But several injuries before the season and early in the year  
contributed to their problems. 
</P>
<P>
	Bavasi was appointed to the GM job on Jan. 12, 1994. His father,  
Buzzie, was executive vice president-general manager of the Angels 
from 1977-84, and held the same position with the Brooklyn and Los 
Angeles Dodgers before that. 
</P>
<P>
	The younger Bavasi began his career with the Angels in 1980 as a  
minor league administrator. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's not a crime to have different styles of management, and  
we do,'' he said. ``I have a lot of faith in the players we put 
together here. 
</P>
<P>
	``I have had nothing but fun here. It was the best time you  
could possibly have in this game. This is the best job you could 
have. 
</P>
<P>
	Bavasi, the eighth general manager in club history, said he was  
uncertain as to his future. 
</P>
<P>
	``I will look in baseball, but mostly I will look outside of  
baseball,'' he said. ``I love living here. I'm wide-open to 
anything, including staying with the Angels. I don't have any 
preconceived notion. I'm just going to take it as it comes.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
