<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> $20M Needed To Keep Reds Together </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	MILWAUKEE (AP) -- On the day Marge Schott became a part of the  
Cincinnati Reds' past, general manager Jim Bowden issued a grave 
warning about his overachieving team's future. 
</P>
<P>
	Bowden, in Milwaukee on Friday to watch the Reds attempt to  
clinch a playoff berth in a three-game series with the Brewers, 
decried the gaps in baseball's economic structure while praising 
his current team's improbable run to the postseason. 
</P>
<P>
	Bowden thinks Cincinnati would need a $20 million payroll  
increase to keep the current team intact for next year. 
</P>
<P>
	``A small-market team just can't do what we've done,'' Bowden  
said. ``What we've done doesn't change the economic problems of 
baseball.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The Reds' payroll is $35 million and is the lowest among the  
nine teams still in contention for a postseason berth. That bottom 
line was even lower before Bowden acquired starting pitcher Juan 
Guzman at the trading deadline. 
</P>
<P>
	Bowden figures he would need at least a $55 million payroll to  
keep intact the solid nucleus he has built in the past 18 months 
through trades, the maturation of young players and good fortune. 
</P>
<P>
	The Reds would be able to generate a large amount of revenue  
with an extended postseason run, but even a trip to the World 
Series and the resulting increases in season-ticket sales for 2000 
might not bring in the funds Bowden said he will need. 
</P>
<P>
	``Anything's possible, but right now it's unlikely,'' he said.  
``It's almost impossible to keep all these elements together.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Bowden has ample experience in building teams and watching them  
be destroyed. His Cincinnati teams in 1994 and 1995 won NL Central 
Division championships, but the team's payroll edged up higher than 
the small-market Reds could afford, particularly when the 
free-spending Schott was forced to stop running the team. 
</P>
<P>
	So Bowden dismantled the Reds, jettisoning Ron Gant, David  
Wells, Benito Santiago, Tony Fernandez and Mike Jackson, among 
others. He tried to patch the lineup with fill-ins like Eric Davis. 
</P>
<P>
	But Cincinnati fell to .500 in 1996, and played 1997 and 1998 at  
18 games under .500, not finishing higher than third place in the 
division. So the Reds decided to tear down the team and rebuild, 
starting with the trade of starter John Smiley to Cleveland in July 
1997. 
</P>
<P>
	``We had to turn it over to young, talented kids, and we had to  
do it at the expense of our best players,'' Bowden said. 
</P>
<P>
	In the next 16 months, Jeff Brantley, Dave Burba, Jeff Shaw,  
Mike Remlinger, Paul Konerko and Bret Boone left as Bowden built a 
core of youngsters for the future. But even Bowden couldn't have 
predicted how quickly the team would come together -- and how much 
fun they would have doing it. 
</P>
<P>
	The addition of veterans Greg Vaughn, Denny Neagle and others  
have complemented and provided leadership to Cincinnati's 
youngsters such as Sean Casey and Pokey Reese. 
</P>
<P>
	``I've never seen a team that has such a good time,'' Bowden  
said. ``In '94, '95, we had trouble in the clubhouse. This year 
we've had nothing but peace.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Bowden had no intention of tracing that peace back to Schott's  
departure from involvement in the day-to-day operations of the 
club, though he did praise the limited partnership controlled by 
Carl Lindner and two others which formally took over the team 
Friday. 
</P>
<P>
	``This ownership group lets employees do their jobs,'' Bowden  
said. ``How much revenue we generate will determine what kind of 
team we can put on the field.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Though he's perennially a contender for other jobs in bigger  
markets, Bowden thinks his future is in Cincinnati. He and Reds 
managing executive John Allen appear to have smoothed over any 
differences they might have had, and the once-dismal farm system 
finally is showing promise. 
</P>
<P>
	Bowden, who was a candidate for GM jobs in Los Angeles and  
Baltimore during the last offseason, signed a three-year contract 
extension last October that will keep him in Cincinnati through 
2003, the same year the Reds' new ballpark is scheduled to open. 
</P>
<P>
	And though he doesn't expect his surprising team to return  
intact in 2000, he'll go back to work anyway. 
</P>
<P>
	``We'll try to figure out another way to win,'' Bowden said.  
</P>
</TEXT>
