<CATEGORY> political </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Bauer Beats Bush in Straw Poll </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	ST. PAUL, Minn. (AP) -- GOP presidential candidate Gary Bauer  
edged out front-runner George W. Bush in a Minnesota straw poll on 
Saturday. 
</P>
<P>
	Bauer, the only presidential candidate at the Minnesota  
Republican Convention, captured 294, or 36.6 percent, of the 803 
ballots cast in the nonbinding straw poll. Bush came in a close 
second with 291 votes, or 36.2 percent. 
</P>
<P>
	The vote has no bearing on the 33 delegates the party will send  
to the national GOP convention next year. 
</P>
<P>
	``Everyday, my candidacy gains momentum as American working  
families add their support for my unapologetic pro-family, pro-life 
Reagan-Republican message,'' Bauer said after hearing the results. 
</P>
<P>
	Before the votes were tallied, the conservative activist had  
told reporters he hoped to place in the top three. 
</P>
<P>
	Meanwhile, former Green Bay Packers defensive lineman Reggie  
White, keynote speaker at Saturday night's gala Christian Coalition 
dinner in Washington, threw his endorsement to Bauer. 
</P>
<P>
	``You have been unflinching in your defense of the family,  
consistent in your commitment to the sanctity of life and reliable 
when the battle has been toughest,'' White wrote Bauer in a letter 
released by Bauer's presidential campaign. 
</P>
<P>
	Bauer aides eagerly circulated the letter at Christian Coalition  
meetings Saturday, one day after coalition founder Pat Robertson 
dismissed Bauer's candidacy as ``a lost cause.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Bauer has raised about $5.4 million so far for his campaign.  
Bush has grabbed a whopping $56 million. 
</P>
<P>
	Tony Sutton, executive director of the state Republican Party,  
said Bauer's first-place finish in the straw poll should tell other 
candidates something. 
</P>
<P>
	``It means that if you show up, it helps your campaign,'' Sutton  
said. ``You can't underestimate the power of being in the room.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Sutton admitted that the straw poll of 803 people may not  
accurately represent how most Minnesota Republicans would vote, but 
added ``you win a straw poll, it can't help but help your 
candidacy.'' 
</P>
<P>
	No other candidates placed even close to Bauer and Bush. Forbes  
came in third with 68 votes, or 8.5 percent, and Alan Keyes had 40 
votes, or 5 percent. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
